## Preface

### Learning to Think

- Thorp's journey spans science, gambling, and securities markets
- Born during the **Great Depression** (1930s), family struggled financially
- Key resource: **learned how to think** despite lack of helpful connections
- Thinks using models — simplified versions of reality for prediction

### Thinking Methods

- **Model-based thinking**: like a street map or gas molecules as elastic balls
- Discovered simple devices (gears, levers, pulleys) follow basic rules
- Experimental approach: discover rules through testing, then predict new situations
- Inspired by **crystal radio** sets — voices from hundreds of miles away via invisible rules

> "The notion that things I couldn't even see followed rules I could discover just by thinking—and that I could use what I discovered to change the world—inspired me from an early age."

### Four Key Habits

- **Test claims yourself** rather than accepting conventional wisdom ("you can't beat the casinos")
- **Invent new experiments** to test theories, forming habit of testing pure thought profitably
- **Make realistic plans and persist** until success
- **Be consistently rational** across all aspects of life, not just specialized areas
- Value of **withholding judgment** until decision can be based on evidence

### The Book's Promise

- Unique perspective on gambling, investments, risk, money management, wealth-building
- Will help readers think differently about these domains

## Foreword (by Nassim Nicholas Taleb)

### Thorp's Significance

- **Ed Thorp** is the first modern mathematician to *successfully* use quantitative methods for risk-taking
- First mathematician to achieve financial success doing it
- Predecessor: **Girolamo Cardano** (16th-century polymath, wrote early version of *Beat the Dealer*)
  - Compulsive gambler, unsuccessful at it
  - *Liber de ludo aleae* ("Book on Games of Chance") influenced probability development
- **Abraham de Moivre**: frequented gambling joints, wrote *The doctrine of chances* (1718)
- Before Thorp, mathematician-gamblers had "their love of chance largely unrequited"

### Thorp's Method

- Cuts to the chase by identifying a clear **edge** (puts odds in his favor long-term)
- Edge must be obvious and uncomplicated
- Example: calculated roulette wheel momentum, estimated ~40% edge per bet
  - Built first wearable computer with **Claude Shannon** (father of information theory)
- The hard part: **capturing the edge** — converting it into dollars without betting too much or too little
- Refined by **John Kelly**: originator of the **Kelly Criterion** (formula for bet sizing)

### Simplicity vs. Academic Sophistication

- Academic work judged by colleagues often rewards complication, not substance
- Mountain giving birth to mouse (after huge labor) is not valued in academia
- Perception of sophistication matters more than real work substance
- Great mathematicians and physicists escape this burden
- As practitioner, *"you want the mountain to give birth to the simplest possible strategy"*

### Thorp's Blackjack Innovation

- Instead of complicated combinatorics and memory-challenging card counting
- **Simple rules**: Go to blackjack table, keep tally, start at zero
- Add one for strong cards, minus one for weak cards, nothing for others
- Bet incrementally up/down based on the running count
- "Mentally easy to just bet incrementally up and down"
- Anyone can apply it; even wearable computers at roulette had simple edge detection

### The Black-Scholes Connection

- Discovered what's now the **Black-Scholes option formula** before Black and Scholes
- Sign of economics public relations that formula doesn't bear his name
- Called it **Bachelier-Thorp** — derivation was "too simple—nobody at the time realized it could be potent"

### Money Management and Survival

- Having an edge and surviving are different things
- **Warren Buffet**: "In order to succeed you must first survive"
- Need to avoid ruin at all costs
- Dialectic between betting and P/L: start small (proportion of initial capital)
- Risk control (dosage) also controls discovery of the edge
- Trial and error process revises both risk appetite and odds assessment

### Academic Finance vs. Practitioner Approach

- **Academic finance** (Ole Peters, Murray Gell-Mann) showed avoiding ruin makes gambling strategy extremely different from academic literature
- Academics invented useless **utility theory** (tens of thousands of papers awaiting real reader)
- Invented idea that collective behavior of future prices can be identified in infinite detail today
- Would need to know entire joint probability distribution of all assets for entire future, plus exact utility function for all times
- **Kelly-Thorp method**: needs only ratio of expected profit to worst-case return, dynamically adjusted (*one gamble at a time*)

### Two Competing Methods

- **Economists' method**: tend to blow up routinely or get rich collecting fees, not from direct speculation
  - Example: **Long-Term Capital Management** blew up spectacularly in 1998
- **Information theorists' method** (pioneered by Thorp): practiced by traders and scientist-traders
  - Every surviving speculator uses this implicitly or explicitly
  - Examples: **Ray Dalio**, **Paul Tudor Jones**, **Renaissance Technologies**, **Goldman Sachs**
  - Those who don't will eventually go bust

### Inheritance Strategy

- If you inherit $82,000, a strategy exists to double it without ever going bankrupt
- Thanks to the second method

### Personal Wisdom from Thorp

- Many successful speculators get involved in large-scale structures after first break
- Multiple offices, morning meetings, coffee, corporate intrigues
- Not Ed Thorp — after separation from partners, didn't start new mega-fund
- Limited involvement in managing other people's money
- Less stressful to be independent
- Never independent when involved in large structure with powerful clients
- Hard to deal with probabilities while avoiding exposure to human moods
- Most stressful job Thorp ever had: running math department at UC Irvine
- Man is in control of his life — looked younger in 2016 than in 2005

## Chapter 1: Loving to Learn

### First Memories

- First memory: standing on outdoor landing, **Chicago**, December 1934 (age 2 years, 4 months)
- Landlady told parents: "No, we don't rent to people with children"
- Image from **Great Depression** depths stayed with him always
- Age 2.5: taken to **Dr. Dailey** — hadn't spoken a single word yet
- Doctor tested him (point to ball, pick up pencil) and reassured parents: "he'll talk when he's ready"

### Learning to Speak

- Campaign to get him to talk intensified around third birthday
- Mother **Charlotte** and friends **Estelle** took him to Montgomery Ward
- Sitting on bench near elevator, women got off
- He said clearly: "The man is going to buy something and the two women are going to the bathroom to do pee-pee"
- Charlotte and Estelle blushed deeply — he noticed but didn't understand why
- From then on spoke in complete sentences, delighting parents with surprising answers

### Father's Background

- **Oakley Glenn Thorp** born Iowa 1898, second of three children
- Brothers two years older and younger
- At age six, family broke up — father took him and brother to Washington state
- Mother and sister remained in Iowa
- 1915: grandfather died from flu (three years before **Great Flu Pandemic 1918-19** killed 20-40 million)
- Two boys lived with uncle until 1917
- Father at eighteen went to France to join **WWI** as part of American Expeditionary Force
- Fought in infantry trenches, rose from private to sergeant
- Awarded **Bronze Star**, **Silver Star**, and two **Purple Hearts**
- Fought at **Château-Thierry**, **Belleau Wood**, **Battles of the Marne**
- Young Thorp remembers sitting in father's lap examining shrapnel scars and mutilated fingers

### Father's Education

- After WWI discharge, enrolled at **Oklahoma A&M**
- Completed year and a half before leaving for lack of funds
- Hunger and respect for education endured, instilled in son
- Unspoken hope son would achieve more

### Learning Numbers

- Father introduced him to numbers as soon as he began talking
- Found it easy to count to hundred, then thousand
- Learned to count forever by adding one to any number
- Adults thought million was very big number
- One morning chose **Sears catalog** (size of big-city telephone book) to count to a million
- Pages filled with merchandise labeled A, B, C… (black letters in white circles)
- Started counting all circled letters, one per item, page after page
- Fell asleep around 32,576, resumed with "32,577…"

### Learning Through Testing

- Trait emerged: tendency not to accept anything told until checked for himself
- Age three: mother warned not to touch hot stove, would burn
- Brought finger close to feel warmth, then pressed stove with hand — burned, never again
- Warned fresh eggs would crack if squeezed "a little bit"
- Squeezed egg slowly until it cracked, practiced to see exactly how far he could go
- "From the beginning, I loved learning through experimentation and exploration"

### Learning to Read

- Father's next project: reading
- Started with **See Spot, See Spot Run**, **See Jane**
- Puzzled and disoriented for couple of days
- Then saw groups of letters stood for words they spoke
- Went through all simple beginner books, developed small vocabulary
- Saw printed words everywhere, realized if he could pronounce them he might know what they meant
- **Phonics** came naturally, learned to sound out words to say them aloud
- Reverse process: hear word, say the letters — **spelling**
- By age five, reading at level of ten-year-old

### New Brother and Independence

- Family dynamics changed with birth of brother
- Father employed during Great Depression, worked longer hours
- Mother fully occupied with new baby
- At six months old, baby caught pneumonia and nearly died
- Left Thorp much more on his own
- Responded by exploring endless worlds in books father gave him

### Early Reading

- Read **Gulliver's Travels**, **Treasure Island**, **Stanley and Livingstone in Africa**
- After eight-month arduous journey, **Stanley** found **Dr. Livingstone's** quarry
- Only European known in Central Africa
- Thorp thrilled by understatement: "Dr. Livingstone, I presume"
- Discussed **Victoria Falls** on **Zambezi River** with father (far surpassed Niagara Falls)
- Special favorite: *Gulliver's Travels* with tiny Lilliputians, giant Brobdingnagians, talking horses
- Finally mysterious **Laputa** — flying island in sky supported by magnetic forces
- Swift's historical allusions and social satire mostly escaped him despite father's explanations

### King Arthur and Values

- From **Malory's** story of **King Arthur** and **Knights of the Round Table**
- Learned about heroes and villains, romance, justice, retribution
- Admired heroes with extraordinary abilities and resourcefulness
- Introverted and thoughtful, may have been inspired to use mind to overcome intellectual obstacles
- Instead of body to defeat human opponents
- Books established lifelong values: fair play, level playing field, treating others as he wished to be treated

### Concentration and Mispronunciation

- Words and adventures largely in his head
- No one to discuss them with except tired father after work or on weekends
- Led to occasional unique pronunciation
- For years thought *misled* (*miss-LED*) was pronounced *MYE-zled*
- Would hesitate when seeing word in print, mentally correcting pronunciation

### Complete Absorption

- When reading or thinking, concentration so complete he lost awareness of surroundings
- Mother would call with no response
- Thinking he was willfully ignoring her, shout became yell
- She'd bring flushed face right up to him
- Only when she appeared in visual field did he snap back to here and now

### Books and Testing

- Though poor, parents valued books and managed to buy occasionally
- Father made challenging choices
- Between ages five and seven, carried around adult-looking books
- Strangers wondered if he actually knew what was in them
- One man put him to unexpected and potentially embarrassing test

### The Kesters and Summer Visits

- Parents became friends with **the Kesters** who lived on farm in **Crete, Illinois** (~45 miles from home)
- Invited out for two weeks every summer starting 1937 (age turning five)
- Special days most looked forward to each year
- For city boy from Chicago outskirts, sheer joy to watch water spiders, play hide-and-seek in tall corn
- Catch butterflies, display them on boards, wander fields among cottonwood trees and orchards
- Eldest Kester boy **Marvin** (twentysomething) would carry him around on shoulders
- Mother, women of household, Marvin's sister **Edna Mae**, mother, aunt May preserved fruits/vegetables
- Father built racks in basement for rubber-sealed mason jars of corn, peaches, apricots
- Rows of fruit jellies, jams, preserves in glasses with paraffin layer on top
- Cornucopia lasted well into next year

### The Dickens Test

- Father helped Marvin and **Old Man Kester** with farm work
- Sometimes Thorp tagged along
- One sunny forenoon during second summer (age six), father took him to pick up supplies
- Tall and thin with mop of curly brown hair, lightly tanned, pants too short, bare ankles in frayed tennis shoes
- Carrying **A Child's History of England** by **Charles Dickens**
- Stranger chatting with father took volume, written at tenth-grade level
- Thumbed through it, told father: "That kid can't read this book"
- Father replied proudly: "He's already read it. Ask him a question and you'll see"

### Proving His Reading

- Stranger with smirk: "Okay, kid, name all the kings and queens of England in order and tell me the years that they reigned"
- To father this seemed just another routine request
- Thorp recited: "Alfred the Great, began 871, ended 901, Edward the Elder, began 901, ended 925," and so on
- Finished list of fifty or so rulers ending with "Victoria, began in 1837 and it doesn't say when she ended"
- Man's smirk had long vanished, silently handed back book
- Father's eyes were shining
- Felt stranger was using him to put father down, realized he had stopped it
- Dad's happiness echoes with force that still seems undiminished

### Exceptional Memory

- Unusual retention of information pronounced until age nine or ten
- Faded into very good memory for what he's interested in
- Not especially remarkable for much else
- Still remembers facts from this time: phone number (**Lackawanna 1123**), address (**3627 North Oriole; 7600 W, 3600 N**) in Chicago
- Chicago's seven-digit population (**3,376,438**) cited in old green 1930 *Rand McNally Atlas and Gazetteer* still on bookshelf

### Learning Arithmetic

- Between ages three and five learned to add, subtract, multiply, divide numbers of any size
- Learned US version of prefixes: million, billion, trillion, up to decillion
- Found he could add columns of figures quickly by seeing or hearing them
- One day age five or six in neighborhood grocery store with mother
- Overheard owner calling out prices as he totaled customer's bill on adding machine
- When owner announced answer, Thorp said no and gave his number
- Owner laughed good-naturedly, added numbers again, found Thorp was right
- Rewarded him with ice-cream cone
- After that dropped by when he could and checked totals
- On rare occasions when they disagreed, usually correct and would get another cone

### Square and Cube Roots

- Father taught him to compute square root of a number
- Learned to do it with pencil and paper as well as in his head
- Then learned cube roots

### Mental Calculation Value

- Before writing and books, human knowledge memorized and transmitted by storytellers
- When skill wasn't necessary it declined
- With computers and calculators, ability to carry out mental calculations largely disappeared
- Yet person who knows just grammar school arithmetic can learn mental calculations comfortably and habitually
- Skill remains valuable, particularly for rapid approximate calculations
- For assessing quantitative statements continually encountered

### DJIA Example

- Listening to business news one morning
- Reporter: "The Dow Jones Industrial Average [DJIA] is down 9 points to 11,075 on fears of further interest rate rise"
- Mentally estimated typical (one standard deviation) DJIA change from previous close
- About one hour after open: about 0.6 percent or sixty-six points
- Probability of reported move of "at least" nine points: less than seventh
- Was about 90 percent, so market action very quiet
- Hardly indicative of fearful response to news
- Simple math separated hype from reality

### Warren Buffett Example

- Well-known mutual fund manager reported **Warren Buffett** compounded money after taxes at 23-24% annually since taking over **Berkshire Hathaway**
- Said "Those kind of numbers will not be achieved in the next ten years—he'd own the world"
- Quick mental estimate: $1 grows to little over $8 in ten years at 24%
- (Calculator gives $8.59)
- Since Berkshire had market cap of about $100 billion at the time
- This rate of growth would bring company to market value of roughly $859 billion
- Falls far short of guesstimate of $400 trillion for present market value of the world
- Notion of market value for whole world reminded him of sign on office door in Physics Department, UC Irvine
- Read: EARTH PEOPLE, THIS IS GOD. YOU HAVE THIRTY DAYS TO LEAVE. I HAVE A BUYER FOR THE PROPERTY

### Kindergarten at Dever Grammar School

- Just after turning five, started kindergarten at **Dever Grammar School** in northwest Chicago
- Immediately puzzled why everything they were asked to do was so easy

<!-- pp. 21-40 -->

## Early Childhood and Depression-Era Struggles

### Skipping First Grade

- Thorp was year and a half younger than classmates after parents decided
against holding him back for social/physical development
- Parents were right in retrospect — he was always smallest and youngest
but academically thrived
- Father's **Depression-era wages** ($25/week) meant private school was
impossible
- Father worked as security guard at **Harris Trust and Savings Bank**;
WWI medals may have helped him get the job

### The Depression's Impact

- Living on $25/week shaped lifelong frugality and hoarding tendencies
- Money was scarce — seeing **WPA workers** (Works Progress Administration,
FDR's New Deal jobs program) in the streets
- Early business lesson: sold Kool-Aid to WPA workers for penny each,
then snow shoveling competition drove down profits

> "Soon lots of the kids were out following my lead and the bonanza
> ended—an early lesson in how competition can drive down profits."

### Chess and Early Conflicts

- Father gave him chess set at age eight (folding board, Staunton-style
pieces)
- Neighbor "Smitty" Smittle beat him at first, then Thorp won consistently
- Smitty banned him from pool table after one-sided losses
- Thorp's response: merit and hard work should be rewarded, not punished

### War Comes to America

- Spring 1941: got measles, confined to shaded room (light feared to ruin
eyes)
- Used atlas left in room to study world maps, follow WWII battles daily
- Tracked battles with pencil on maps, used eraser when Allies reclaimed
territory
- Developed facility with maps and geography that served him for life
- Summer 1941: mother's brother **Uncle Edward** visited (chief engineer,
merchant marine, tall/dark/Spanish accent like Clark Gable)
- Learned to build model airplanes together with balsa wood and tissue
paper
- First planes failed (too much glue), then mastered technique

### Pearl Harbor (December 7, 1941)

- Family was decorating Christmas tree when radio announced attack
- **Franklin Delano Roosevelt** next morning: "a date which will live in
infamy"
- Thorp, age nine, understood the gravity while other children played
normally
- Mother's family trapped in Manila — grandfather worked as accountant for
**Rockefellers** in Philippines
- Grandmother and six siblings with families trapped when Japanese invaded
10 hours after Pearl Harbor
- Would not learn their varied fates for three years until liberation
- Followed **Battle of Bataan**, **Bataan Death March**, **Corregidor**
resistance in detail

### Father's War Experience

- Father had been stationed on **Corregidor** in Philippine constabulary
- Accurately predicted Corregidor would only fall when troops/weapons/
ammunition/food exhausted
- Became "twentieth-century version of the Alamo"
- Father left Oklahoma A&M to support himself, worked as lumberman in
Pacific Northwest
- Member of **International Workers of the World (IWW)**
- Fled IWW persecution, went to Manila where military credentials got him
into constabulary
- Met and married Thorp's mother there
- Moved to Chicago 1931 where Thorp and younger brother were born
- Family spent war in safety while mother's family endured Japanese prison
camps

### WWII's Transformation of America

- Great Depression ended by greatest government jobs program ever (WWII)
- Unemployment peaked at 25%, suddenly ended
- Women poured into factories building planes, tanks, ships
- "Arsenal of democracy" built ships faster than U-boats could sink them
- Gasoline, meat, butter, sugar, rubber rationed
- Blackouts at night, air raid wardens, barrage balloons over oil
refineries

### Move to California (1942)

- Family moved to **Lomita, California** (base of Palos Verdes Peninsula)
- Parents hoped to find war industry jobs
- Mother worked swing shift (4 PM-midnight) at **Douglas Aircraft**,
nicknamed "Josie the riveter"
- Father worked graveyard shift at **Todd Shipyards** in San Pedro as
security guard
- Parents rarely saw each other or children
- Boys (ages 10-11) raised themselves: made own breakfast, packed own
lunches

## School Years in California

### Orange Street School (Grade 6)

- Year and a half younger than classmates, missed first half of school
year
- Condemned to repeat sixth grade initially
- Parents protested; took supervised test one afternoon
- Completed 130 questions, then drew line through last 20 True-False to
leave early
- Test revealed he'd taken **California Test of Mental Maturity** (IQ
test)
- Scored highest the high school had ever seen — statistically expected
once in hundred years
- Advanced to seventh grade despite being behind scholastically
- Befriended "alpha dog" who protected him through sixth grade

> "Decades later I especially appreciated the IQ test: My bodyguard."

### Narbonne High School (1943-1949)

- Started grade seven fall 1943
- Extreme misfit where muscles mattered more than brains
- Gifted English teacher **Jack Chasson** became mentor and lifelong friend
- Chasson: age 27, UCLA background in English and psychology, idealistic
teacher
- Wanted students to succeed and work for social good
- Became Thorp's first great teacher

### Newspaper Route (Age 11)

- Signed up as paperboy for *Los Angeles Examiner* (fall 1943)
- Earned about $25/month (equivalent to $25 in 2014 dollars for eleven-
year-old)
- Had to collect payment from customers; shortfalls deducted from pay
- Saved earnings in war bonds through mother ($18.75 booklets exchanged
for $25 bonds maturing in several years)
- College began to seem possible as bonds accumulated
- Area supervisor gradually cut wages to keep more for himself
- Boys went on strike against unfair treatment

> "Would King Arthur's Knights of the Round Table tolerate this? No! We
> took action."

- Supervisor forced to deliver papers himself after strike
- Thorp moved to *Los Angeles Daily News* (afternoon paper, better sleep)
- Delivered during wartime blackouts in complete darkness on bicycle
- Fell asleep rolling down hill, crashed into mailbox, scattered papers
- Quarter mile from home: **Lomita Flight Strip** (military base)
- Sold extra papers to soldiers at base for extra income
- Invited to eat breakfast in mess with soldiers until security ended it

### Key Locations

- Base later became **Torrance Airport**, dedicated as **Zamperini Field**
for **Louis Zamperini**
- Zamperini grew up couple miles away, became Torrance High Olympic track
star
- Subject of **Laura Hillenbrand's** bestseller *Unbroken*
- Zamperini was B-24 bombardier just months before Thorp's family arrived

### Economics of Paper Routes

- ~100 stops per route, paid about $25/month ($300 in 2014 dollars)
- Subscriptions $1.25-$1.50/month
- Deadbeats, those who refused to pay, missed papers reduced actual take-
home significantly
- War ended August 14, 1945 — Thorp's thirteenth birthday

## Chapter 2: Science Is My Playground

### Discovery of Radio and Electronics

- Got first simple **crystal radio** set years earlier (rectifier of galena,
cat's whisker wire, tuning capacitor)
- "Then like magic: Through my earphones came voices from the air!"
- Invisible waves traveling through space — had to figure it out through
experiments and logic
- Electric shop teacher **Mr. Carver** ("Bunny") was universally liked,
plump man
- **Jack Chasson** told Carver about Thorp's electronics interest
- Introduced to world of **amateur radio** (ham radio)
- Network of do-it-yourselfers with transmitters/receivers talking
worldwide
- "In effect the first Internet"

### Amateur Radio License Exam

- Exam required: written questions on radio theory + **Morse code** test
- Morse code major obstacle — needed error-free 13 words/minute
- Bought used "tape machine" for $15 (almost three weeks' newspaper
income)
- Machine: stubby black box with two spindles, pale-yellow paper tapes
with holes for dots/dashes
- Hand-cranked, simple, low-tech, effective
- Connected to "audio oscillator" emitting piano middle C tone
- Mastered tapes at slow rate, then gradually increased speed
- Army WWII trainees provided benchmark (older, under wartime pressure)
- Thorp's method: learned 4x faster per hour than army trainees
- Brought code speed to 21 words/minute (margin of safety)

### Becoming Amateur Radio Operator W6VVM

- Joined **American Radio Relay League** for exam preparation guidance
- Saturday morning: took 20-mile bus ride to federal building in downtown
LA
- Age twelve in flannel shirt and worn jeans among ~50 adults
- Passed exam, became **amateur radio operator W6VVM**
- One of youngest amateurs ("hams") — age record at time was 11 years some
months
- ~200,000 amateurs in US, comparable worldwide
- Could talk to people anywhere on earth

### Family Reunification After War

- American troops liberated survivors of mother's family from Japanese
prison camp
- Grandmother, mother's youngest brother, two sisters and families came to
stay
- Aunt Nona and husband had been paraded in front of children by Japanese
- Grandfather died painfully of prostate cancer in camp week before
liberation
- Denied medicine and surgical facilities
- Uncle Sam (pre-med student) could only offer comfort to dying
grandfather
- Father built out attic with two bedrooms and stairway between graveyard
shifts
- Shared bedroom with brother James (Jimmy); other bedroom for Uncle Sam
- Ten extra residents brought difficulties beyond overcrowding and economic
burden

### Tuberculosis Exposure

- One aunt with husband and three-year-old contracted tuberculosis as
Japanese prisoners
- Kept separate set of tableware, severe penalties for mistakes
- Shared air still risked infection from coughs/sneezes
- Decades later: Thorp's lung X-rays showed small stable lesion, likely
from tuberculosis exposure

### Cousin Frank — The Sociopath

- Other aunt brought spouse and three children
- Husband: fascistic martinet who abused compliant wife
- Oldest boy became sociopath (in Thorp's view)
- Frank told Thorp's brother he wanted to kill Thorp
- Thorp kept squirt bottle of full-strength household ammonia as weapon
- Frank later went to war in Korea, enjoyed killing, reenlisted
- Years later seen with seven-year-old son ordered about in military
fashion
- Died 2012, obituary mentioned he became well-known martial arts
practitioner and teacher

### Determination and Tolerance

- Seeing what wars did to relatives (WWI and WWII impact)
- Determined to do better for self and hoped-for children
- Never blamed or discriminated against Japanese Americans despite
relatives' suffering
- Only learned of internment camps, land/homes expropriation, children
disappearing from classes later
- **Jack Chasson** educated close friends **Dick Clair** and **Jim Hart**
about injustice
- After war: student with IQ 71 returned, retested at 140 (extremely
gifted)
- Chasson saw language barrier, tutored him during lunch
- Scored 140, extremely gifted, in upper 1%, well above **Mensa** threshold

### Scientific Pursuits and Equipment

- Used paper-route money for electronic parts, ham radio equipment,
chemistry by mail, drugstore supplies
- Built cheap telescope from cardboard tubes
- November 1946 (high school sophomore): saw **Edmund Scientific Company**
ad for war-surplus weather balloons
- Fantasized about personal flying machine since building model airplanes
- Ideas: tiniest possible airplane, one-person helicopter, flying platform
- Plan: build scale models to prove feasibility, solve practical problems
- Balloons were beyond financial capability but not visualization

### Balloon Flight Experiment (Age 14)

- Ordered ten balloons (eight feet tall each) for $29.95 (like $360 today)
- Knew from self-taught chemistry: each eight-footer filled with hydrogen
would lift ~14 pounds
- Weighed 95 pounds; eight balloons (112 pounds lift) should carry him plus
harness/ballast
- Problem: couldn't afford hydrogen at reasonable price
- Solution: family stove powered by natural gas (methane + less than half
hydrogen's lifting power)
- If tests succeeded, could always buy more balloons
- Imagined being tethered to 16+ eight-foot balloons, slowly ascending,
looking out over Southern California
- Planned to carry sand bags as ballast, valve system for controlled
descent
- Saturday when family away: connected gas line to balloon, inflated to ~4
feet diameter
- Maximum size squeezable through kitchen door to get outside
- Sent balloon to ~1500 feet on strong kite string
- Nearby plane "buzzed" balloon
- ~45 minutes later plane returned, flew near balloon, then balloon
suddenly popped
- Plane appeared to have shot it down

### Balloon Experiments End

- Gave pause to fantasy of being tied to flock of balloons as target for
kids with BB guns
- Original balloon ad successful — still running 54 years later:
"PROFESSIONAL WEATHER BALLOONS"
- "Lawnchair Larry" (almost 40 years later) tied cluster of four-foot
helium balloons to chair, ascended several thousand feet

### Parachute Flares and Night Spectacle

- Father brought home wartime parachute flares from surplus lifeboats
- Metal canisters fired high into sky by special gun
- Blazing flare illuminated large area as it drifted down on parachute
- Attached homemade slow-burning fuse to flare
- Hung flare with fuse on giant balloon, went to quiet intersection near
house
- Lit fuse, sent gas-filled balloon up on several hundred feet of cord
- Loosely noosed cord around telephone pole; noose slid up pole as balloon
rose
- Backed off and waited
- Sky lit up with dazzling brilliance, crowd gathered, police cars
converged
- Few minutes later light went out, police/crowd dispersed
- Second slow-burning fuse severed cord, evidence leapt into sky

### Learning Through Experimentation

- "Pranks and experiments were part of learning science my way"
- Tested theory by doing experiments, many invented for fun
- Learning to work things out independently, not limited by teachers/
parents/curriculum
- "I relished the power of pure thought combined with the logic and
predictability of science"
- Loved visualizing idea, then making it happen

### Home Laboratory Setup

- Upstairs bedroom: two-meter wavelength amateur radio station with
rotating directional beam antenna
- Laboratory space in narrow laundry room attached to rear of garage
- Did many chemistry investigations, some went awry
- Hydrogen gas experiment: poured hydrochloric acid onto zinc in glass
flask with rubber stopper
- Hoped to produce so much hydrogen it would "wash" air out before
attempting ignition
- Otherwise — boom
- Brother burst in unable to stop hand with match, screamed "DOWN", ducked
- Apparatus blew apart
- Painted white "no trespassing" line across floor (5 feet wide, 10 feet
long)
- Stocked zone with shelves of chemicals and glassware
- Frequent fumes and explosions ensured voluntary compliance

### Explosives Experiments (Age 13)

- Seriously exploring explosives
- Found gunpowder recipe in old **Funk and Wagnalls encyclopedia**
- Ingredients: potassium nitrate (saltpeter), charcoal, sulfur
- Batch ignited accidentally while working on it
- Burned skin of entire left hand to gray-black brittle crust
- Father soaked hand in cold tea, wore tea-soaked bandage for week
- Overjoyed to see total recovery when bandage and crusted skin came off

### Homemade Rockets and Motor Cars

- Made large quantities of gunpowder for homemade rockets and model rocket
cars
- Cars: balsa-wood bodies, lightweight hobby shop wheels
- "Motor": **CO₂ cartridge** (carbon dioxide, like ones in drink
carbonators/air rifles now)
- Father brought them home as war surplus from shipyard
- Drilled out seal at cartridge end to rush of escaping gas
- Cold white powder of solid CO₂ collected as gas expanded and cooled
- Filled empty cartridge with homemade gunpowder, inserted fuse
- Motors sometimes exploded casting shrapnel — wore safety goggles, kept
away neighborhood kids
- When all worked: cars astonishingly fast, appeared/disappeared/
reappeared blocks away
- Built and tested bigger versions designed to explode — pipe bombs
- Used to blow craters in cliff faces at nearby undeveloped **Palos Verdes
Peninsula**

### Guncotton (Nitrocellulose)

- Next challenge: guncotton (nitrocellulose), basis for smokeless powder
- Encyclopedia recipe: slowly add one part cold concentrated sulfuric acid
to two parts cold concentrated nitric acid
- Whenever mixture becomes warm, chill everything before continuing
- Added ordinary surgical cotton, chilled again
- Let stew in refrigerator with DON'T TOUCH sign attached
- Family knew such signs meant serious business
- After 24 hours: removed cotton, rinsing and drying
- Verified it was no longer ordinary cotton by dissolving some in acetone
- Continued making guncotton in refrigerator "factory," began experiments
- Explodes but not easily, typically requires detonator
- Put small wad on sidewalk, whacked with sledgehammer: *whum-m-p*
- Sledgehammer leapt up and back over shoulder while hanging on
- Sidewalk sported palm-sized crater
- After few more craters: used guncotton in rockets and pipe bombs (more
predictable/effective than gunpowder)

### Nitroglycerin — The Big One

- Felt ready to try nitroglycerin
- Recipe/procedure followed guncotton with one change: substituted
ordinary glycerine for cotton
- Result: pale, almost colorless liquid floating on top (removed
carefully)
- Violent and treacherous explosive that killed many in past
- One quiet Saturday: bundled up, put on safety visor, moistened glass
tube lip with nitro
- "Using far less than a drop, surely a safe amount"
- Heated over gas flame and suddenly: *CRACK!*
- Duration much shorter, violently different from other slower-acting
explosives
- Tiny bits of glass embedded in hand and arm, blood seeping from myriad
holes
- Picked bits out with needle over next few days
- Put more nitro on sidewalk, used sledgehammer to blow another crater
- Nitroglycerin's dangerous instability worried him, discarded rest of
stockpile

### Access to Dangerous Chemicals

- Where did 14-year-old get such powerful dangerous chemicals?
- From local pharmacist who sold them privately at nice markup
- Parents worked long hours, were either seeing to needs of refugee
relatives or exhausted
- Children left to manage on own
- Didn't volunteer information about experiments
- If parents realized full extent, would have shut it down

### Chemistry Class (Eleventh Grade)

- By eleventh grade: had been doing experiments for couple years
- Read high school chemistry book cover to cover
- Fell asleep at night mentally reviewing material (habit proved effective
then and later)
- Teacher: **Mr. Stump**, short bespectacled man in fifties who loved
subject
- Had always longed to produce student good enough to be one of fifteen
winners in **Southern California American Chemical Society** high school
contest
- Three-hour spring examination
- Attracted ~200 top high school chemistry students from all over Southern
California
- After 20+ years at academically impoverished working-class school ranked
31st out of 32 in LA district, he'd given up hope

### Mr. Stump Spots Talent

- Saw thin younger student with dark hair who volunteered to answer every
question
- Heard about this kid from other teachers
- After first exam: other students scored 0-33 out of 100; Thorp scored 99
- Went to discuss chemistry contest
- Stump saved every old exam for 20 years, wanted to lend them for study
- Reluctant to give them all, pointed out huge odds against Thorp
- Taking exam as junior (age 15-16) vs. seniors (17-18)
- Skipped a grade, only five months to prepare
- School's facilities inferior, no peers to study with or push to higher
level
- None from school had ever been audacious enough to enter, none had placed
- "Why not wait a year?" suggested Stump
- But Thorp was determined

### Preparing for the Contest

- Stump agreed to lend ten tests (kept other ten to check preparedness
level)
- Worked through two college chemistry texts alongside high school book
- When concept unclear in one text, generally clarified in another
- With experimental background and previous reading, subject "sang to me"
- Every night: one hour on theory, then fell asleep mentally reviewing
periodic table, valences, allowable chemical reactions, Gay-Lussac's law,
Charles's law, Avogadro's number
- Continued experiments and pranks

### The Aniline Red Dye Prank

- Read about powerful dye called **aniline red**
- Turned water deep blood color in ratio of 6 million grams water per 1
gram dye
- Obtained 20 grams for experiments
- Homemade chemistry lab in laundry room behind garage opening to backyard
- Middle of yard: kidney-shaped goldfish pool (10 feet by 5 feet by 1 foot
deep)
- Little less than 1.5 cubic meters
- One gram dye would color 6 cubic meters deep red, so pinch (1/4 gram)
ought to do the job on pool
- Put in four times that much (whole gram), stirred vigorously
- Goldfish pool turned satisfying blood red
- Color so dense plants no longer visible except where breaking surface
- Only sign of fish: when stuck mouths up to feed

<!-- pp. 41-60 -->

### The Long Beach Plunge Prank

- Young Thorp executed an elaborate prank: dyeing the **Long Beach Plunge** pool red
- Pool measured 120 feet by 60 feet, average depth 5 feet (~1,000 cubic meters)
- Used 19 grams of **aniline red dye** sealed in waxed paper pouch with strings
- Recruited a pale, nerdy classmate as accomplice
- Successfully released dye, creating basketball-sized red cloud that expanded
- Pool evacuated in panic; staff eventually found waxed paper debris
- Local newspaper article: "Unknown Pranksters Dye Long Beach Plunge Red"
- 60 years later, son-in-law **Judge Richard Goul** heard story from retired judge who remembered the incident

### The Chemistry Exam Setback

- Studying for **American Chemical Society exam**, scoring 990+ out of 1,000 on practice tests
- Mr. Stump encouraged him to take advanced exam from previous year
- Exam required **slide rule proficiency** for calculations
- Brought only cheap 10-cent toy slide rule; discovered full-sized slide rules were **required**, not optional
- No credit given for showing correct method, only for numerical answers to specified precision
- Completed only 873 of 1,000 points worth of questions
- Scored **869 points** (top winner ~930); finished fourth place
- Second and third place were only a few points ahead
- Top winners came from elite LA high schools (Beverly Hills, Fairfax, Hollywood)
- Thorp's school (Narbonne) was a "nobody" working-class school
- Bought best slide rule he could afford afterward; lesson learned

> "I was sickened by the realization I would likely not place high enough to get the scholarship I needed."

- **Mr. Stump** drove him to awards dinner despite his shame
- Winners picked scholarships in order: top two chose Caltech and UC Berkeley
- Thorp didn't know enough to choose a backup school
- Learned he couldn't retake test the following year

### Intelligence Testing and Breaking Into School Records

- Became interested in measuring intelligence; took 20-mile bus ride to LA Public Library
- Found IQ tests with answer keys; took nine different tests over nine Saturdays
- Pleased with results; wanted to see earlier scores from sixth grade
- Decided to break into high school at night to access records
- Used flat L-shaped metal tool to open locked doors
- Rode bike over, hid it in bushes, nervously entered darkened school
- Found psychologist's office, searched through IQ test records by flashlight
- Verified suspicions, including that most talented girl had IQ of **148**

### High School Social Structure

- **Narbonne High School**: 800 students, grades 7-12
- Class divided into "ins" (socies) and "outs" (brown-baggers)
- **20% "socies"**: held offices, planned events, had cars at 16, wealthier families
- "Ins" had access to dating, beach parties, athletic events via cars
- Working-class Lomita/Harbor City meant "wealthier" = small business owners
- "Brown-baggers" ate lunch wherever, excluded from cafeteria social scene
- Thorp launched chess club and science club for fellow "outs"
- **Jack Chasson** found room for chess during lunch

> "I viewed everyone I met as my equal, due the same respect I wanted, unless their behavior showed me otherwise."

### The PE Grade Conflict and Tennis

- Got B in ninth-grade **physical education (PE)**; discovered PE grades counted for college
- Athletes in football/track got automatic A's, using up quota
- PE system favored athletes; Thorp was fast but physically a year younger
- At Chasson's urging, took tennis (no instruction, learned by playing)
- Made junior varsity, then varsity for junior and senior years
- Football player called tennis "a sissy sport"; Thorp challenged him to match
- Ran football player to exhaustion in 20 minutes

### Student Government Revolution

- Spring of junior year (1948): formed **Student Betterment Committee**
- Inspired by 1948 presidential campaign (Truman vs. Dewey and Wallace)
- Recruited dozen members including **Dick Clair** and **Jim Hart**
- Goal: make student government work for all students, not just "ins"
- Ran slate of candidates for every student body office
- Met at Japanese member's family lettuce farm to organize
- Night before election: hoisted banners "VOTE STUDENT BETTERMENT COMMITTEE" using **weather balloons** and telephone pole loop trick
- "Ins" had no time to counterpunch; attacked Thorp personally in speeches
- Lost student council bid narrowly, but swept **13 of 15 positions**
- **Dick Clair** elected student body president

### Summer Reading and Family Dissolution

- Summer 1948: read ~60 great novels on the beach
- Authors: **Thomas Wolfe, John Steinbeck, Theodore Dreiser, John Dos Passos, Upton Sinclair, Sinclair Lewis, Ernest Hemingway, F. Scott Fitzgerald, Dostoyevski, Stendhal**
- **Jack Chasson** provided list and loaned books from personal library
- Parents filed for divorce (three years after war ended)
- Household had been filled with conflict due to ten guests taking years to move out
- Father moved to Los Angeles; saw him only Sunday mornings during senior year
- Mother preparing to sell house when Thorp left for university
- Learned years later: mother had affair with family friend's husband starting before Pearl Harbor; father discovered it, leading to divorce

### The Physics Exam Triumph

- Learned of **Physics Teachers Association** all-Southern California physics test
- Physics teacher was athletics coach who "babysat the class and knew nothing"
- Taught himself physics; no old tests to practice on
- Experiments with electricity, mechanics, magnetism, electronics helped with theory
- Built **refracting telescope** with mail-order lenses from **Edmund Scientific**
- Discovered "Lover's Lookout" half mile away where teenagers parked at night
- Mounted **12-volt auto headlight** on telescope; illuminated parked cars
- Caught teenagers in "various states of entanglement"; they fled in panic
- Used trick only a couple times before stopping

> "Was I doomed again to fourth place? I asked myself, *What can I do about this?*"

- Physics exam day: knew ~860 of 1,000 points; two questions worth 140 points were unfamiliar material
- Used **dimensional analysis** to reason out formula in remaining time
- Made educated guess on second question
- Scored **931 points** (first place); second place 50-60 points behind
- Same elite LA schools dominated finalists; astonishment at winner from Narbonne
- Won first pick of scholarships: wavered between **Caltech** and **UC Berkeley**
- Caltech offered full tuition but needed extra $2,000/year for dorm and expenses
- Pasadena too expensive; couldn't afford Caltech
- **UC Berkeley scholarship**: $300/year tuition, covered separately by scholarship for WWII veterans' children
- Berkeley had low-cost **Student Cooperative Housing Association**: $35/month room and board plus four hours work/week
- Chose Berkeley, hoping for girls and social life

### Mr. Hodge and Early Electronics

- **Mr. Hodge**: retired electrical engineer with elaborate California property
- Property had Spanish-style stucco, goldfish pools, adjoined Thorp's back fence
- From tree house, spotted mysterious tower wrapped in green asphalt roofing
- Hodge invited him inside: 30-foot spiral staircase with radio components at each level
- Hodge let him choose one gift: **variable capacitor** (magnificently crafted, air-spaced)
- Essential part of radio receivers/transmitters; dial brought metal plates closer/farther
- Incorporated into homemade radio; Hodge fed his hunger with treasures every few weeks
- Speculated about future technological uses: **wearable electronic device** to wirelessly control objects
- Envisioned using brain's electrical currents picked up from scalp to send signals
- Never built gadget, but idea of wearable electronics stayed with him

### Westinghouse Science Talent Search

- **Mr. Hodge** bought subscription to **Science News-Letter** (now *Science News*)
- Told him about annual **Westinghouse Science Talent Search** (later Intel, then Regeneron)
- No one in high school had heard of contest; entered **Eighth Annual Search** in 1949
- 16,000+ high school students from across US competed
- Essay required; wrote scholarly piece on recent discoveries
- Essay title: **"Some Original Calculations"**
  - First calculation: approximate planet positions assuming circular orbits instead of Keplerian ellipses
  - Second calculation: find index of refraction of glass prism by moving it until it half reflected, half transmitted light
- Received telegram: "Congratulations, you are one of **forty finalists**"
- Five-day all-expenses-paid trip to Washington, DC with other two California finalists
- Met **Nobel Prize-winning physicist I. I. Rabi**; visited 60-inch cyclotron
- No magnetizable material allowed in cyclotron room (electromagnet would rip loose metal objects)
- Public exhibition: displayed homemade radio station with remote-controlled antenna
- Top ten finalists: cash awards $10,000 to $1,000
- Remaining 30 got $100 each
- All sought after by science departments of leading universities
- Greeted in **White House Oval Office** by **President Harry S. Truman**

> "I remember the feel of his hand as we shook: firm, compact, and with the sensation of a leather chair lightly dusted with talcum powder."

### High School Friendships and the Casino Seed

- Studied/experimented in physical sciences alone; taught himself
- Shared other interests with friends **Dick Clair** and **Jim Hart**
- Discussed school politics, national/world issues, elections, Cold War, rebuilding Western Europe, racial discrimination
- Read literature, pondered morality and ethics
- Jim was poet, writer, gifted cartoonist; Dick was writer and philosopher
- Stayed in touch for lifetime despite leading different lives
- Only game played was **chess**; no interest in cards or gambling at this point
- Briefly thought about analogy between **circling roulette ball and orbiting planet**
- At **Jack Chasson's** house after he returned from Las Vegas trip
- Chasson said no way to beat casinos; Thorp rashly said someday he would
- Chasson replied: "Oh, come on, Eddie"

> "But the idea lay dormant, waiting to come to life."

<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

## Roulette Physics and the Martingale Fallacy

### Betting Systems Don't Work
- Mathematics proved all betting systems must fail under general assumptions
- No method of varying bet sizes can overcome the casino's advantage
- **Martingale system** (doubling after losses) fails because required bet grows
too large—either you run out of money or casino won't allow it
- With infinite possible sequences of outcomes, impossible to verify any system
through trial and error alone

### Physical Prediction of Roulette
- Thorp argued roulette could be beaten despite mathematical proof to contrary
- His high school physics idea: friction gradually slows orbiting ball until
gravity pulls it down toward center
- Equations could forecast ball position during this process
- Ball crosses onto rotor spinning opposite direction—second equation for rotor
position
- Random irregularities (**noise**) limit prediction, but Thorp believed they
weren't enough to ruin it
- Didn't know **Henri Poincaré** had "proven" physical prediction impossible—his
proof only assumed modest randomness in final resting place

### PhD Progress and Career Crossroads
- Completed all coursework for physics PhD at UCLA, passed written exams
- Halfway through thesis on shell structure of atomic nuclei under **Professor
Steven Moskowski**
- Quantum mechanics required advanced math he hadn't studied as physics student
- Realized he could get a math PhD as quickly as physics PhD
- UCLA physics PhDs often took 10+ years to finish

### Meeting Vivian
- Graduate physics consumed him; drifted from friends
- **Vivian** sent Christmas card: "Don't be such a stranger"
- First date: art theater in Hollywood, saw **Jean Renoir's** *The River*—seemed
dreary
- Light meal afterward revealed their compatibility
- Both experienced enough dating to recognize how well suited they were
- Like **Jane Austen** books she loved—would have right person or no one

### Shared Vision for Life
- Both avid readers, enjoyed plays, movies, music
- Wanted children, agreed on educational philosophy: teach them to think
independently
- Looked forward to academic life with smart people, teaching, research, travel
- Not much money but enough
- More important: how they spent time and with whom
- Complementary differences: Vivian = literature, people, psychology, art, drama;
Thorp = math and science
- She had scientist's clear, logical thinking; he would help expand her insights
about human world

### Vivian's Family Background
- Parents **Al and Adele Sinetar** met 1920s New York as Jewish immigrants
- Started with no money, little education
- Built successful businesses, rose to middle-class comfort
- First in extended family to graduate with university degree
- Breaking new ground: first to marry outside Jewish faith
- Both her parents accepted Thorp

### The Borscht Dinner
- Dinner at in-laws closed the deal
- **Adele** was legendary cook: borscht with sour cream, chicken paprikash,
stuffed cabbage, potato latkes, more sour cream
- Living years in student co-op where ultimate entrée was blue-veined horse meat
and canned peaches, Thorp was perpetually hungry
- Adele urged additional helpings
- Then brought out cheese blintzes—ate two, offered more, and again
- Finally stopped at twenty, "pretty much wiping out the family reserves"

### Interfaith Marriage Challenge
- Got MA in physics June 1955, asked Vivian to marry shortly after
- Her parents willing to accept son-in-law who would be "forever poor" on
academic salary
- Problem: needed Jewish wedding or family scandalized
- Solution: **Rabbi William Kramer**, young Reform rabbi
- Kramer had been chaplain of US Senate five years earlier
- Later (1960) would perform ceremony for **Sammy Davis, Jr.** and **May
Britt**—so politically polarizing JFK asked them to wait until after election
- Marriage outraged conservatives in America

> "My handicap? I'm a one-eyed Negro Jew." — Sammy Davis, Jr. (lost eye in auto
accident, converted to Judaism)

### Wedding and Material Poverty
- January 1956 wedding
- High school teacher proclaimed loudly: "I always knew he would marry a
landsman!" (Yiddish term for fellow Jew from same region)
- Older relatives feigned hearing loss
- Thorp's possessions fit in single suitcase with broken clasp
- Worn clothing shared dishwater-gray commonality with hints of purple, beige,
yellow
- Shared $40 Harris Tweed jacket with roommate for dates
- Boxes of books with improvised bookcases: planks on concrete blocks

### Switching to Mathematics
- After marriage, began taking math courses
- Vivian supported bold gamble: skip upper-division background courses, jump
straight into graduate work
- Fill gaps as best he could
- Summer job needed for income despite Vivian working
- **Tom Scott** (co-op friend, engineering student) said **National Cash
Register (NCR)** hiring
- Offered $95/week ($760/week in 2016 dollars)
- Job: teach upper-division modern algebra to employees
- Chose textbook: **_A Survey of Modern Algebra_** by **Birkhoff and MacLane**,
legendary in mathematics education
- Learned material each day, lectured on it the next

### Meeting Richard Feynman
- Invited to house party by Tom Scott's female friend from NCR
- Introduced to her boyfriend **Richard Feynman**, playing bongo drums in alcove
- Thirty-eight-year-old professor at **Caltech**, already regarded as one of
world's most brilliant physicists
- Later won **Nobel Prize**, publicly explained **Challenger** disaster using
glass of ice water and rubber ring

### Feynman's Roulette Story
- Told story about Feynman in Las Vegas
- Man placing $5 bets on red or black—Feynman told him betting against casino
was losing proposition
- Offered to play part of casino
- Wandered wheel to wheel, gambler betting against Feynman by calling "red" or
"black" before spin
- Paying Feynman when lost, getting paid when won
- Even with disadvantage, gambler got ahead by $80, at which point Feynman quit
- Acting as casino and would eventually come out ahead, but wasn't willing to
risk further losses
- Like casino with only $80 bankroll—likely to be wiped out by customer's lucky
run

### Bankroll and Risk Management Lesson
- Even one of world's greatest physicists may not have realized he needed much
larger bankroll to cover risk
- **Understanding trade-off between risk and return** is fundamental challenge
faced by all gamblers and investors
- Poorly understood even by experts

### Asking Feynman About Roulette
- Asked Feynman: "Is there any way to beat the game of roulette?"
- He said there wasn't—Thorp was relieved and encouraged
- Suggested no one had worked out what he believed possible
- Began series of experiments

## Chapter 4: Las Vegas

### First Vegas Trip (Christmas 1957)
- Twenty-six-year-old with PhD in mathematics, earning too little at UCLA to
treat money casually
- As money manager now, believes surest way to get rich: only play gambling
games or make investments where you have an edge
- Knew of no one who had found way to beat casinos
- Gambling in Vegas wasn't on his priority list

### Las Vegas in 1958
- Not today's glittering strip of giant high-rise hotels jammed together
- Legendary casinos (**Sands, Flamingo, Dunes, Riviera, Tropicana**) are gone
- Mob and cash-skimming operations replaced by multibillion-dollar public
companies
- Then: long, straight, uncrowded highway with dozen one-story hotel-casino
complexes
- Hundreds of yards of sand and tumbleweeds separating them

### New Blackjack Strategy
- Colleague **Professor Robert Sorgenfrey** told him about new blackjack strategy
- Claimed to give players smallest house edge of any casino game
- Next best: baccarat (1.06% house advantage), then craps (1.41%)
- New figure: 0.62% house edge for blackjack—so close to even
- Planned to risk a few dollars for fun
- Strategy devised by four mathematicians during army time
- Covered several hundred possible decisions a player might face

### First Blackjack Experience
- Condensed strategy onto palm-sized card
- Only prior casino experience: putting coins in slot machine
- Found two rows of blackjack tables separated by "pit" with reserves of chips,
extra cards, cocktail waitresses
- Pit boss monitored closely
- Plunked down entire stake—stack of ten silver dollars—on green felt behind
"betting spot"
- Didn't expect to win (odds slightly against), but time to get casino experience
- Knew virtually nothing about casinos or how they operated
- "Like a person who had glanced at recipes but never been in a kitchen"

### Blackjack History and Rules
- Same as Spanish game **twenty-one**, referred to as early as 1601 in story by
**Cervantes**
- Mid-eighteenth century European gambling craze: French called it **vingt-et-un**
- Twentieth century US gaming: bonuses offered for special card combinations
- **Ace of Spades plus black Jack** = "blackjack"—name stuck for any two-card
total of 21
- Dealer gives two cards to everyone including himself
- First dealer card faceup, second facedown
- Goal: draw cards to get as close to 21 as possible without going over
- **Aces** count as 1 or 11 at player's option
- **Ten-value cards** (Ten, Jack, Queen, King) all count as 10
- Other cards count face value
- Dealer must draw until 17, then stop or "stand"
- Dealer's edge: player must risk busting first

### Player Advantages Over Dealer
- Dealer has fixed rules; player has choices
- Flexibility creates remarkable impact
- Can **split pairs** into two new hands, add bet equal to original
- Can **double down**: turn first two cards faceup, double bet, get exactly one
more card
- Free to draw or stand on any total of 21 or less

### The Seven-Card 21
- Sat down, players losing heavily
- Worried about consulting strategy card—would he be kicked out or ridiculed?
- Dealer made patronizing suggestions, indicated to crowd who was betting with
someone from farm
- Onlookers wondered who would split pair of lowly 8s when dealer's upcard was
powerful Ace
- Playing with unhurried deliberation, kept stack of chips even
- Strange thing happened: dealt Ace and 2 (total 3 or 13)
- Drew 2, then 3 (Ace, 2, 2, 3 = total 8 or 18)
- Dealer had 9 up, might have Ten hidden (total 19)
- 18 was pretty good hand—strategy said ask for another card
- Drew Ace (total 9 or 19)
- For sixth card drew Ace (total 15)
- "You deserved to bust," muttered kibitzer
- Seventh card was 6: seven-card total of 21 (Ace, 2, 2, 3, 6, Ace, 6)

> "Serves him right," said a bystander

### The $25 Bonus Myth
- Crowd said $25 bonus coming
- Dealer said no—only paid at few places in Reno
- Thorp thought amusing to create impression he sacrificed 18 because he foresaw
seven-card 21
- They might even pay him
- Of course they didn't, but amusement and patronizing attitude of bystanders
changed to respect and awe
- Lost $8.50 of $10 stake and quit
- Hooked on blackjack—not in usual sense
- Atmosphere of ignorance and superstition convinced him even good players didn't
understand underlying mathematics
- Returned home intending to find way to win

### Why Gamblers Keep Losing
- Despite all math proving no betting system could overcome casino advantage,
people kept losing tens of billions
- For most casino gambling games, mathematicians proved no system of varying bets
could blunt casino's edge
- Generations sought the impossible
- Players confused about inevitability of losing long-term because each plays
comparatively short time
- Allows some to be lucky winners

### Games Where Edge Can Be Computed
- True for any game where you can compute edge and payoff doesn't depend on
results of previous bets or wagers of other players
- Examples: coin tossing, craps, keno, roulette, money wheel
- Provided you don't have help of prediction device

### Different: Horse Racing and Stock Market
- Can't compute probabilities
- Other players' bets affect payoffs

### Conventional Wisdom About Blackjack
- Belief casinos must come out ahead in long run supported by conventional wisdom
- Argued if blackjack could be beaten, casinos would change rules or drop game
- Neither had happened
- Confident from roulette experiments he could predict roulette, wasn't willing
to accept these claims about blackjack
- Decided to check for himself if player could systematically win

## Chapter 5: Conquering Blackjack

### The Intellectual Challenge
- Not money that drew him to blackjack
- Could use extra dollars, but expected low-budget academic life
- Intrigued by possibility that by sitting and thinking, could figure out how to
win
- Curious to explore world of gambling he knew nothing about

### Library Research
- Back from Vegas, headed to section in UCLA library where mathematical and
statistical research articles kept
- Grabbed volume containing article with strategy played in casino
- Stood and began to read
- As mathematician, heard winning systems supposed to be impossible—didn't know
why
- Knew theory of probability begun 400+ years earlier with book on games of
chance
- Attempts to find winning systems over following centuries stimulated theory
development
- Eventually led to proofs that winning systems for casino gambling games
impossible under most circumstances
- Benefited from habit of checking it out for himself

### The Eureka Moment
- As eyes gobbled up equations, suddenly saw both why could beat game and how to
prove it
- Strategy used in casino assumed every card had same chance of being dealt as
any other during play
- Cut casino's edge to just 0.62%—best odds of any game offered
- Realized odds as game progressed actually depended on which cards still left
in deck
- Edge would shift as play continued, sometimes favoring casino, sometimes player
- Player who kept track could vary bets accordingly
- With help of mental picture based on advanced mathematics, believed player edge
must often be substantial
- Saw how player could condense and use information about actual play at table

### The Strategy Development
- Decided to begin by finding best strategy when knew which cards already played
- Bet more when odds in favor, bet less otherwise
- Casino would win more of small bets, but player would win majority of big
wagers
- If bet enough where had advantage, should eventually get ahead and stay ahead

### Contacting Roger Baldwin
- Left UCLA library, went home to figure out next steps
- Wrote to **Roger Baldwin**, one of four authors of blackjack article
- Asked for details about calculations, told him wished to extend analysis
- Generously sent actual computations weeks later
- Two large boxes of lab manuals filled with thousands of pages of calculations
- Done by authors on desk calculators while served in army during spring 1959
- Wedged between teaching duties and research in UCLA Mathematics Department
- Mastered every detail, excitement mounting as strove to speed up enormous
number of calculations between him and winning system

### Baldwin Strategy Limitations
- Best way to play when nothing known about which cards already played
- Analysis for single deck (only version played in Nevada at time)
- Showed advice of reigning gambling experts poor, unnecessarily giving casinos
extra 2% advantage

### The 550 Strategy Table Problem
- Any strategy table must tell player how to act for each case arising from ten
possible dealer upcard values versus each of fifty-five different pairs of cards
dealt to player
- 550 different situations
- To find best way for player to manage cards in each, need to calculate all
possible ways subsequent cards can be dealt and payoffs that result
- May be thousands, even millions of ways each hand can play out
- Do this for each of 550 situations
- Computations for complete deck become enormous
- If dealt pair, table must tell whether to split
- Next decision: whether to double down
- Final decision: whether to draw more cards or stop ("stand")

### Condensing to Pictorial Cards
- Once figured out winning strategy, planned to condense myriad decisions onto
tiny pictorial cards
- Allow to visualize patterns, making much easier to recall what to do in each
of 550 possible cases

### The Computational Challenge
- Baldwin group's calculations approximate because exact calculations couldn't be
done with desk calculators in human lifetime
- Work in 1959 much more extensive
- Had to deduce strategy for each of millions of possible partially played decks
- Standard practice: dealer begins by "burning" one card (taking from top,
placing on bottom faceup as signal not to deal later)
- Leaving fifty-one cards still in play
- Ten cases to analyze, corresponding to ten different card values of missing
card: Ace, 2…9, 10
- Could apply Baldwin analysis for each, make strategy table for each of 550
playing situations
- Eleven strategy tables total: one for full deck, one each for ten
possibilities where one card missing

### The Exponential Growth Problem
- Identify two missing cards, so only fifty cards left to play
- How many different fifty-card decks can arise?
- Forty-five ways to take out two cards with different values
- Ten ways to take out two cards of same value
- Total: fifty-five
- Leads to fifty-five more calculations and fifty-five more strategy tables (each
could take twelve man-years on desk calculators per Baldwin group)
- Continue developing strategy tables for every partial deck
- For one deck of fifty-two cards: about thirty-three million partially played
decks
- Leading to gigantic library of thirty-three million strategy tables

### Simplifying the Problem
- Facing 400 million man-years of calculations, with resulting railroad car full
of strategy tables (enough to fill Rolodex five miles long)
- Tried to simplify
- Predicted strategies and player's edge for partly used decks depended mainly on
fraction (percentage) of each type of card remaining rather than how many there
were

### The Fraction Insight
- Turned out to be true
- Meant effect of 12 Tens when forty cards left to be played about same as 9
Tens with thirty cards left, and 6 Tens with twenty cards left
- All three decks have same fraction (3/10 or 30%) of Ten-value cards
- In counting cards, mainly the fraction remaining matters, not the number

### Starting the Analysis
- Started by looking at how player's strategy and edge changed when varied
percentage of each card
- Planned to take out all four Aces, do calculations, see what happened
- Repeat by removing only four 2s, then only four 3s, and so forth

### Academic Positioning and MIT Move
- Began work during spring semester 1959
- Teaching at UCLA for year after received PhD June 1958
- Happened because gotten degree sooner than either he or adviser **Angus
Taylor** expected
- Hadn't applied for postdoctoral teaching position, thinking would be another
year before available
- Taylor arranged interim appointment at UCLA, helped find possible positions for
next year
- Offers liked best: **C. L. E. Moore Instructorship at MIT** and job at **GE
Corporation** in Schenectady, NY
- At GE would use physics background to do orbital calculations for space
projects
- Sounded interesting for while, but didn't think would have freedom expected to
find in academia to follow interests wherever led
- Expecting that kind of life as professor in university, chose MIT as first step

### Cross-Country Move to MIT
- Moved to MIT June 1959
- Purchased used black Pontiac sedan for $800 at police auction
- Drove across country towing two-wheeled U-Haul trailer loaded with household
goods
- Expecting first child in two months
- Vivian stayed with parents in Los Angeles while he went to Cambridge to set up
apartment and do mathematics research on summer grant
- Obliged under grant terms to work at MIT until mid-August
- Baby due few days later—very nervous about whether would get back in time

### The MIT Computing Opportunity
- Two Japanese mathematicians visiting UCLA needed ride to New York
- Happy to take them, in return for sharing driving
- On deserted highway somewhere in Ohio, startled from sound sleep about 1 AM as
brakes squealed and car shuddered
- Stopped just feet from large brown-and-white cow meandering placidly across
road
- Only set of brakes on car, loaded trailer doubled mass, also doubled stopping
distance
- Explained carefully before left, apparently without success
- Fighting fatigue, drove rest of way

### Cambridge Summer
- Once reached Cambridge, had lot to think about
- Never been to Boston area, didn't know anyone there
- Most regular staff and faculty away for summer
- Department arranged marvelous rental: first floor of grand old three-story
family home
- Having taken sight unseen, pleasantly surprised at how large and graciousness
of landlady (Irish widow lived there with two youngest of her children)
- By day did academic research in mathematics
- After dinner walked through nearly deserted buildings to calculator room
- Pounded **Monroe calculators** every night from 8 o'clock until shortly before
dawn
- Noisy electromechanical beasts about size of very large typewriter
- Could add, subtract, multiply, divide
- Equivalent to today's simplest cheapest handheld digital devices
- No air-conditioning—worked shirtless, fingers flying over clacking keyboard,
calculator whirring and rumbling in humid Cambridge summer nights

### The Towing Incident
- One morning about 3 o'clock, came out to find car missing from spot where
regularly parked
- Went back inside to call police
- Friendly night owl graduate student told him officers of law might themselves
be problem
- Phoned police station, learned car had been towed
- When pointed out had been legally parked, officer on duty explained since seen
in same spot every night, assumed abandoned
- Hurried downtown to night court where judge appealed screamed and threatened to
fine $100 on spot if said another word
- Friendly student (who driven there) explained police had arrangement with tow
yard
- Impound charges going to go up quickly if pressed case
- Next morning ransomed car at tow yard for about $100 (week's pay)
- Welcome to Boston
- Fortunately new hometown also beautiful, rich in science, education, culture,
arts

### Progress and the IBM 704
- Weeks wore on, calculations piled up
- Even though introduced shortcuts and efficiencies and very fast, making little
progress
- Hand calculations going to take hundreds, perhaps thousands of years
- At that point learned MIT had **IBM 704 computer**
- Being faculty member, could use it
- Using book from computer center, taught self to program machine in its
language, **FORTRAN**

### Birth of Daughter Raun
- August 1959 flew to Los Angeles four days before birth of first child
- Knowing having girl, agonized over name choices for weeks
- Found many liked but none first choice for both
- Enlisted help of Vivian's brother **Ray** (speech major at UCLA with gift for
English language)
- Would go on to distinguished legal career
- Invented name **Raun** with uplifting rhyming images like dawn and fawn
- None had ever heard of it but loved it
- Search was over

### MIT Teaching Load
- Back at MIT month later with Vivian and new baby
- Beginning teaching and research duties
- MIT had one of best mathematics departments in world
- Much expected of young faculty members
- Taught two classes each semester = six hours per week in classroom
- Preparation could run another twelve to fifteen hours per week
- Additional hours in office to meet with and help students
- Giving and grading of homework and exams
- Also expected to conduct and publish own original research in scholarly journals
- Submitted work reviewed by anonymous experts (**referees**) as precondition of
acceptance
- Rejections common

### "Publish or Perish"
- All who wanted to succeed in academic hierarchy knew mantra **"Publish or
perish"**
- Despite all this, continued to work on "arbitrary subsets" blackjack program
for IBM 704
- Testing and correcting computer code for modulus ("subroutine") at a time

<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

## Counting Systems and the Ten-Count Strategy

### Refining Card Counting Methods

- Removing four 5s from the deck was optimal — changed casino edge of 0.21% to
a huge player edge of 3.29%
- **Ultimate strategy** assigned point values to every card proportional to its
effect on the game
- Aces counted as −9, 2s as +5, down to Tens as −7
- Too complex for mental calculation, but simpler systems worked well
- Best practical compromise: small cards (2-6) = +1, neutral cards (7-9) = 0,
large cards (10-A) = −1
- This became the foundation for nearly all modern blackjack counting systems

### The Five-Count System

- Simple winning system based on tracking 5s in the deck
- Bet small when 5s remain, bet big when they're gone
- When 20-26 cards left, all 5s gone happens ~5% of the time
- When only 13 cards left, happens 30% of time
- At these favorable points, player has 3.29% edge

### Testing in Las Vegas (Summer 1960)

- Cross-country family drive from Boston to California
- Stopped in Las Vegas with $200 bankroll (~$1600 in 2016)
- Used a **palm-sized strategy card** — first of its kind
- Card showed optimal play for every hand versus each dealer upcard, plus
betting amounts based on Ten percentage
- Started counting "36, 16" (36 non-Tens and 16 Tens in full deck)
- Ratio of 36 ÷ 16 = 2.25 was the baseline
- When ratio dropped to 2.0, player had ~1% edge
- Bet $2-$10 at favorable counts, $1 otherwise
- Vivian bet 25 cents per hand to keep him company
- Lost $32 over the session — within expected variance
- Proved the system worked at casino speed without needing to look at the card

> "You'd better take out some more money, because you're going to need it."
— Hostile dealer who smelled a rat

## Publishing the Discovery

### The Academic Plagiarism Risk

- **Angus Taylor** (UCLA PhD thesis adviser) suggested sending work to a
well-known California mathematician
- Sent mathematical work — got no response
- 11 months later at Southern California meeting of the American Mathematical
Society, Taylor discovered someone presenting Thorp's discovery as original work,
about to be published under their name in a well-known journal
- Neither Taylor nor Thorp knew what to do — both were stunned
- Academic vice president of entire UC system was an ethical mathematician but
didn't know how to handle the situation

### The Timing Factor

- Common in science for discoveries to be made independently by multiple
researchers at nearly the same time
- Examples: **calculus** (Newton and Leibniz), **theory of evolution**
(Darwin and Wallace)
- Five years before Thorp's work, blackjack analysis would have been much more
difficult
- Five years later, with better computers, it would be much easier
- Easier to solve a problem if you know it can be solved — word of mouth meant
others would repeat the work sooner rather than later

### Publishing Strategy

- Chose **Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences** — quickest to
publish (2-3 months), very prestigious
- Required a member of the academy to approve and forward the work
- Sought out **Claude Shannon**, only mathematics member of academy at MIT
- Shannon famous for creating **information theory**, crucial for modern
computing and communications

### Meeting Claude Shannon

- Department secretary warned Shannon would only give a few minutes
- Shannon was "thinnish alert man of middle height and build, somewhat
sharp-featured"
- Few minutes turned into hour and a half of animated dialogue over lunch in
MIT cafeteria
- Shannon pointed out Thorp made the big theoretical breakthrough; remaining
work was details and elaboration
- Shannon suggested title change from "A Winning Strategy for Blackjack" to
"A Favorable Strategy for Twenty-One" (more sedate and acceptable to academy)
- Space in magazine was tight — reluctantly accepted Shannon's suggestions for
condensation
- Shannon asked: "Are you working on anything else in the gambling area?"
- Thorp revealed roulette work — plans to build small wearable computer for
predictions
- Ideas flew between them; several hours later, excited by plans to work
together to beat the game

## The American Mathematical Society Presentation

### Initial Resistance

- Submitted abstract titled "Fortune's Formula: The Game of Blackjack" for
Washington DC meeting
- Screening committee nearly unanimously rejected it
- **John Selfridge** (number theorist from UCLA, committee member) held the
world's record for finding the largest known prime number
- Selfridge persuaded committee Thorp was legitimate mathematician — if he said
it was true, it likely was

### Why Reject a Gambling Talk?

- Mathematicians regularly receive crank claims of solving famous problems
- Claims almost always from the mathematically uneducated or contain simple
errors
- So-called solutions often to problems proven impossible (e.g., trisecting any
angle with compass and straightedge)
- Mathematicians had proven winning system impossible for most standard gambling
games
- Committee's skepticism — ironically — became Thorp's strongest motivation for
proving it could be done

### Media Explosion

- Two evenings before the meeting, **Dick Stewart** of The Boston Globe called
inquiring about the talk
- Next morning: picture and Stewart's article on front page
- Within hours, news services released story and photos to scores of papers
nationwide
- Vivian wearily logging incoming wave of hundreds of messages
- Baby daughter Raun cried each time the telephone rang

## Chapter 6: The Day of the Lamb

### The Washington Presentation

- Flew into Washington DC during gigantic storm, city packed after JFK's recent
inauguration
- American Mathematical Society meeting held at old Willard Hotel
- Expected scholarly audience of 40-50, found animated standing-room crowd of
hundreds
- Audience included reporters with cameras, people sporting sunglasses and gaudy
oversized pinkie rings
- Presented matter-of-fact technical talk on counting 5s, then Tens, then
hinted at more sophisticated systems
- Press conference arranged after talk, televised by major network, radio
program interviews

### Press Skepticism

- Scientists and technical types understood and believed the winning strategy
- Casinos and some press did not
- **The Washington Post** ran cynical editorial comparing claim to weed killer
scam: "Send $1 for a surefire weed killer. Back comes a note saying 'Grab by
the roots and pull like hell.'"
- Casino spokesman mockingly claimed they sent cabs to airport to meet players
with systems

> "When a lamb goes to the slaughter, the lamb might kill the butcher. But we
always bet on the butcher." — Casino spokesman

### Tom Wolfe's Coverage

- Young reporter **Tom Wolfe** for The Post followed up with interview
- Ran story: "You Can So Beat the Gambling House at Blackjack, Math Expert
Insists"
- Wolfe curious, sympathetic but probing — later became one of America's most
famous authors

### Reflection on Life's Turning Point

- Wondered how research into mathematical theory of a game might change his life
- Abstract: life is mixture of chance and choice
- Chance = cards dealt in life; choice = how you play them
- Chose to investigate blackjack — chance offered new set of unexpected
opportunities

> "Acknowledgment, applause, and honor are welcome and add zest to life but
they are not ends to be pursued. What matters is what you do and how you do it,
the quality of the time you spend, and the people you share it with."

### The Deluge of Mail

- National AP wire service ran Tom Wolfe's story
- Thousands of letters and phone calls poured into MIT Math Department
- Secretaries busy for weeks
- 25-page "proof" claiming reincarnation of Ponce de León
- Offer to be bodyguard, assuring protection needed when beating casinos
- Hostile letter from would-be bodyguard warning he could "put a bullet between
your eyes at 25 yards" with .45-caliber automatic
- Greatest number asked for copies of paper and detailed instructions
- Manufactured and sent out hundreds of copies

### The Backers: Mr. X and Mr. Y

- Most promising offer came from two New York multimillionaires
- **Emmanuel "Manny" Kimmel** — wealthy businessman from Maplewood, NJ, about 65
- **Eddie Hand** (Mr. Y) — wealthy businessman from upstate NY, fortyish
- Kimmel arrived at Cambridge apartment with two nieces (actually mink-coated
beauties)
- Dealt blackjack for hours, quizzed Thorp about research
- Agreed to trip to Nevada during MIT's spring break in April
- Drew out pearl necklaces from overcoat pocket as gift for Vivian
- Offered to put up $100,000+ ($800,000 in 2016)

### Training Sessions in New York

- Every Wednesday (no classes to teach), flew Boston to New York
- Arrived at Manny's Manhattan penthouse; dealt while Thorp played Ten-Count
- Kimmel fixated on Ten-Count, wouldn't consider other counting methods
- After each session Kimmel gave $100-$150 to cover expenses plus a salami
- Salamis added unmistakable aroma to cabin during return flight

### The Two Strategies

- **Wild approach**: bet table limit whenever player advantage exceeded small
figure (e.g., 1%)
- Wins most money but violent wealth fluctuations, requires large bankroll
- Kimmel and Hand offered $100,000+
- **Conservative approach**: vary bet size based on edge (2x bet at 1% edge, 4x
at 2%, 10x at 5%+)
- Goal was to test system, not make big money for backers
- Planned moderate certain win rather than big payout with more risk
- Betting $50-$500, highest casino maximum generally available

### Vivian's Concerns

- Both apprehensive and supportive
- Knew Thorp didn't make claims he couldn't back up
- Worried about dangers: Would casinos play fair? Might they cheat? Drug or use
violence?
- Worried about "nieces" who weren't really nieces
- World of easy money and easy women — what other perils?
- Could backers protect him against casino funny business?
- After whole country heard claims, backing down would validate retorts of
baloney
- Thorp was certain he was right — challenging Goliath on his terms, not
Goliath's
- Vivian, despite reservations, thought he could do it

### The Nevada Trip Begins

- Met at New York airport on cold April afternoon
- Boarded plane at midnight, approached Reno as garish patch of light in
Stygian blackness
- City looked like "bloody reddish neon spider spread over the landscape"
- Vivian more alarmed than Thorp about flight into unknown
- Called collect if everything okay, coded by middle initial indicating
thousands ahead or behind
- Code: Initial A = $1,000-$2,000, B = $2,000-$3,000, up to Z covering
$25,000-$26,000

### First Casino Session

- Started small at casino outside town, betting $1-$10
- Lost a few dollars in an hour, then establishment closed for three hours on
"Good Friday"
- Chose downtown Reno casino with very favorable rules
- Lost steadily for eight hours despite favorable rules
- Down $100 after eight hours
- Management thought he was using fallacious betting system
- At 3 AM got table to himself, new unfriendly dealer
- Moved bets to $2-$20 range after deck became favorable
- Won next several hands, recouped losses, finished slightly ahead by 5 AM

### Harold's Club Triumph

- Saturday evening: visited famous **Harold's Club** in downtown Reno
- Starting with floundering bingo parlor in 1930s, owner **Harold Smith Sr.**
built it into most famous casino in US
- Innovations: women dealers, 24-hour operation, customer service for everyday
gambler
- Twenty years earlier as 10-year-old, Thorp intrigued by roadside signs:
"HAROLD'S CLUB, RENO, OR BUST"

### The Private Game

- Pit boss invited them to private upstairs area for higher-stakes players
- Own dealer, one of three tables entirely to themselves
- Asked for better playing conditions after 15 minutes at $500 ahead
- **Harold Smith Sr. and Jr.** slipped in from side door, came up behind dealer
- Knew who Manny and Eddie were; concerned about scheme that could prove costly
- Pleasantries exchanged, but made their point: deck would be shuffled often as
necessary
- Dealers shuffled with 12-15 cards left, halfway through deck, finally after
only two hands
- Still won, squeezed out another $80

### The Next Casino Disaster

- Next stop: maximum $300, excellent rules
- Cards ran badly, lost steadily
- After four hours down $1,700 and discouraged
- Knew house can lose short-term even with advantage — card counter can fall
behind for hours or days
- Persisted, waited for deck to become favorable
- Deck suddenly produced 5% advantage
- Made maximum $300 bet — all remaining chips
- Picked up hand: pair of 8s (must split)
- Drew probably bust or stand on one 8, dealer beats with 17+
- But splitting starts each new hand with 8 (so-so first card)
- Flung three $100 bills onto second 8
- On one 8 received a 3; doubling down was right move — dropped another $300
- $900 (largest bet yet) now on the table
- Dealer showing 6 up, had Ten under, promptly busted — won both hands for $900
gain
- Left only $800 down, next deck quickly became good
- Within minutes wiped out losses and went ahead $255

### The Ten-Count System Performance

- Second time Ten-Count showed "moderately heavy losses mixed with 'lucky'
streaks of most dazzling brilliance"
- Characteristic of random series of favorable bets
- Would see this again in both gambling and investment worlds

### Being Barred

- Next afternoon visited casino outside town again
- Before sitting down, called Vivian — when returned, casino barred them from
play
- Would only be too happy to pick up meal tab
- Floor manager explained they'd seen steady winning at large bet sizes the day
before, puzzled, decided system was involved
- Nevada casinos could bar players without cause — considered private clubs
- Skin color among criteria once used by some establishments

### Stateline at Lake Tahoe

- Drove to **Stateline, Nevada** at south end of Lake Tahoe
- Town jammed against Nevada side of border with California
- Casinos and hotels crowded close to California to lure tourists
- Arrived about 6 PM at large, brightly lit gambling factory — jammed
- Barely able to get seat at blackjack tables
- Placed $2,000 in chips on table
- Manny insisted on playing beside Thorp, calling his plays and controlling bet
sizes
- Bad idea: didn't know strategy, lost the advantage
- Unable to correct him without making what they were doing obvious
- Excitable and bad listener, paid little attention to proper play, misplayed
hands, bet too much for $10,000 bankroll
- Soon won $1,300; betting wildly, Manny won $2,000
- Drooling pit boss invited to dinner and show
- Enjoyed filet mignon and champagne
- Bill presented: $11,000 in lost profits

### Harvey's Wagon Wheel — Breaking the Bank

- Strolled to new glittering high-rise **Harvey's Wagon Wheel**
- Evolved from one-room log cabin built 1944 by **Harvey Grossman** and wife
Llewellyn
- Now held casino towers on south shore, 197-room twelve-story hotel
- Bought $2,000 in chips, sat at empty table
- Plagued by $1 bettors slowing game and concealing cards
- After few minutes pit boss offered private table
- Explained club didn't like psychological effect on other customers, but $25
minimum game could be arranged
- Small crowd gathered, quiet, anticipating "imminent slaughter of their
fiscally plump fellow lamb"

### Manny Joins In Again

- After winning few hundred dollars, Manny jumped in again
- Wouldn't listen; tried to make best of it
- Kept count, directed play of hands for both
- Tried to be subtle; he wasn't paying close attention
- He knew to follow bet size changes up and down — still had an edge
- After 30 minutes emptied money tray — "breaking the bank"
- No longer smiling, pit boss scared

### Casino Panic

- Employees began to panic
- Dealer begged boyfriend for help: "Oh, help me. Please, help me."
- Pit boss trying to explain away win to nervous knot of subordinates
- Money tray being restocked, crowd swelled cheering their David against casino
Goliath
- Played another two hours, broke bank again
- Great heaps of chips: more than $17,000 in profits
- Thorp won $6,000, Manny (overbetting wildly) added $11,000
- Tiring from huge dinner, increased effort managing Manny's hand and own,
fatigue from previous days

### The Dramatic Win

- Getting harder to count properly, partner wilting
- Insisted they quit, headed for cashier
- Pockets bulged like saddlebags, bounty unnoticed
- Along the way startled to meet "three or four lovely ladies wandering back
and forth smiling affectionately"

> "I…will…not…leave…this…place!" — Manny refusing to stop when Thorp tried to
dislodge him

- In 45 minutes lost back entire $11,000 he'd won
- Even so, returned to hotel that evening with winnings — ahead $13,000 so far
on trip
- Daily calls to Vivian showed winning more each day
- Best call: asked dramatically for Edward M. Thorp (ahead $12,000-$13,000)
- In relieved and buoyant voice Vivian told operator "wasn't home"

### Final Day — The Ultimate Countermeasures

- Returned to club where first practiced
- Put $1,000 in chips on table, began to win
- Word spread, owner on scene within minutes
- Gave dealer and pit boss instructions in a panic
- If Thorp changed bet size, dealer to shuffle entire deck before next deal
- Whenever varied number of hands taken, cards shuffled
- Could play from one to each hand at a time, faster than best dealers could
deal — cards shuffled
- Dealer from little practice session standing in background saying how much
Thorp had advanced in skill
- When happened to scratch nose, dealer shuffled
- Asked whether she would shuffle each time he did so — said yes
- Tested with few more scratches — she meant it
- Asked if any unusual act would cause shuffle — again "Yes"
- Now playing even with house — shuffling all cards and starting each deal with
full deck destroyed advantage
- Asked for larger chips ($50 or $100) — all he had were twenties
- Owner stepped forward: house would not sell them
- Had brand-new deck brought in, dealer spread facedown then faceup
- Asked why they spread them facedown — common practice in casinos
- Although common, casinos seldom examine card backs — now they did for full
two minutes
- Dealer explained they believed Thorp had unusually acute vision, could
distinguish tiny blemishes on backs
- Let him know what cards would appear next
- Scoffed, but panicky owner brought in four fresh decks in five minutes
- Changing decks didn't matter — gave up on that
- In whispers formulated new theory: dealer claimed could count every card as
played, always knew exactly which cards had/hadn't appeared
- Well known to mnemotechny students you can memorize deck in proper order as
dealt
- But information when memorized cannot be used quickly enough for blackjack
play
- Challenged dealer by claiming no one in world could watch 38 cards dealt
quickly off pack then quickly tell how many of each type remained
- Claimed pit boss standing next to her could do just that
- Offered $5 for demonstration — both looked down sheepishly, wouldn't answer
- Raised offer to $50, then $500 — remained silent and ashamed
- Eddie Hand watching throughout, increased offer to $500 — no response, left
in disgust

### Trip Results

- Spring break ending at MIT — trip at an end
- In 30 man-hours of medium-to-large-scale play, $10,000 grew to $21,000
- Never had to go into original capital further than $1,300 (plus expenses)
- Experiment was success, system performed at tables just as theory predicted
- Satisfied — future blackjack trips would have to fit around academic schedule
and family life
- Made no plans for another trip with Manny and Eddie, simply left possibility
open

<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Chapter 6 Conclusion: Manny Kimmel's Criminal Background

### The Revelation About Manny Kimmel

- Journalist **Connie Bruck** contacted Thorp decades later for her book *Master of the Game*
- Revealed **Manny Kimmel's** true background: hidden partner in Kinney Service Corporation (later Time Warner)
- Kimmel made fortune in 1920s-'30s from **bootlegging and numbers racket**
- Partner with **Abner "Longie" Zwillman**, second most powerful mobster in U.S. (1935)
- **Eddie Hand**, Manny's friend, shipped cars for Chrysler and later received **$47 million in Ryder warrants**

### Manny's Death and Legacy

- Kimmel died in Florida, 1982, age 86
- Left young widow **Ivi**, who married Manny after his wife's death
- In 2005, History Channel featured Vivian and Thorp in one-hour blackjack program
- Ivi still had Thorp's 1964 letter about baccarat discoveries
- Eddie Hand retired wealthy to Montecito, then Southern France

> "When a lamb goes to the slaughter, the lamb might kill the butcher. But we always bet on the butcher. The day of the lamb had come." — Casino spokesman after Thorp's blackjack claims

## Chapter 7: Card Counting For Everyone

### MIT Career Decision (1961)

- Thorp cashed $100 bills weekly from casino winnings at MIT cafeteria
- Currency depreciation: $100 in 1961 ≈ $1,000 today
- Department chairman **W. T. "Ted" Martin** encouraged third year at MIT
- Prestigious environment: **Norbert Wiener** (cybernetics), **Isadore Singer** (future Abel Prize winner)
- **C.L.E. Moore Instructorship** brought in future Nobel winners like **John Nash** (economics) and **Paul Cohen** (Fields Medal)
- Thorp declined to stay—felt he needed more mathematical background
- Lacked senior faculty collaboration in his specialty area
- Work with **Claude Shannon** on blackjack and roulette had no academic constituency

### New Mexico State University Offer

- **$5 million post-Sputnik Centers of Excellence Grant** from National Science Foundation
- $40 million equivalent today, mandate to build PhD program over four years
- Salary jumped from $6,600 (MIT/Washington) to **$9,000/year**
- Promoted to **associate professor with tenure**
- Six-hour-a-week teaching load of graduate courses
- Better climate for family (baby Raun) closer to relatives

### Writing *Beat the Dealer*

- **Yale Altman** from **Blaisdell** (Random House subsidiary) commissioned book
- Working title: *Fortune's Formula: A Winning Strategy for Blackjack*
- Random House took project from Blaisdell, changed title to **_Beat the Dealer_**
- Published **November 1962**, timed to exploit Nevada casinos before publication
- Furious summer 1961: writing, math research, Nevada trips, preparing for New Mexico State move, working 20 hours/week on roulette with Claude Shannon

### Learning About Casino Cheating (August 1961)

- Trip to Las Vegas with **"Junior"** (also known as **Sonny**), a Harvard law student who contacted Thorp at MIT
- Junior started playing casino blackjack at age 21 using **end play**
- End play: single-deck games dealt all the way down could get very rich in Aces and Tens
- Canny players made huge favorable bets, needed enormous bankrolls to withstand wild fluctuations
- Junior had been barred, cheated, or reshuffled; once used Hollywood makeup artist to look Chinese
- Sat down at Las Vegas blackjack table wearing bulky body shell, dyed black hair
- Pit boss pointed and laughed: "Look at Junior, all dressed up like a Chinese"

### The January 1962 Nevada Trip with Russell Barnhart and Mickey MacDougall

- **Russell T. Barnhart**: magician and gambling scholar who contacted Thorp after January 1961 DC talk
- **Percy Diaconis**: seventeen-year-old prodigy with card sleight of hand, later became Harvard professor and won MacArthur Foundation "genius" grant
- Diaconis studied card shuffling theory; concluded **seven fairly thorough shuffles** randomize any deck
- **Mickey MacDougall**: magician and card detective, wrote *Danger in the Cards*
- MacDougall worked as special consultant to **Nevada Gaming Control Board** for several years
- Board cited several small casinos for cheating based on his findings
- Barnhart raised **$10,000 from anonymous backers** (later revealed: **William F. Rickenbacker** and *National Review* staff)

### The Blackjack Foray Strategy

- Bet modestly until Mickey gave go-ahead signal
- Raise betting scale and play for one hour maximum
- Stop sooner if warned by Mickey or Russell
- Change casinos after each session, vary shifts to limit observation time
- Stop after moderate loss to limit impact of undetected cheating
- **Key insight**: "Mathematically, interruptions didn't matter, because my lifetime of playing was just one long series of hands, and chopping it into sessions and playing them at various times and in various casinos should not affect my edge, nor the long-run amount I could expect to win. This principle applies in both gambling and investing."

### Detecting Casino Cheating

- When Mickey and Russell signaled cheating, Thorp quit for a lesson in how it was done
- Mickey demonstrated cheating slowly, then at casino speed
- Techniques included **"tells"** (poker player term for unconscious signals)
- Common cheat: **peeking at top card** (called "top card")
  - If top card good for player, deal the second card instead
  - If top card good for dealer giving himself a card, take the top; otherwise deal himself the second
  - Heavy favorite to beat the player
  - Nearly impossible to prove even when told in advance and watching closely

### Session Sixteen: Second Dealing Exposed

- Favorite strip hotel casino, winning session fifteen
- Pit boss asked how they were doing; Mickey replied: **"Up and down, like an elevator"**
- Twenty minutes later, man rushed through front door and replaced dealer
- Mickey showed Thorp the **virtually undetectable peek and second-card dealing**
- Suspicious, Thorp reduced bets to minimum, lost a couple hands, left
- Back in rooms, Mickey demonstrated the technique

### The Reno Disguise Test

- Arranged through mutual friends to meet couple who would watch Thorp play in casinos
- They had never met and didn't know what Thorp looked like
- Thorp appeared at dinner: bearded fellow in brightly patterned Hawaiian shirt, wraparound sunglasses, jeans
- Headed for one of big hotel casinos
- Chose **third base** (farthest seat to left as viewed from player's side)—best seat for card counter
- Last to act, benefits from having seen more cards before playing hand

### The Reno Win and Recognition

- Flashed roll of bills, bought heap of chips
- Dealer (attractive young woman) found him interesting, chatted
- Offered drinks to relax them (not to relax himself)
- She told him her shift ended at 2 A.M., maybe they could "do something" afterward
- Steady winnings attracted pit boss attention
- By 1 A.M. management decided he was a card counter
- Parade from management came to watch
- Told dealer he was no longer welcome at tables
- Word evidently spread; wearing same disguise, barred from play next day at several casinos

### The Transformation

- That afternoon, decided to test disguise further
- Shaved beard, replaced prescription sunglasses with contact lenses, combed hair differently
- Sports jacket and tie—cocktail attire—completed transformation
- Companions showed no signs of recognition: "Yes-s-s?" Astonishment was Thorp's delight

### Return to Same Casino

- Went to same casino, took same seat as night before
- Same dealer looked up as he put chips on table
- She saw no cash roll, now wearing wedding ring—not a person of interest
- To avoid being given away by voice, didn't talk
- Cocktail waitress offered drink; said in barely audible hoarse whisper: "Milk"
- Won again, all was well—for a while

### Exposing a Player Cheat

- Pit boss came to watch, followed by same management parade as previous night
- But focused on player cheat seated next to Thorp
- After receiving first two cards, if he liked his chances he would add to wager; take some of bet back if he didn't
- For an hour or so, management scolded him repeatedly
- When he wouldn't stop or leave, escorted him out
- With pile of chips growing steadily, Thorp played on undisturbed
- Next day had no problem playing in establishments that had barred his bearded self the day before

### Casino Countermeasures Philosophy

- **More to beating blackjack than counting cards and keeping cool as bankroll fluctuates**
- Green felt table is a **stage**, card counter is an **actor on that stage**
- Must put on effective act and present nonthreatening persona
- As many ways to do this as there are characters to portray in theater
- Can be: drunken cowboy from Texas, wildly animated lady from Taiwan, **Caspar Milquetoast** (nervous accountant from Indianapolis), Miss Spectacular

### Publication Impact

- **Dave Scherman's** piece "It's Bye! Bye! Blackjack" in **January 1964 _Sports Illustrated_**
- *Beat the Dealer* sold out everywhere
- Two months later *Life* ran nine-page story
- Book moved onto *New York Times* bestseller list

### Personal Consequences of Publicity

- Pleasure of seeing father's silent pride
- Contact from father's younger sister who vanished from his life in 1904 with mother when parents divorced
- *Life* story led his sister to him through Thorp
- Father arranged to visit her in Iowa with five children and numerous grandchildren
- Separated when he was six and she was four
- Father dreamed lifetime he would somehow find her again
- He never saw her—died of heart attack shortly before the trip

### The Card Counter Invasion

- After reading articles, thousands of counters and would-be counters headed for Las Vegas
- **Nevada Resort Hotel Association** met in secret emergency session
- Twenty-nine years later, casino executive **Vic Vickrey** described meeting

> "How the heck do I know how he does it? I guess he's got one of them mathematical minds or photographic memories, or something." — Cecil Simmons, Desert Inn casino boss

> "All I know, is he wrote a book that teaches everyone how to win every time they play blackjack. I'm just telling you, this book-learning SOB has ruined us…we're out of the blackjack business." — Carl Cohen, Sands casino manager (mid-1960s conversation)

### April Fool's Day Rule Changes (1964)

- **April 1, 1964**: Nevada Resort Hotel Association announced first-ever blackjack rule changes
- **Pair splitting and doubling down would be restricted**
- **Entire pack of cards would be reshuffled after just a couple of deals**
- These changes designed to thwart card counters

### Media and Industry Response

- *Las Vegas Sun* editorial (April 3, 1964): "Anybody who has been around Nevada very long knows that [casinos welcome] players with a system"
- Claimed Thorp "obviously doesn't know the facts of gambling life. There has never been a system invented that overcomes…the advantage the house enjoys in every game of chance"
- "Dr. Thorp may be qualified at mathematics, but he is sophomoric on gambling" — **Edward A. Olsen**, Gaming Control Board chairman
- **Gene Evans of Harrah's Club**: "…the club believes the player may have a better chance when the deck is shuffled every time, because all the Aces and face cards could come up on each deal"

### Impact of Rule Changes

- Thorp told press changes would hurt business badly
- Skilled counters would still win
- **Vic Vickrey** reported: "Our regular 21 players who were not attempting cards…rebelled to such a degree that our 21 play began to decline at an alarming rate"
- After several weeks, had no choice but to reinstate original rules more favorable to player
- Casino bosses understood what their apologists denied
- Mocking replaced by headlines: **"Vegas Casinos Cry Uncle, Change Rules—Players Too Smart"** and **"How Wizard of Odds Beat Las Vegas Cards"**

### Casino Industry Panic and Evolution

- From mathematical idea in Thorp's head, he forged system for beating the game
- Ridiculed by "casino beast" which sent cabs for "fools like me"
- Found himself barred, cheated, betrayed by gaming control board representative, generally persona non grata at tables
- Felt **satisfaction and vindication** when great beast panicked
- Felt good to know that **just by sitting in a room and using pure math**, could change the world

> "From a mathematical idea in my head, I forged a system for beating the game. Then I was ridiculed by the casino beast...I felt satisfaction and vindication when the great beast panicked. It felt good to know that, just by sitting in a room and using pure math, I could change the world around me."

- Rather than quit, **launched an army with _Beat the Dealer_**
- Thus continued great blackjack war between casinos and players
- Still rages **more than fifty years after the invention of card counting**

## Chapter 8: Players Versus Casinos

### The Post-Publication Blackjack Boom

- After book appeared, legions of blackjack players hit Nevada tables
- Anyone could bring palm-sized strategy cards and find games with rules good enough to play on level terms with casino
- Card counters and would-be card counters emerged
- Many were good and some would make their living from blackjack
- For majority, effort and persistence required to practice card counting, plus restraint, discipline, and temperament were obstacles to success
- Fact that blackjack could be beaten led to **upsurge in play**
- Over next few decades **blackjack displaced craps as dominant table game**

### Casino Dilemma

- Should they let minority of counters beat them in return for vastly increased revenues from great majority who couldn't or wouldn't count?
- Or should they choke off card counters with countermeasures, even if this would slow boom in blackjack play?
- When casinos first tried rules change, lost more in revenues than they gained in benefits
- Went back to old rules

### Multi-Deck Shoes

- Next brought in **dealing boxes known as shoes**
- Allowed use of four, six, or even eight decks
- Supposed to make card counting more difficult
- For those using **High–Low System**, wasn't much harder
- Correct play of hand pretty much same for various numbers of decks
- High–Low System already adjusted for number of unused cards, whether one or several decks

### Griffin Investigations and the "Black Book"

- Most widely used photo gallery of undesirables developed by **Griffin Investigations, Inc.**
- Private detective agency founded 1967 by **Beverly and Robert Griffin**
- Usual collection of criminals, player cheats, public nuisances rapidly expanded by addition of card counters
- Barred on sight, descriptions shared among casinos
- Dealers and pit bosses often couldn't figure out who was counting and who wasn't
- Non-counters who inadvertently aroused suspicion were forbidden to play
- Players were cheated and beaten in back rooms
- Griffin agency successfully sued by two top card counters, one was **James Grosjean** (Blackjack Hall of Fame member)
- Firm filed for bankruptcy in 2005

### Team Play and Bankroll Pooling

- Card counters formed informal networks, developed new and improved techniques
- *Beat the Dealer* introduced idea of a team
- Example: Five players each with $10,000 bankroll playing separately, winning at average rate of 1% or $100/hour
- Five together gain average of $500/hour
- If they pool money into one $50,000 bank, one player can bet five times as much as safely risk on own $10,000
- Expects to win five times as much: 1% of $50,000 = $500/hour rather than $100
- Four other players can all be playing simultaneously at different tables/casinos
- Each acting as though they have $50,000 bankroll, so group makes **$2,500/hour** when all playing
- Without pooling bankrolls, would make collectively only $500/hour

### Professional Blackjack Teams

- Entrepreneurs recruited and trained players, provided bankroll, shared profits
- Notable teams: **Tommy Hyland's** and **MIT group**
- MIT group chronicled in *Bringing Down the House*, inspired 2008 movie *21*
- **Al Francesco** pioneered creation of blackjack teams
- Idea well publicized by recruit **Ken Uston (1935–87)**
- Uston's books *Million Dollar Blackjack* and *The Big Player* inspired formation of other teams and intensified casino efforts to stop them

### Ken Uston's Background

- One of more colorful characters in blackjack history
- One-quarter Asian, Japanese grandfather
- Born **Kenneth Senzo Usui**
- Started career in securities business
- Became **youngest senior vice president ever at Pacific Stock Exchange**
- Drawn by allure of blackjack, left securities industry to play professionally

### Big Player Strategy

- Card counters wish to bet as little as possible when casino has edge
- Make large bet when cards favor them
- Ideal: player with bankroll large enough to allow $1,000 bets when deck favorable
- Bet table minimum ($5) when it isn't
- Wide betting spread of **200:1** is red flag to casino personnel
- To bet $1,000 on good situations with narrower betting spread of 4:1 requires **$250 bets when deck unfavorable**
- Cuts back overall gain

### Big Player Execution

- Teams placed members at several blackjack tables to track deck
- Betting minimum
- When deck became favorable, signaled **Big Player**
- Big Player wandered randomly from table to table, putting down sizable bets erratically
- Hadn't been at table before bet, so couldn't be counting
- Disguised with act
- Big Player might appear to be drunken flamboyant high-roller, often with beautiful companion

### Advanced Counting Systems

- Blackjack community explored and developed various possible counting methods
- Followed directly from Thorp's original computations showing effects of removing cards from deck
- Counting system assigns points to each card reflecting card's impact upon removal
- Closer these points correspond to actual effects of cards, more accurately that counting method estimates player's current edge

### The Ultimate Strategy

- Thorp presented what he called **ultimate strategy**
- Assigned whole number value to each card in close proportion to its impact on odds
- Numbers in table from 1962 edition of *Beat the Dealer*
- Second line shows change in player's edge upon removing one card
- Third line (obtained by multiplying by 13 and rounding): point count for ultimate strategy
- Good approximation to perfect point count
- Diverse point values meant Thorp expected this system to be used by computers, not people
- Intended only to illustrate basic principle for constructing point-count systems

**Table 1: Effect of Removing One Card from One Deck and the Ultimate (Point-Count) Strategy**

| Card | 2 | 3 | 4 | 5 | 6 | 7 | 8 | 9 | 10 | A |
|------|-----|-----|-----|-----|-----|-----|-----|-----|------|-------|
| Change In Edge | 0.36 | 0.48 | 0.59 | 0.82 | 0.47 | 0.34 | 0.03 | -0.23 | -0.54 | -0.68 |
| Points | 5 | 6 | 8 | 11 | 6 | 4 | 0 | -3 | -7 | -9 |

### High–Low (Complete Point Count)

- Best compromise between power and simplicity
- Appears in 1966 revised edition of *Beat the Dealer*
- Still used today by top professionals
- **Simplest possible point count**: cards get values of −1, 0, or +1 only
- Start with count at 0
- As "small" cards 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 used, each adds +1 to cumulative count
- Intermediate cards 7, 8, 9 counted as 0 (appearance doesn't affect total count)
- Big cards (Aces and Ten-value cards) count as −1, each reduces total by one

### High–Low Count Example

- Player sees these cards in first round: A, 5, 6, 9, 2, 3
- Count (starting with zero): −1 + 1 + 1 + 0 + 1 + 1 = +3
- With this count in one-deck game and reasonably favorable rules—player has edge on next deal
- As cards dealt, count goes up and down around zero
- When count positive: player benefits
- When negative: helps casino
- Impact of any particular value greater when fewer cards left
- **Good players simply estimate this by seeing how many cards are in discard tray**

### Testing the Point Count

- How hard is it to keep point count?
- Typical test: shuffle deck, remove one to three cards facedown, count through rest of deck
- Player declares result, then missing card(s) turned over to check accuracy
<!-- pp. 121-140 -->

### Advanced Card Counting Techniques

- **Inferring unseen cards**: When point count is zero after one card set aside,
  the unseen card must be a 0-point card (7, 8, or 9) to balance the complete
  deck's count
- **Puerto Rico incident with Henry Morgan**: Playing two-deck shoe, Thorp
  deduced dealer's hole card was 8 based on point count reaching zero with one
  unseen card
- Dealer exposed hole card, confirming the mathematical deduction
- Other dealers gathered in disbelief that an American expert knew the hidden card

### Counting Speed and Skill Development

- **Thorp's benchmark**: Could count one deck in 20-25 seconds to maintain pace
  in any game
- **Speed contests**: World Game Protection Conference card counting competition —
  fastest time ever witnessed was **8.8 seconds**
- Blackjack Hall of Fame member counted two decks in 33 seconds

### Casino Countermeasures

- **Technology**: Cameras, one-way mirrors, face-recognition software, RFID chips
  tracking bets
- Machines track cards and detect counting patterns
- **Continuous shuffle machines**: Perfect defense, no slowdown, but casinos pay
  vendor fees
- Nevada legislature (1985) outlawed devices assisting players in calculating odds
- **Legal status**: Card counting itself is not cheating under Nevada law — using
  your brain to play well is allowed
- Introducing loaded dice = cheating; subtracting chips after seeing cards = cheating;
  counting cards = legal

### Dealer Techniques and Player Exploits

- **Hole-card checking**: Dealer peeks at hidden card when showing Ace or Ten
- Careless dealers would warp cards by bending corners repeatedly
- **Warps**: Savvy players could spot warped Aces and Tens before they were dealt
- **Spooks**: Confederates positioned to see dealer's hole card, signal to player
- Some casinos delay dealer's second card draw until after players finish

### Non-Random Shuffling (1970s)

- Several people developed concealed computers despite 1985 Nevada devices law
- **Shuffle tracking**: When multideck packs aren't shuffled thoroughly, predictable
  patterns emerge
- Thorp's two-pronged approach: mathematical models + empirical studies of real shuffling

### Ace Location Technique

- Spread deck faceup, track Ace of Spades and card ahead of it (King of Hearts)
- Turn both faceup in otherwise facedown deck
- **After one shuffle**: Cards may separate but knowing KH position indicates
  Ace likely nearby
- Multiple shuffles: order sometimes reverses — Ace appears first
- If deck not shuffled well, player frequently knows Ace has higher-than-average
  chance of appearing soon
- **Applied to all four Aces**: Powerful advantage
- Casinos use standardized shuffling techniques which can be analyzed
- Players (with computer aid) track chunks of high cards redistributed in deck
- Camouflage effective since shuffle-trackers often found advantage at start of
  first deal, betting big before seeing any cards

### 1997 St. George Marathon and Las Vegas Visit

- **Peter Griffin** (The Theory of Blackjack author) arranged comped stay at
  Treasure Island through **Joe Wilcox**, casino manager
- Agreement: Thorp wouldn't play blackjack in Steve Wynn's casinos
- Joe mentioned casinos losing significant amounts to shuffle-trackers
- No effective shuffle defense found yet
- Thorp watched dealers at Treasure Island and two other casinos — many wheels
  were tilted
- Discovered new shuffle preventing tracking, kept method to himself

### Legal Landscape: Nevada vs. New Jersey

- **Nevada**: Casinos permitted to bar players
- **New Jersey**: Casinos could not bar players
- Both states allow gaming establishments to protect themselves via rule changes
  or reshuffling at will
- Card counting clearly not cheating under statutes
- **Las Vegas transformation**: Early mob period (*The Green Felt Jungle*, 1964) →
  corporate era (1980s) → corporate gambling billionaires → worldwide gaming expansion
- Professional players still thrive but opportunities increasingly limited for newcomers

### Blackjack Ball Gathering

- Annual private Nevada event hosted by **Max Rubin**, sponsored by Barona Casino
  (Southern California)
- **Blackjack Hall of Fame**: Members honored, featured in picture gallery at Barona
- Can stay free but must pledge never to play blackjack there — "most profitable
  investment ever by a casino"
- **2013 attendees**: Thorp's children (Raun, Karen, Jeff), **James Grosjean**
  (Harvard math graduate, advantage play developer), **Holy Rollers** (Christian
  card counting team transferring winnings to church)
- 102 guests, nearly half professional winners of $1+ million total
- **Blair Hull**: Parlayed blackjack winnings into hundreds of millions at Chicago
  Board Options Exchange
- **Bill Benter**: Used blackjack bankroll to build billion-dollar horse racing
  betting business worldwide
- **B.J. Traveler** (Taiwanese): Played in 64 countries over 6 years, netted ~$7
  million, survived year in Moscow dodging thieves

### Lunch with John Chang

- **John Chang**: Star of MIT team featured in movie *21*
- Casino wouldn't allow photo at blackjack table
- Sat at $100-minimum/$10,000-maximum table with good rules
- Chang and friend bought in with rolls of $100 bills ($5,000 each)
- "Our pockets are our banks"
- Eastern European dealer (friendly older woman) gave beginner's advice
- Chang thanked her politely, indicated willingness to learn
- Twenty minutes later: casino a few thousand dollars poorer, employee took
  photos by entrance

### Can Ordinary Players Still Beat the Game?

- Answer: qualified yes
- Many games have rules making them hard to beat
- **Blackjack payoff degradation**: Original 3:2 changed to 6:5 or 1:1 in many casinos
- Newsletters and services rate current games, identify beatable ones
- Thorp's keynote speech at third World Game Protection Conference (Las Vegas, 2008)
- When writing *Beat the Dealer* (1962), uncertain if impact would last 5 or 50 years
- Impact continues to present day

## Chapter 9: A Computer That Predicts Roulette

### History of Roulette Systems

- Modern roulette appeared in **Paris, 1796**
- Became favored high-stakes game at Monte Carlo
- High stakes, splendid settings, extreme luck swings attracted system players
- Systems too complex for precise gambler analysis but had plausible features

### The Labouchère (Cancellation) System

- Used for even-money bets in roulette (red/black, each 18/38 chance of winning)
- Write down string of numbers (e.g., 3, 5, 7)
- Total = 15
- First bet = sum of first and last numbers (3 + 7 = 10)
- If win: cross off first and last, bet remaining middle number (5)
- If lose: add 10 to string → (3, 5, 7, 10), bet 3 + 10 = 13
- Each loss adds one number; each win crosses off two numbers
- Only need to win slightly over one-third of time to reach goal
- **Mathematical proof**: No betting system can succeed if all numbers equally
  likely and appear in random order

### Karl Pearson and the French Newspaper Mystery

- **Karl Pearson (1857-1936)**: Discovered exploitable patterns in roulette numbers
  reported daily in French newspaper
- Mystery resolved: reporters simply made up numbers at end of each day rather
  than watching wheels
- Statistical patterns detected reflected failure to invent perfectly random numbers

### Biased Wheels

- **Albert Hibbs (1924-2003) and Roy Walford (1924-2004)**: University of Chicago
  graduate students
- 1947: Found biased wheel in Reno favoring number 9
- Increased $200 stake to $12,000
- 1948: Wheel at Palace Club in Las Vegas — won $30,000
- Took year off, sailed Caribbean
- **Hibbs**: Became director of space science at Caltech's Jet Propulsion Laboratory
- **Walford**: UCLA medical researcher showing caloric restriction in mice could
  more than double maximum life span
- Walford quote: "I wanted to conquer space, and my roommate, Roy Walford, decided
  he would conquer death"

### Feynman's Insight

- **Richard Feynman** told Thorp no way to beat roulette (Hibbs got PhD under
  Feynman at Caltech previous year)
- Biased wheels at big casinos likely thing of past — gambling houses took better
  care of equipment

### Claude Shannon Collaboration (September 1960)

- **Setting**: Last year of Thorp's two-year MIT appointment
- Task: Build computer to beat roulette in nine months
- Everyone else thought physical prediction impossible
- Worked 20 hours/week at **Shannons' three-story wooden house** (dated 1858,
  Mystic Lakes near Cambridge)

### Shannon's Gadgeteer Paradise

- Basement: $100,000 worth of electronic, electrical, mechanical items
- Thousands of components — motors, transistors, switches, pulleys, gears,
  condensers, transformers
- Someone who spent boyhood building and experimenting in electronics, physics,
  chemistry
- "Ultimate gadgeteer"

### Equipment and Setup

- Purchased reconditioned regulation roulette wheel from Reno company ($1,500)
- Borrowed strobe light and large clock with second hand from MIT labs
- Clock dial divided into hundredths of second
- Set up shop in billiard room with massive old slate table as base

### Roulette Wheel Mechanics

- **Stator**: Large stationary piece with circular track around top
- Croupier launches small white ball on track
- Ball gradually slows, falls down sloped conelike inside of stator
- **Rotor**: Circular centerpiece with numbered pockets, spins opposite direction
  to ball launch
- Ball crosses onto rotor after spiraling down stator

### Motion Analysis Strategy

- Motion complicated by several phases
- Divided ball and rotor motion into stages, analyzed each separately
- Began by predicting when/where orbiting ball would leave outer track
- Measured time for one revolution
- Short time = ball moving fast, goes relatively far
- Longer time = ball traveling slower, would soon fall from track

### Timing Mechanism

- **Microswitch**: Hit as ball passed reference mark on stator, started clock
- Second pass stopped clock, showing duration of one revolution
- **Strobe light**: Very short pulses (disco-like) triggered by switch
- Strobe "stopped" ball each time switch hit
- Dimmed room lights so strobe showed how much ball was ahead or behind reference mark
- Corrected recorded times for one revolution, making data more accurate
- Provided numerical measure of errors and visual feedback
- Practice reduced timing errors from ~0.03 second to ~0.01 second
- Retained accuracy later when concealing for casino play with big toes operating
  hidden switches

### Prediction Stages

1. **Predict when/where ball leaves circular track** (high accuracy achieved)
2. **Determine time and distance as ball spirals down stator** — most wheels had
   8 vanes/deflectors ball frequently hit
3. **Ball crosses onto moving rotor, bounces among numbered pockets** — introduces
   final uncertainty

### Error Analysis

- Total prediction error from: imperfect timing, ball spattering on rotor frets,
  deflection by metal obstacles, possible wheel tilt
- **Gaussian distribution assumption**: Total error approximately normally distributed
  (bell curve)
- Needed standard deviation ≤ 16 pockets (0.42 revolution) for edge
- Achieved tighter estimate: **10 pockets (0.26 revolution)**
- **Average profit: 44% of amount bet on forecast number**
- Spreading bet over two closest numbers on each side (5 numbers total) cut risk,
  still had **43% advantage**

### Russian Roulette Analogy

> "Did you ever hear of Russian Roulette?" […] With the Russian army in Romania,
> around 1917, some officer would suddenly pull out his revolver, put a single
> cartridge in the cylinder, spin the cylinder, snap it back in place, put it to
> his head and pull the trigger…

- Physics helps survival in Russian roulette
- Properly lubricated weapon held upright with cylinder parallel to ground: gravity
  causes full chamber to end near bottom
- Relatching shifts odds in player's favor
- Effect of gravity on final resting position varies with gun orientation
- Thorp's daughter (assistant deputy district attorney 2+ decades): Modern forensic
  scientists aware of this

### Shannon's Character and "Degrees of Separation"

- Treasury of intriguing information and ingenious ideas
- Discussing secrecy need, mentioned social network theorists studying rumor/secret spread
- **"Three degrees of separation"** claim: Two random people in US usually connected
  by chain of ≤3 acquaintances
- Test: Ask what famous people they know
- Famous person they know likely shares acquaintance with famous person you know

### Thorp's Test: Train to Princeton

- Well-dressed motherly-looking lady beside him seemed agitated
- Didn't understand English, French, or Spanish but responded to elementary German
- Problem: knowing when to get off in Philadelphia
- **Hungarian economic official** from Budapest on way to meeting
- Thorp played "degrees of separation" game
- "Do you know anyone in Budapest named Sinetar?"
- "Of course. They are a famous family. There's Miklos, the film producer, as
  well as an engineer, and a psychologist."
- "Well, they are relatives of my wife."
- Me → Vivian → Budapest Sinetar → economist seatmate: **Two degrees of separation**
- Never needed more than three to connect with stranger

### Erdős Number

- **John Guare's 1990 play**: Popularized "six degrees of separation"
- Notion well known by 1969 among mathematicians as **Erdős (ERR-dosh) number**
- Linked mathematicians via **Paul Erdős** using "coauthored a paper with" relation
- Coauthored with Erdős = Erdős number one
- Coauthored with someone who had Erdős number one = your number is two, etc.
- Few steps connect strangers, explaining how rumors spread rapidly
- 1998 *New York Times* Science Times article: Mathematicians discovered networks
  might "make a big world small"
- Attributed concept of six degrees to sociologist in 1967
- **All known to Claude Shannon in 1960**

### Shannon's Gadgets and Tricks

- Built ingenious devices — coin flipper landing heads or tails (his choice) after
  specified revolutions
- Cable from workshop to kitchen — finger attached, silently summoned wife Betty
- **Work breaks**: Claude taught Thorp to juggle three balls while riding unicycle
- Steel cable tied between tree stumps — Thorp learned with balance bar
- Shannon's goal: juggle + ride unicycle + balance on tightrope simultaneously
- **Water shoes**: Huge Styrofoam pieces worn like snowshoes to "walketh upon the
  water" (Mystic Lake)
- Neighbors astounded to see Claude moving upright above lake surface
- Thorp tried but found difficult to avoid toppling
- Got along well — science was play for both from early age
- Tinkering and building was fun, curiosity ranged freely

### American Roulette Mathematics

- Wheel has 38 pockets (1-36 red or black, plus green 0 and 00)
- Winning single-number bet pays 35:1
- Without 0 or 00: game would be even (win $35 one time in 36 spins, lose $1
  35 times = no net gain/loss)
- **With 0 and 00**: Average bettor wins $35 once in 38 spins, loses $1 37 times
  = net loss $2 per 38 bets
- **Casino edge**: $2 ÷ $38 = 5.26%
- European roulette typically more generous (single zero only)

### Kelly Strategy for Bet Sizing

- **1956 paper by John Kelly**: Adapted as guide for bets in blackjack, roulette,
  later sports betting and stock market
- Kelly strategy: Worth trading small expected gain for large risk reduction by
  betting on several neighboring numbers rather than single number

### The Wearable Computer Design

- **Computer**: 12 transistors, cigarette-pack size
- Data input: switches hidden in wearer's shoes, operated by big toes
- **Computer forecast transmitted by radio**: Used inexpensive, widely available
  model airplane remote control equipment
- **Bettor wore radio receiver**: Musical tones via tiny loudspeaker in ear canal,
  connected by very thin wires
- Wires stuck on with transparent spirit gum, painted to match skin and hair
- Fragile copper wires (hair diameter) broke constantly
- Claude suggested ultrathin steel wires after hour of telephoning
- Located supplier in Worcester, Massachusetts

### The Musical Tone System

- Croupier spins rotor
- Computer times one rotor revolution, knows future position until croupier pushes again
- Computer sends repeating 8-tone increasing pitched numerical sequence
  (do, re, mi…piano scale)
- Chose to time ball with 3-4 revolutions remaining
- Accurate measurements, 3 revolutions still gave enough time to place bets
- **Timing switch hit when orbiting ball first passed reference mark**: Tone
  sequence shifted and played faster
- When ball clocked after one revolution: tones stopped
- **Last tone heard named group of numbers to bet**
- If timing misjudged revolutions remaining: tones didn't stop, no bets placed
  (camouflage)
- Prediction simultaneous with last input — **compute time was zero**

### Casino Testing (August 1961)

- Claude and Betty, Vivian and Ed in Las Vegas with equipment in adjoining hotel rooms
- Located suitable wheels — machine could beat all seen
- Chose one for next day based on casino ambience
- Dinner and plans for next day
- **Next morning wired up**: Claude wore computer and radio transmitter, operated
  toe switches
- Thorp wore radio receiver with steel wires up neck to ear speaker
- As Claude headed out, cocked head with elfish smile: **"What makes you tick?"**
- Jokingly referring to strange sounds (musical tones) he'd send to Thorp's ear
- Thorp stopped in time, thought about deeper meaning

### The Crossroads Moment

- Could choose between two very different futures:
  1. **Professional gambler**: Roam world winning millions per year, switch between
     blackjack and roulette, camouflage by betting other games with small casino edge
  2. **Academic life**: Path determined by character — *What makes me tick?*
- **Greek philosopher Heraclitus**: "Character is destiny"
- Unfroze time, headed for roulette tables

### First Casino Trial

- Four arrive in casino: Vivian and Betty Shannon strolling and chatting, Claude
  and Ed strangers to them and each other
- Claude lacks casino experience — others nervous but don't show it
- Claude stands by wheel, times ball and rotor, writes down winning number after
  each roll (misdirection — looks like doomed system player)
- Thorp takes seat at far end of layout, distance from both Claude and wheel
- Claude waits for croupier to push rotor
- As green zero passes reference point on stator (ball-deflecting vanes), Claude
  hits silent mercury switch with big toe — contact
- Green 0 comes around again — click
- Elapsed time = one rotation duration
- After second click, 8-tone musical scale begins in Thorp's ear, repeating each
  rotor turn
- Computer knows rotor speed and position relative to stator

### The Betting Process

- Thorp ready to bet
- Croupier launches ball
- Claude watches, clicks when ball has 3-4 revolutions remaining
- Pace of repeating musical scale speeds up
- As ball completes next revolution, Claude's toe hits switch again — *Click!*
- Musical tones stop
- Last tone heard tells Thorp which group of numbers to bet
- Test run: bet 10-cent chips
- Within few spins, computer works magic — few dimes become heap
- Bet each time on group of 5 adjacent numbers ("octants" — 8 groups of 5, with
  0 and 00 appearing twice, totaling 40 numbers on 38-pocket wheel)
- **Voisinage** (French): "neighborhood" — betting groups common in Europe

### Technical Challenges

- Had issues during winning session
- Lady next to Thorp looked over in horror mid-session
- Knowing should leave but not why, raced to restroom
- **Mirror revealed**: Speaker peeking from ear canal like alien insect
- More seriously: frequently turned small dime piles into large ones
- Wire problem prevented moving to large-scale betting
- Steel wires to ear speaker so fine they broke frequently
- Long interruptions returning to rooms for repairs and rewiring
- Computer success demonstrated
- Knew could solve wire problem with larger wires and growing hair to cover ears
  and wire up neck
- Considered persuading reluctant wives to "wire up," concealing under fashionable
  longer hair

### Decision to Abandon the Project

- No one watching had any idea what Claude and Thorp were doing was unusual
- Didn't realize connections among the four
- Even if casinos figured out what they were doing, easy way to stop: say "No
  more bets" before ball spun (instead of waiting until ball almost completed rotations)
- To prevent casinos catching on: would need rehearsed theatrics, disguises,
  misdirection
- Already knew effort required from blackjack experience
- Neither Thorp nor Vivian, Claude, Betty wanted extensive theatrics
- All blackjack publicity made Thorp too conspicuous for unrecognized play for long
- None of the four wanted to spend large amount of time required
- **With ambivalence, put project aside**
- Thorp: "I have always thought it was a good decision"

### Historical Significance

- **MIT Media Lab lists device as first wearable computer**
- Computers worn on body as part of function
- **Late 1961**: Thorp built second wearable computer (knockoff) to predict wheel
  of fortune / money wheel
- Used toe-operated switch for input, speaker for output, single unijunction transistor
- Only one person required
- Matchbox-sized, worked well in casinos
- Game had too little action to conceal spectacular bet consequences
- Several times when placed 40:1 bets while wheel spinning, croupier gave wheel
  extra push

### Public Announcement (1966)

- Publicly announced roulette system in 1966 — clear by then wouldn't exploit it
- Published details later
- Mathematician from UC-Santa Cruz phoned for explanation
- **Eudaemonic Pie group** (UCSC physicists): Used more advanced 1970s technology
  to build own roulette computer
- Like Thorp/Shannon, found 44% advantage
- Like them, frustrated by hardware problems
- Later groups using roulette computers reportedly won large amounts

### Wearable Blackjack Computer Discussion

- Shannon and Thorp discussed building wearable blackjack computer
- Using Thorp's blackjack analysis program, computer could count cards and play
  perfect game
- Could win at up to double rate of best human card counters
- Early instance of computer potentially outplaying any human at game
- Later: computers played perfect checkers, beat world's best at chess, Go, Jeopardy
- Subsequently others built and marketed wearable blackjack computers
- Nevada law initially didn't forbid use
- As hidden computers cut into casino profits, **Nevada devices law passed May
  30, 1985**
- Banned use or possession of any device to predict outcomes, analyze probabilities,
  analyze strategy, or keep track of cards played
- Penalty: fines and imprisonment
- Broadly drawn legislation seems to outlaw palm-sized strategy cards included
  in every copy of *Beat the Dealer*
- 2009: Entrepreneur wrote popular iPhone application to count cards and recommend
  plays for blackjack
- Casinos reminded users it was crime to use at tables

### Correspondence with Shannon

- Corresponded at intervals for few years initially about roulette
- Became increasingly clear didn't want to take it further
- Last letter Thorp remembers: late 1965 or early 1966
- **Recalled stock market discussions triggered by seeing 2^11 (= 2048) on Shannon's
  blackboard**
- Investing goal Shannon contemplating
- Told him in letter about extraordinary stock market method discovered
- Could make 30% per year in small niche
- Given time, could surpass 2^11 figure
- Shannon never said what he thought of this "hubris"
- **Actual rate of profit turned out closer to 20%**

### Final Meeting (1968)

- Met for last time in 1968 at math meeting in San Francisco
- Shannon's poignant last words: **"Let's get together again before we're both
  six feet under"**

### Shannon's Legacy

- After Claude's death (2001), Betty donated many papers and devices to MIT museum
- Roulette computer lent to **Heinz Nixdorf Computer Museum** in Paderborn, Germany
- Spring 2008 exhibit: 35,000 people viewed it in first 8 weeks
- When Claude walked up to Las Vegas roulette wheel (August 1961), using something
  only the four had ever seen
- **World's first wearable computer**
- Name indicates: computer worn by person to fulfill intended function
- Though device had little impact on later developments, wearable computers (Apple
  Watch) everywhere today

### Final Question

- After blackjack and roulette, Thorp wondered: Could other casino games be beaten?

<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## Chapter 10: An Edge at Other Gambling Games

### Move to Las Cruces, New Mexico (1961)

- September 1961: Thorp, Vivian, and Raun moved to Las Cruces after testing the roulette computer in Vegas
- Thorp joined Mathematics Department at **New Mexico State University** (NMSU)
- Las Cruces: 37,000 people, high desert (4,000 feet elevation), near Rio Grande
- Personal milestones: daughter **Karen** born in Las Cruces, son **Jeff** born in nearby El Paso
- Met **Clyde Tombaugh** (1906-97), NMSU professor who discovered Pluto at Lowell Observatory in 1930
- Met **Stanislaw Ulam** (1909-84), legendary mathematician from Manhattan Project
  - Ulam developed crucial ideas for hydrogen bomb (Ulam-Teller concept)
  - Meeting arranged by student **Bill Walden** from Los Alamos

### Analyzing Baccarat

- Thorp noticed **baccarat** in Nevada casinos—James Bond's game in *Casino Royale* and film
- Long played in Europe for high stakes, recently introduced to Vegas in modified form
- Recruited **Bill Walden** (computer scientist interested in applied mathematics) to analyze it
- Goal: determine if card counting methods could beat baccarat (1962 analysis)

#### Baccarat Rules

- Nevada-style dealt from **8 decks** (416 cards total)
- Card values: Aces = 1, 2-9 = face value, 10s/Jacks/Queens/Kings = 10 (only last digit counts)
- Example: 9 + 9 = 18 counts as 8
- Game begins after shuffle with blank "cut card" inserted near end of pack
- Cards placed in wooden **shoe**; first card exposed, value noted, that many cards "burned"
- If 10 or face card exposed, ten cards burned
- Table seats twelve: customers and **shills** (house employees posing as players)
- Two main bets: **Banker** and **Player**

#### Baccarat House Edge Calculations

- Thorp and Walden calculated **first-ever correct house advantage values** for Nevada baccarat
- Banker bet (no card counting): **1.058%** of all bets (1.169% excluding ties)
- Player bet: **1.235%** (1.365% omitting ties)
- Casino edge differs for two bets due to drawing rules and 5% commission on Banker wins
- **Fundamental Theorem of Card Counting**: advantage improves as more cards are seen
  - Best situations come toward end of shoe
  - But opportunities were "tiny and rare" in baccarat

#### Side Bets Discovery

- Baccarat had four side bets beyond main Banker/Player: Banker natural 9, Player natural 9, Banker natural 8, Player natural 8
- **Natural 9**: first two cards total 9, pays 9:1 (winning $1 bet pays $9)
- Non-counters faced terrible house edges: **5.10% for natural 9s, 5.47% for natural 8s**
- Discovered card counting could beat these side bets despite failing on main bets
- Edge varied widely as cards were used
- About one-third through shoe, good opportunities appeared and improved

### Practical Counting System

- Devised system using excess of 9s for natural 9 bet (Player favored)
- **8-rich deck** favored Player natural 8 bet similarly
- Counting harder than blackjack: 416 cards total, tracking unseen cards, 8s, 9s, and 32 total 8s

### Casino Test Team

- Recruited **Ralph Crouch** (Math Department chairman) for casino test
- Ralph: middle height, florid-faced, bubbly, chatty—extreme extrovert
  - "Life of the party," promoted departmental gatherings with "Las Cruces Punch"
  - Punch: huge bowl with 2+ gallons Bacardi rum, frozen orange/pineapple juice, lemonade
- Also recruited Ralph's golfing buddy **Kay Hafen** (university controller)
- Kay: low-key, levelheaded, unflappable
- Both learned to count well; wives Vivian, **Isobel Crouch**, and **Bellamia Hafen** joined for safety monitoring

> "I am often asked what it takes to be a successful card counter. I've found that an academic understanding is not enough. You need to think quickly, be disciplined enough to follow the system, and have a suitable temperament, including the ability to switch your mind into the here and now and stay focused on the cards, the people, and your surroundings."

- Needed "act" or persona to seem like familiar player type to casinos

### First Night at the Dunes (1963 Spring Break)

- Drove to Vegas, arrived at Dunes shortly before 9 PM for baccarat
- Velvet ropes separated raised baccarat alcove from main casino floor
- Imposing table: six chairs at each horseshoe-shaped end
- Female shills already seated when Thorp sat down
- Betting limits: **$5 to $2,000** on main bets, **$5 to $100** on side bets (equivalent to ~10x in 2016)

#### Recognition and Casino Response

- Someone shouted: "There's the guy who wrote the book"
- Baccarat supervisor's eyes popped, ran to phone
- Wife eavesdropping upstairs saw his concern change to "reassurance and then amusement"

> "Beating blackjack is one thing; baccarat is another. Our spy heard, 'Ha, ha. Let him play!' And so play we did."

### Playing the System

- First night: newly shuffled 416-card pack favored house
- Started with $5 minimum Banker bets, tracked numbers
- Set win rate target: **$100 per hour** (low enough to avoid being barred)
- Took ~45 minutes to play through one shoe
- After two shoes, Thorp rested while Ralph and Kay played next one
- Ralph monitored natural 8 bets, Kay counted and bet natural 9s
- When game shut down at usual 3 AM, team ahead **$500-600**

#### Second Night Drama

- Atmosphere changed drastically—crew distant, unfriendly
- Shills behaved strangely: filled all twelve seats on first night, then used rotating strategy
- Previous night: half dozen female shills spread among seats
- Night two: shills on each side remained parked, watching closely
- **"Just one seat left—grab it while you can"** rotating shill tactic
- Each new player drawn to that seat, another shill popped out, leaving exactly one seat empty
- Continued through evening but on second night shills flanking Thorp stayed put
- Thorp had bronchial tickle triggering frequent strident coughs
- Undercover wives amused when shills showed health concern, rebelled, ordered to stay at posts

#### The Asian Lady

- Vivian noted **bleached-blond Asian lady** with long magenta fingernails
- Heavily made up, bejeweled, betting $2,000 limit each hand and losing
- Owned chain of supermarkets, lost one in couple hours
- By 1995 baccarat in Nevada accounted for half as much casino profit as blackjack
- Baccarat table was **25 times as profitable as blackjack table**

### Third Night Hostility

- Game shut down ~3 AM again; Ralph and Kay went to bar for drink
- Pit boss and men from casino examined shoe and eight decks
- Muttering, examining cards one by one for bends, crimps, markings

> "They were muttering and examining the cards one by one, looking for bends, crimps, markings, and any other clues as to how we were winning."

- Third night: obvious hostility from all pit employees
- Conspicuously watched Thorp's every move
- Thorp touched thumb behind ear frequently (as if marking cards with "daub"—invisible Vaseline-like substance)
- Hoped they'd waste time examining every card looking for what wasn't there
- First two evenings: repeatedly offered drinks, chose coffee with cream and sugar
- Third night: war—didn't offer anything; won again

### Fourth Night Drugging Incident

- Fourth night atmosphere changed "drastically"—pit boss and minions smiling, relaxed
- Seemed pleased to see Thorp
- Volunteered "coffee with cream and sugar, just the way you like it"
- Deep into first shoe, happily winning, drinking coffee
- Suddenly couldn't think, couldn't keep count
- Shocked—had managed well through noise, smoke, conversation, high-speed play, excitement, alcoholic beverages
- "Something unexpected had taken place"
- Took chips and left, replaced by Ralph and Kay

#### Recovery

- Wives saw Thorp's pupils "hugely dilated"
- **Bellamia Hafen** (nurse) recognized signs from hospital patients who'd used drugs
- Wanted to collapse but Vivian, Isobel, Bellamia plied him with black coffee
- Walked him for several hours until effects wore off
- Ralph and Kay played through evening until 4 AM; won again

### Fifth Night Water Test

- After discussion, Thorp took seat for game start on night five
- No longer smiling, boys offered coffee with cream and sugar again
- Said: "No thanks. Just bring me a glass of water"
- Group "groaned silently"—took "suspiciously long time" for water
- Carefully put only single drop on tongue

> "Ugh! It tasted as if a box of baking soda had been emptied into the glass. But that single drop was enough to flatten me again."

- Left with numb brain and dilated pupils, repeated black-coffee-and-walking routine
- Ralph and Kay asked to leave permanently, same for all their friends

### Barred at the Sands

- One more baccarat game with side bets: **Sands casino**
- After day of R&R, went with bankroll, took seat at table
- Revised target: $100/hour → **$1,000/hour** (figured Dunes would bar soon anyway)
- After 2.5 hours, ahead $2,500
- **Carl Cohen** (part owner, person in charge) paid table-side visit
- Cohen had previously disciplined **Frank Sinatra** for casino commotion
- When Sinatra persisted, Cohen ensured he didn't return (Sinatra was minor part owner)
- Cohen told Thorp not to play anymore

> "I asked why and he said, 'No reason. We just don't want you to play here.'"

- Accompanied by largest security guard Thorp had yet seen; discussion pointless; left

### Results and Aftermath

- Six nights of play: proven system worked at tables
- Validated theoretical calculations, demonstrated another **Kelly system** application
- Trip had "unnerving postscript"

#### Harrowing Drive Home

- Six people left Vegas next morning driving back to Las Cruces
- Thorp at wheel on northern Arizona mountain road, going 65 mph
- Accelerator pedal suddenly jammed
- Steep downhill, wide-open throttle too much for brakes
- Car sped to 80 mph, turns unmanageable
- Set emergency brake, downshifted for engine braking, cut power by turning off ignition
- Managed to stop in turnout
- **Good Samaritan** who understood cars stopped to help
- Opened hood to see why accelerator jammed
- Found part unscrewed from long threaded rod—"something he had never before seen happen and found baffling"
- Fixed it; continued alive, relieved, sobered

### Impact on Casinos

- Proven system worked like theory predicted
- Both Dunes and Sands **removed natural 8 and 9 side bets** after this trip

## Chapter 11: Wall Street: The Greatest Casino on Earth

### Gambling vs. Investing Connection

> "Gambling is investing simplified. The striking similarities between the two suggested to me that, just as some gambling games could be beaten, it might also be possible to do better than average in the markets."

- Both analyzable using mathematics, statistics, computers
- Each requires money management: proper balance between risk and return
- Betting too much (even with edge) can be ruinous
  - Example: **Long-Term Capital Management** (Nobel Prize winners), collapsed 1998, nearly destabilized US financial system
- Playing safe/betting too little: leave money on table
- Psychological makeup for investing similar to gambling
- Great investors often good at both

### Summer 1964 Self-Education

- Spent summer educating himself about markets
- Haunted Martindale's bookstore in Beverly Hills
- Read classics: **Graham and Dodd's** *Security Analysis*, **Edwards and Magee's** technical analysis work
- Read scores of books/periodicals: fundamental to technical, theoretical to practical, simple to abstruse
- "Like a baleen whale filtering tiny nutritious krill from huge volumes of seawater, I came away with a foundation of knowledge"
- As with casino games, surprised by how little known by so many
- First investment: a loss that contributed to education

### Electric Autolite Investment (Early Mistake)

- Heard about **Electric Autolite** allegedly selling at bargain (automobile batteries for Ford)
- Business page said expect great future: tech innovations, big contracts, sales jump
- (Same forecasts for battery makers made 40 years later)
- Had capital from blackjack and book sales
- Bought 100 shares at $40, watched stock decline over two years to $20
- Lost half of $4,000 investment
- No idea when to sell; decided to hang on until returned to purchase price (avoid taking loss)
- Exactly what gamblers do: play until even
- Took four years but finally got out with original $4,000
- 50 years later, tech stock investors shared experience, waiting 15 years to break even after buying near top (March 10, 2000)

#### Vivian's Analysis of Mistakes

- Discussing Electric Autolite purchase driving home from lunch
- Vivian almost read Thorp's mind:

> "First, you bought something you didn't really understand, so it was no better or worse than throwing a dart into the stock market list. Had you bought a low-load mutual fund [no-load funds weren't available yet] you would have had the same expected gain but less expected risk."

- Story about Electric Autolite meant it was superior investment—that thinking was wrong
- Most stock-picking stories, advice, recommendations are "completely worthless"

> "Then Vivian remarked on my second mistake in thinking, my plan for getting out, which was to wait until I was even again."

- Focused on price of unique historical significance to him only (purchase price)
- **Behavioral finance theorists** call this **anchoring**: attaching yourself to price with meaning to you but not market
- Had no predictive power; any exit strategy as good or bad as any other
- Error in thinking about when to sell: choosing irrelevant criterion (price paid) rather than economic fundamentals

### Anchoring Examples

#### Mr. Davis House Story

- Former neighbor saw market value rise from $2M purchase (mid-1980s) to $3.5M peak (1988-89)
- Decided to sell, anchored to $3.5M price
- Next ten years: house fell back to $2.2M, kept trying to sell at "now laughable anchor price"
- 2000: resurgent stock market, dot-com price rise in expensive homes, escaped at $3.25M
- Thinking error of anchoring left him with "substantially less money" than if acted otherwise

#### Mr. Davis Investment Story

- Jogged together occasionally, talked about money and investments
- Following Thorp's recommendation, joined limited partnership allocating to hedge funds
- Expected ~10% annual return after taxes, more stability than real estate or stocks
- Thorp advised: sell house at current market after 1988-89 peak
- Should have received ~$3.3M, moved to $1M house
- After costs and taxes: additional $1.6M to invest
- Money in hedge fund at 10%/year for 11 years → $4,565,000
- Add $1M house (market price would have declined then recovered) = **$5,565,000 in 2000**
- Instead ended with $3,250,000 due to anchoring

#### Traffic Anchoring Example

- Driving home in heavy traffic, SUV forced its way in front
- Choice: yield ("maintain my rights") or fender bender
- Receives such invitations daily, saw no need to accept "for fear I would miss out"
- SUV in "my" space (anchoring to abstract moving location with unique historical meaning)
- Allowing it to dictate driving behavior
- Lined up ~70 cars deep in "most notoriously slow left-turn lane in Newport Beach"
- Road usually two lanes, construction narrowed to one
- Complex light sequence allowed ~20 cars through each two-minute cycle
- What if evil SUV last one through yellow when finally got to signal?
- "My" space justified risking accident by rolling through red?
- Temptation may sound foolish in cold print, but "I see this kind of behavior regularly"

> "Having learned the folly of anchoring from my investment experience, I have seen that it can be equally foolish on the road. Being a more rational investor has made me a more rational driver!"

### Life Insurance Investment Failure

- Two "expert" longtime insurance investors from Dallas drew him into next market adventure
- Claimed to have become rich investing in life insurance companies
- **A. M. Best AAA index** of average price: gone up each of last 24 years
- Had plausible arguments trend would continue
- "Amazing winning streak" identified ended just after Thorp's purchase
- All lost money
- **Lesson**: Don't assume momentum (long streak of rising or falling prices) will continue unless sound case

### Charting and Technical Analysis

- Thinking about momentum: wondered if past prices could predict future prices
- Looked at **charting**: using patterns in stock/commodity price graphs to forecast changes
- Introduced by **Norman**, Canadian resident in Las Cruces while teaching at NMSU
- After months examining data and predictions, unable to find anything of value
- Vivian's prediction:

> "This is going to be a waste of time. Norman's been doing this for years and you can tell he's barely getting by. Just look at his worn-out shoes and shabby clothes. And you can tell from the quality of his wife's old and dated outfits that they were once better off."

### Mr. Market Introduction

- Still owed tuition to **Mr. Market** for introductory course in investment mistakes
- Mr. Market: allegorical character introduced by **Benjamin Graham**
- Illustrates excessive market price swings above/below actual underlying business values
- Some days manic (prices high), other days gloomy (shares bought well below "intrinsic value")

#### Silver Investment (Early 1960s)

- Demand for silver exceeding supply; expected prices to spurt sharply
- Silver extracted from melting everyday coins eventually expected to exceed face value (enough to pay costs and profit)
- **Bill Rickenbacker** (backed blackjack trip with Mickey MacDougall and Russell Barnhart) had purchased US silver dollars, stored in vault
- Further price rise would slow as new supply came from melting coins
- Five billion ounces of silver potentially extractable from vast pool of jewelry in India
- Once demand absorbed new supplies, prices would jump even more
- When silver passed $1.29/ounce, US coins with 90% silver worth more as metal than legal tender
- Coins skimmed from circulation, melted to extract silver
- After US government banned this, coins hoarded, bought/sold in 60-pound bags via dealers

#### Leveraged Silver Purchase

- Believing economic supply/demand analysis correct, opened Swiss bank account to buy silver
- With help/encouragement of local promoters (got commission)
- Recommended doing on **33⅓% collateral** (each dollar's worth silver bought, deposit only 33⅓ cents)
- Promoters arranged for friendly Swiss bank to loan the rest
- Borrowed to buy 3x as much silver as could with cash alone (triple commissions for promoters, bank happy collecting interest + monthly storage fees)

#### Silver Collapse

- Silver rose as predicted; promoters recommended using profits + more bank loans for yet more silver
- When commodity reached $2.40/ounce, account had lot more metal than when started
- Had large profit on all early purchases
- Reinvested profits on way up; $1.60 of $2.40/ounce owed on loan from bank (like buying house one-third down)
- Price of silver dropped
- Some people sold to capture profit, drove price further down
- Others borrowed to even greater extent, sold out by lenders as accounts threatened to go underwater (not enough left to pay loan)
- Sales pushed price down more, forcing more sales by remaining borrowers
- Silver drop rapidly to little below $1.60 (just enough to wipe Thorp out)
- Resumed upward path

> "I learned from this that even though I was right in my economic analysis I hadn't properly evaluated the risk of too much leverage. For a few thousand dollars I learned from this to make proper risk management a major theme of my life for more than fifty years thereafter. In 2008 almost the entire world financial establishment didn't understand this lesson and had overleveraged itself."

- Also learned: when salesmen/promoters' interests differ from client's, client better look out for himself
- **Agency problem in economics**: interest of agents/managers don't coincide with principals/owners
- Shareholders of companies pillaged by self-serving CEOs/boards painfully familiar

> "After these lessons from Mr. Market, I was tempted to believe that the academics were right in claiming that any edge in the markets is limited, small, temporary, and quickly captured by the smartest or best-informed investors. Once again, I was invited to accept the consensus opinion at face value, and once again I decided to see for myself."

### Discovery of Warrants (June 1965)

- Began second summer of self-education in economics, finance, markets
- Thin pamphlet on **common stock purchase warrants** arrived in mail—revelation
- **Warrant**: security issued by company giving owner right to buy stock at specified price (exercise price) on or before stated expiration date
- Example: 1964 **Sperry Rand warrant** entitled holder to purchase one share common stock for $28 until September 15, 1967
- Final day: if stock trades above that price, use one warrant + $28 to buy one share
- Warrant worth amount by which stock price exceeds $28
- If stock price below $28, cheaper to buy stock outright (warrant worthless)

#### Warrant as Lottery Ticket

- Like lottery ticket: always worth something before expiration if any chance stock price could move above exercise price and put warrant "into the money"
- More time left, higher stock price, more warrant likely worth
- Prices of two securities followed simple relationship regardless of balance sheet/business complexities
- Formed rough idea of rules relating warrant price to stock price
- Important idea of **"hedging"** occurred: use relationship to exploit mispricing while simultaneously reducing risk

### Hedging Concept

- **Hedge**: take two securities whose prices tend to move together (warrant and purchasable common stock), comparatively mispriced
- Buy relatively underpriced security, sell short relatively overpriced security
- If proportions chosen well, gains and losses on two sides approximately offset or **hedge** each other even as prices fluctuate
- If relative mispricing disappears as expected, close position in both, collect profit

### Move to UC Irvine (1965)

- Days after warrant idea, packed possessions, moved from NMSU to Southern California
- Became founding faculty member Mathematics Department, new Irvine campus, **University of California (UCI)**
- Four years Las Cruces: learned much more mathematics, directed PhD dissertations, published research as professional articles
- Wanted to be in Southern California: children see grandparents/siblings/families, near old friends
- Liked that UCI purposely starting out emphasizing collaboration between faculty/students from different subject areas

### Meeting Sheen Kassouf (September 1965)

- First day new teaching position UCI
- **Julian Feldman** (head school information and computer sciences) asked what Thorp working on
- Described ideas about warrant valuation and hedging
- Said another new faculty member, economist **Sheen Kassouf** (1928-2005), written PhD thesis on subject
- Feldman introduced them
- Kassouf discovered same concepts in 1962, already shorting overpriced warrants and hedging
- Doubled initial $100,000 in just three years

#### Collaboration on Theory and Practice

- Realized working together could develop theory and techniques for hedged investment more rapidly than alone
- Weekly meetings: roughly determined fair price for warrant, finding quite a few substantially overpriced
- Way to profit: **sell them short**
- To sell security short: borrow desired quantity through broker from someone who owns it, sell in marketplace, collect proceeds
- Later repurchase at whatever price prevails to meet contractual obligation to return what borrowed
- Win if buy-back price below earlier sale price; lose if higher

#### Risk Management Through Hedging

- Short selling overpriced warrants profitable on average but risky
- Same for buying stocks
- Two risks largely canceled when hedged warrants by purchasing associated common stock
- Historical simulation: optimized method made **25% per year with low risk**, even during 1929 crash and aftermath
- While working on theory, Kassouf and Thorp investing for themselves in warrant hedges (also made 25%/year)

### Publishing *Beat the Market* (1967)

- Explained methods for investing, presented actual results from hedges
- Finished late 1966, published Random House 1967
- Extended approach to include much larger area of **convertible bonds**
- Willing to share discoveries publicly for several reasons:
  - Awareness others would make same discoveries eventually
  - Scientific research ought to be public good
  - Would continue to have more ideas

#### End of Collaboration with Kassouf

- Somewhat different ideas about setting up hedged investments
- Ended collaboration after finishing *Beat the Market*
- As economist, Kassouf felt understood companies well enough to deviate from neutral hedge
- **Neutral hedge**: balanced protection against loss whether market moves up or down
- Kassouf willing to modify, short proportions in hedge to favor rise or fall in underlying stock price depending on analysis
- Given Thorp's bad experiences picking stocks, lack of background analyzing companies, wanted hedges as protected as possible against stock price changes (no matter which direction)
- Continued to work on theory and invest on own

### Theoretical Breakthrough (1967)

- Major breakthrough came in 1967
- Used **Occam's razor**: given more than one explanation, begin by choosing simplest one
- Plausible reasoning to arrive at neat formula for determining "correct" price of warrant
- Armed with this, could tell when mispriced and by roughly how much
- Same year began using formula to hedge over-the-counter warrants, options, and later convertible bonds
- **Option** to buy stock similar to warrant (principal difference: warrants typically issued by company itself, options not)
- **Convertible bonds**: like ordinary bonds but with additional feature they can be exchanged for fixed number of issuing company's stock shares if holder desires

#### Increased Confidence and Returns

- Formula further increased confidence and returns
- Available investment opportunities much larger than could exploit with modest capital
- Led to next step: began to manage hedged portfolios for friends and acquaintances
<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## Meeting Warren Buffett

### The Gerards' Introduction (1968)
- **Ralph and Frosty Gerard** moved money from Buffett (24% returns) to Thorp (20% expected)
- Buffett was liquidating his partnership after the 1967 market spike
- Large-cap stocks gained 38% over two years, small-caps up 150%
- Buffett said it was "too tough to find undervalued companies"
- Investors could take distribution as cash or shares in **Berkshire Hathaway** textile company
- Buffett himself owned $25M of the $100M partnership from management fees

### Dinner at the Buffetts' (Summer 1968)
- Gerards invited Thorp and Vivian to dinner with **Susie and Warren Buffett**
- Newport Beach home overlooking harbor and ocean
- Ralph wanted to check Thorp out and get Buffett's reading

### Warren's Investment Philosophy
- **"Be fearful when others are greedy and greedy when others are fearful"**
- Focus on buying undervalued companies with ample margin of safety
- Goal: outperform market in the long run by regularly beating it during fluctuations
- Expected each investment to substantially outperform indices (DJIA, S&P 500)
- Like mentor **Ben Graham**, invested in warrant/convertible hedging and merger arbitrage
- Shared overlap with Thorp in this area—Buffett was vetting Thorp as possible successor

### Contrasting Investment Approaches
- **Buffett**: Evaluated businesses, bought shares cheaply with margin of safety for unknown/unanticipated
- Opportunities arose when investors became excessively pessimistic about company or stocks generally
- Judged himself largely on performance relative to the market
- **Thorp**: Didn't judge business worth—compared different securities of same company
- Found relative mispricing to construct hedged positions
- Long undervalued, short overvalued—extracted positive return despite market ups/downs
- Didn't mind substantial market price variations because long-run belief in market strength
- Goal: accumulate the most money

> "I enjoyed using mathematics to solve certain interesting puzzles, which I found first in the world of gambling, then in the world of investing. Making money confirmed my theories by showing that they worked in the real world."

### The Nontransitive Dice Puzzle
- Warren showed Thorp **oddly numbered dice** with nontransitive properties
- Three dice where no single die is "best"—each can be beaten by another
- Example: A beats B, B beats C, but C beats A
- **Violates the transitive rule**: if A > B and B > C, then A should be > C
- Rock-Paper-Scissors is a nontransitive game
- Solution: A = (3,3,3,3,3,3), B = (6,5,2,2,2,2), C = (4,4,4,4,1,1)
- A beats B 2/3 of time, B beats C 5/9 of time, C beats A 2/3 of time

### Voting and Arrow's Theorem
- Nontransitive preferences have practical impact in elections
- Example: Majority prefers A over B, B over C, C over A—who wins?
- **Kenneth Arrow** won Nobel Prize in Economics for showing no voting procedure satisfies all intuitively natural desirable properties
- Article in *Discover* magazine argued with "more reasonable" election procedure based on voter comparisons, **John McCain** would have won 2000 Republican nomination and presidency instead of **George W. Bush**

### Bridge and Market Parallels
- Thorp wondered if bidding systems at bridge were like nontransitive dice
- Could there be no "best" system—each beaten by another in endless cycle?
- Computers could potentially solve this by playing large numbers of hands with various systems
- If no best system exists, best strategy: ask opponents to disclose their system, choose most lethal counter
- **Bridge is a game of imperfect information**—bidding precedes play, players infer from cards seen
- The stock market also is a game of imperfect information with deceptions
- Better in the market to get more information sooner and put it to better use

> "It's no surprise that Buffett, arguably the greatest investor in history, is a bridge addict."

### California Politics: Proposition 13
- Buffett's Emerald Bay house became newsworthy during **Arnold Schwarzenegger's** 2003 governor campaign
- Buffett was supporter and economic adviser initially
- Campaign issue: how to cut California's budget deficit
- Problem caused partly by **Proposition 13** (1978)—anti-tax measure
- Limited real estate tax to 1% of assessed valuation with 2% annual revaluation cap
- Houses that weren't traded fell to small fraction of 1% of current value
- Tax base eroded, budget deficit expanded
- Houses reassessed at current market price only when sold
- Created major inequities—comparable houses paid vastly different taxes depending on ownership timing

### Schwarzenegger's Tax Dilemma
- Buffett publicly advised Schwarzenegger to shift to fair, equitable property tax
- Pointed out Proposition 13 made his Emerald Bay house tax (worth several million) substantially less than his Omaha house ($700,000)
- Governor-to-be said: **"I told Warren that if he mentions Proposition 13 again he has to do five hundred sit-ups"**
- Warren quietly discontinued advising Schwarzenegger

### Bridging Bridge and Bidding Systems
- Thorp reflected on parallels between nontransitive dice and bridge bidding systems
- Could inventors of "better" bidding systems be chasing tails forever?
- Only beaten by still newer systems, which might lose to old previously discarded ones
- Answer might come when computers can play bridge and bid at expert level
- Test by playing large numbers of hands, pitting various bidding systems against each other

## First Meetings with Future Partners

### Thorp's Prediction About Buffett
- Thorp told Vivian he believed Buffett would eventually become richest man in America
- Extraordinarily smart evaluator of underpriced companies
- Could compound money much faster than average investor
- Could continue to rely mainly on his own talent as capital grew enormous
- Understood power of compound interest, planned to apply it over long time

### The Prediction Fulfilled
- Came true for a few months in 1993—Buffett was richest in world
- Passed by **Bill Gates** and later other dot-commers
- Regained world's top spot in 2007, traded places with bridge buddy Gates in 2008
- By then, time with Warren had become commodity of great value
- Asian investor bid $2 million (to be donated to charity) for privilege of lunch with him on eBay

### Thorp's Investment Model
- **Ralph Gerard** gave Thorp copies of Buffett's letters to partners and partnership documents
- Simple two-page affair showed ideal plan: pool investing in single limited partnership like Warren had done
- At the time, Thorp managed about $400,000
- At 25% per year, accounts were grossing $100,000
- Performance fee was 20% of profits = $20,000/year earning rate, roughly same as professor salary
- Pooling assets into single account allowed managing more with less effort
- Particular warrant hedge only had to be set up and managed once, not replicated individually

### Jay Regan's Call (1969)
- Young stockbroker in New York named **Jay Regan** read *Beat the Market*
- Wanted to get into investing business using limited partnership to implement convertible hedging
- Thought he could handle business aspects while Thorp focused on investments and research
- Met at Thorp's UCI Math Department office

### Partnership Formation
- Regan: twenty-seven years old, medium height, thinning reddish hair, freckles, social skills of promoter
- Dartmouth graduate in philosophy, quickly understood investment principles
- Natural team: Thorp would generate ideas, Regan would bring suggestions from "the Street"
- Thorp would do analysis and compute orders, Regan would execute through brokers
- Regan to handle taxes, accounting, most legal and regulatory paperwork
- Thorp could focus on research and development

### Creating the Partnership
- Agreed to create and manage together new investment partnership based on *Beat the Market* ideas
- Newport Beach = think tank and trade generator
- New York = business office and trading desk
- Set $5 million as target capital to start
- If made 20% net of expenses and charged 20% of that as performance fee: 4% of $5M = $200,000
- More than Thorp's remuneration as professor of mathematics

### Hedge Fund Structure
- Example of what became known as **hedge fund**
- Private limited partnership managed by one or more general partners (each risks loss of entire net worth)
- Group of investors = limited partners, whose loss is limited to amount they commit
- Investors primarily passive, no role in management or investments
- At the time, lightly regulated if no more than ninety-nine partners and didn't solicit general public
- Offshore hedge funds could be structured as corporations or trusts

### Historical Context of Hedge Funds
- Not a new concept—**Jerome Newman** and **Benjamin Graham** started one as early as 1936
- Under skilled managers whose interests aligned with investors, incentive of profit sharing
- Investors hoped for substantially better returns
- Name *hedge fund* probably came from journalist **Alfred Winslow Jones**
- Jones researched article on investments, started partnership in 1949
- Bought stocks he believed were cheap, attempted to hedge risk by shorting shares believed overpriced
- Short seller profits if price falls, loses if price rises
- Potentially more stable returns in down market

### Jones's Fame
- Idea didn't receive wide attention until 1966 *Fortune* article by **Carol Loomis**
- **"The Jones Nobody Keeps Up With"** announced Jones's hedge fund had beaten all several hundred mutual funds over last ten years
- Possibilities became widely apparent

### Launching in a Down Market (1969)
- Finding investors would not be easy
- 1967-68 had been manic two years for markets and few existing hedge funds
- 1969 was major downer:
  - Large-company stocks lost average of 9%
  - Small-company stocks crushed by alarming 25%
- Most hedge funds suffered severe losses and were closing down
- Explained they were to be market-neutral and hedged, thus protecting principal
- Ideas were new and people were scared

### Initial Capital Raising
- Finally signed up fourteen limited partners plus themselves, each for $50,000 or more
- Thorp's individual investors were among first partners
- Regan found more money by going to courthouse, getting lists of limited partners from documents filed by other hedge funds, cold calling
- Thorp flew to New York to meet prospects, explain methods, add cachet with books and academic position
- By late October had managed to get only $1.4 million in commitments
- Decided to move ahead anyway—would simply grow through profits, attract more capital later from current and new investors

### Official Launch
- **Convertible Hedge Associates** (later renamed **Princeton Newport Partners**) opened bicoastal doors Monday, November 3, 1969
- Article in *Wall Street Letter* announced start, setting it in context of that year's widespread market rout and closing down of several hedge funds

> MONEY ON THE MOVE. As some hedge funds break up in the aftermath of sour performances this year, new investment partnerships continue to be formed. One of the newest is Convertible Hedge Associates, whose general partners are Ed Thorp and Jay Regan. Thorp is the fellow who developed a computerized system for beating the blackjack tables in Las Vegas, before they changed the rules on him, and wrote the book *Beat the Dealer*. He's turned his computer talents to money management and has a book out called *Beat the Market*. Regan has been with Butcher & Sherrerd, Kidder, Peabody and White, Weld. Among their limited partners are Dick Salomon, chairman of Lanvin-Charles of the Ritz; Charlie Evans (formerly of Evan-Picone) and Bob Evans (Paramount Pictures), and Don Kouri, president of Reynolds Foods, Ltd.

### Early Results
- First two months of operation: 4% profit = $56,000
- S&P 500 Index down 5% in same two months
- Thorp's $5,600 share of general partner's fee exceeded university income for same period

### The Crossroad Decision
- Clear Thorp was at crossroad
- Could use mathematical skills to develop strategies for hedging and possibly become rich
- Or could compete in academic world for advancement and distinction
- Loved university-level teaching and research, decided to stay as long as he could
- Best quantitative financial ideas would be saved for investors, not published
- Over time would be rediscovered by and credited to others

### Buffett's Endorsement
- Buffett's report on Thorp to Gerards must have been favorable
- They joined and their trust fund retained investment in partnership until after deaths of Ralph and then Frosty
- Time spent with Buffett had two major effects: helped move Thorp along path to own hedge fund
- Later led to very profitable investment in company Buffett transformed: **Berkshire Hathaway**

