## Chapter 22: Hedging Your Bets

### The 2008 Financial Crisis

- Hedging supposedly protects against catastrophic losses
- **2008 recession**: Many hedge fund investors lost heavily
- Worse than any downturn since Great Depression
- Housing prices tumbled, **S&P 500 fell 57%** (October 2007-March 2009)
- **US private wealth declined** from $64 trillion to $51 trillion
- Small investors (Thorp's niece, house cleaner) watching equity index funds
  in IRAs plunge asked if they should dump stocks
- Many investors had to sell, including wealthiest university endowment
  (**Harvard**: $36.9B early 2008, now desperate for cash)

### Hedge Fund Performance in 2008

- Hedge funds dropped average **18%**
- **James Simons** of **Renaissance Technologies** (most highly compensated
  manager) made $2.5 billion
- Top twenty-five managers collected $11.6B (down from $22.5B in 2007)

### Hedge Fund Industry Growth (1988-2008)

- Twenty years after Princeton Newport Partners ended
- Hedge funds proliferated: ten thousand worldwide
- Total equity estimated **$2 trillion**
- Worldwide pool of wealthy investors: mix of private individuals, trusts,
  corporations, pension/profit-sharing plans, foundations, endowments
- **2008 crash dealt massive blow**: $400 billion swept away
- Triggered worldwide withdrawal requests by angered investors (losses weren't
  supposed to happen)
- Shocked when many funds refused to return remaining money

### Recovery & Growth by 2015

- Economy slowly recovered, market bounced to new highs
- Investors forgot 2008-09 experience
- **By 2015**: Hedge fund assets reached new high of **$2.9 trillion**
- **Management fees**: 1.5-2% annually
- **Performance fees**: Perhaps another $50B (20% of profits after charges)
- $50B in performance fees supposedly represents 20% of profits after all
  other charges
- **But investors pay larger percentage as group**

### Fee Math Example

- Two funds start year at $1B each
- One nets $300M, other loses $100M
- At 20% of profits: first fund collects $60M performance fee, second collects
  none
- Pooling results: investors pay **$60M on $200M profit** = 30% of combined
  gains and losses

### The Funding Challenge Era (Late 1990s Onward)

- With Princeton Newport, growth from new capital came slowly, earned by
  performance
- Over forty years, battle for funding changed dramatically
- **"Alternative investments"** became hottest new frontier
- Beginning late 1990s: could put up sign saying HEDGE FUND OPENING HERE

> "...a line of investors would quickly extend around the block."

### Typical Fee Economics ($100M Fund Example)

- $100M fund earning 10% gross return ($10M)
- Management fee: 1% of $100M = $1M
- Performance fee: 20% of remaining $9M profit = $1.8M
- Total to manager: $2.8M/year
- Expenses (perhaps $1M): net $1.8M/year pretax income
- Limited partners: remaining $7.2M for 7.2% annual return

### Scale Economics

- General partners in billion-dollar fund might share **ten times as much**
  ($28M/year)
- Even little $10M hedge fund: single general partner with $280,000/year
- "It's clear from this that you can get very rich running a hedge fund"
- With these rewards, shouldn't be surprised to find many of the best investors
  running hedge funds

### Hedge Fund Return Reality

- Consensus of industry studies: considering risk level, hedge funds **once**
  gave investors extra return
- **Faded as industry expanded**
- Later analyses: average results worse than underprayed
- **Funds voluntarily report results** to industry databases
- Winners tend to participate much more than losers
- One study: **doubled reported average annual return** from actual 6.3%
  (1996-2014) to supposed 12.6%

### Return Weighting Distortion

- If returns weighted by dollars invested, returns are **"only marginally
  higher than risk-free [US Treasury Bonds] rates of return"**
- Industry reports combine higher-percentage returns from earlier years (when
  total invested smaller) with lower-percentage returns later (when managing
  much more money)

### Stock Picking Difficulty Applies to Hedge Funds

> "It's difficult to get an edge picking stocks. Hedge funds are little
> businesses just like companies that trade on the exchanges. Should one be
> any better at picking hedge funds than we are at picking stocks?"

### Major Hedge Fund Disasters

**Julian Robertson / Tiger Fund (Spring 2000)**:
- One of biggest hedge fund collections in world
- Included flagship Tiger Fund
- Small beginnings 1980 → $22B before demise
- At end: market losses + investor withdrawals chopped pool to $7B (more
  withdrawals pending)
- Robertson claimed to be value investor, blamed irrational crazed high-tech
  markets

> "The fault is not in our markets, but in ourselves..." — Shakespeare
> (adapted)

**George Soros / Quantum Fund (Months Later)**:
- Another of world's biggest hedge fund groups
- Announced heavy losses, followed by withdrawal of most investor funds
- Drastically downsized from peak over $20B
- Operation restructured and converted into vehicle to manage his own money
- **Stanley Druckenmiller** (Soros's principal associate) had taken opposite
  posture to Robertson: bet on tech stocks
- **Van Hedge Fund Advisors** article "Good Year for Hedge Funds": Preceding
  year 1999 was best for their index since 1988 start
  - +40.6% United States
  - +37.6% offshore
- Soros later resurged; 2008 personally made $1.1B (only fourth place among
  hedge fund managers that year)

### Should You Invest in Hedge Funds?

**Determine if economically qualified**:
- Typically require **minimum $250,000** investment or more
- Start-ups sometimes relax to $50,000-$100,000 when first raising money
- Historical reason: To qualify for securities regulation exemptions (freedom
  to make wide range of investments), had to limit to fewer than one hundred
  partners
- To have pool of tens/hundreds of millions, fund had to avoid filling quota
  with small investors

**SEC later raised limit to 500 partners** in certain circumstances

**Accredited investor requirement**:
- Many hedge funds only admit accredited investors
- For individuals: jointly with spouse have **net worth of at least $1 million**
  OR income of at least $200,000 in each of last two years (expect to repeat
  in current year)
- Leaves plenty of candidates: 2013, among 100+ million US households, number
  with net worth $1M+ estimated between five and eight million

### Knowledge & Due Diligence Requirement

- Must be knowledgeable enough (you or agent you choose) to evaluate
- **$65 billion Ponzi scheme** by **Bernard Madoff**: Thirteen thousand
  investors and advisers didn't do elementary due diligence (thought other
  investors must have done it)
- Same issue as for stocks/bonds/mutual funds
- **Need to make convincing, reasoned case** for why proposed investment is
  better than standard passive investments (stock/bond index funds)
- Using this test, likely will rarely find investments qualifying as superior
  to indexes

### Tax Issues

- **US domestic hedge funds** (like most active investment programs) are
  **tax-inefficient**
- High turnover tends to produce short-term capital gains/losses taxed at
  higher rate than securities owned >1 year

**For tax-exempt investors**:
- US hedge funds that borrow money (not their clones based outside US) trigger
  taxes
- Otherwise tax-exempt entity must pay taxes on realized gains, losses, and
  income generated by loans
- Called **unrelated business taxable income (UBTI)**

### Evaluating Hedge Funds by Strategy

**If you have area of expertise**, look for funds your knowledge can help
evaluate:
- Hedge fund data services list 1,000+ funds from several thousand that exist
- Internet sources (Wikipedia) classify by asset types
- Sort by methodology: **fundamental** (using economic data) vs. **technical**
  (price/volume data only) vs. **quantitative** (computers/algorithms) vs.
  **non-quantitative**
- **Bottom-up** (analyzing individual companies) vs. **top-down** (focusing
  on broader economic variables)

### Important Fund Characteristics

- Fund's expected returns, risks
- How payoffs correlate with those from other asset classes
- Returns from funds exploiting trends in commodity futures prices often **not
  significantly correlated with market** — useful in reducing overall portfolio
  fluctuations
- Equity long-only, short-only, long/short funds
- **Market-neutral funds** (like PNP and Ridgeline) attempt returns
  uncorrelated with market
- Funds may specialize by: geographic area, country's financial/economic
  development level (emerging markets), economic sector (biotechnology, gold,
  oil, real estate)

### Fund of Funds

- **"Fund of funds"**: Hedge fund that invests in portfolio of other hedge
  funds
- The way mutual funds invest in collection of stocks
- Management in business of evaluating hedge funds
- In addition to what hedge funds charge directly, fund of funds manager
  collects **second layer of fees** (typically 1% per year + 10% of profits)

---

<!-- pp. 261-280 -->

## Hedge Fund Deception Tactics (continued from Chapter 22)

### Salting the Mine

- **"Salting the mine"** scheme: fund managers launch funds with small
capital, stuff with hot IPOs from brokers, establish stellar track record
while closed to public
- Once track record proven, open to public → flood of capital → managers
reap huge fees
- Brokers rewarded with additional business from triumphant new fund
- Problem: available volume of hot IPOs too small to help returns once
fund gets big, so track record declines to mediocrity
- Fund promoters can use more hot IPOs to incubate yet another
spectacularly performing new fund — cycle continues
- **SEC finally acted in 1999** — first time firing a well-known fund
manager for this game
- Manager's growth fund had only a few hundred thousand dollars in 1996,
got more than half its 62% first-year gain from thirty-one hot IPOs
- Opened to public in February 1997 to flood of money, failed to disclose
IPO inflation of track record

### Other Paths to Mediocrity

- Besides salting the mine, many reasons for decline to mediocrity
- Managers need decent initial record or extensive case based on prior
reputation/business plan
- Some managers simply lucky when starting — e.g., "growth fund" in late
1990s buying AOL or Amazon
- With time, lucky managers tend to fade

### "Heads We Win, Tails You Lose"

- Hedge fund operators have ways of ending up with far more than the 20%
management fee
- Thorp interviewed wealthy hedge fund manager in 1986 about investing in
his fund of hedge funds (OSM Partners)
- Manager invited Thorp to leave PNP, bring expertise and employees, join
him — would get half the management fee on much larger pool
- Following year: **October 1987 crash** hit manager's funds with 30-70%
losses
- Performance fees wouldn't be paid again until losses recovered — could
take years
- Facing no performance fees for years, manager chose to **terminate his
hedge funds**, leaving himself rich and investors with losses
- Net result: manager made off with all the profits
- Less than a year later, launched fresh set of hedge funds from which he
could immediately collect performance fees

> "The net result was that he made off with all the profits."

### Cherry-Picking

- **Cherry-picking**: another way hedge fund managers milk limited
partners
- Thorp first encountered this in late 1970s — lackluster decade for
equities
- Manager had been picking undervalued companies, making 20% or so per
year before his fee
- After friends recommended investment, Thorp did digging and learned
manager had another pool making 40% — just for himself, family, and close
friends
- That pool got its fill of the best situations, rest went to the 20%
pool
- **Hedge fund documents** drawn up by lawyers hired by general partner
typically permit these conflicts of interest

### Improper Expense Charging

- Another way limited partners get less than they should: improper expense
charging
- Thorp's point: hedge fund investors don't have much protection
- Most important thing to check before investing: **honesty, ethics, and
character of the operators**

## Long-Term Capital Management (LTCM)

### The Dream Team

- **Launched in 1994** with dream team of sixteen general partners
- Led by legendary former **Salomon Brothers** trader **John Meriwether**
- Two future (1997) **Nobel Prize winners**: **Robert Merton** and
**Myron Scholes**
- Included other former Salomon traders, distinguished academics, former
Federal Reserve vice chairman
- Investors included central banks of eight countries, plus major
brokerages, banks, other institutions

### Thorp's Declination

- Principals of financial engineering group Thorp knew were working for
LTCM, asked if he had interest in investing
- **Thorp declined** — Meriwether had history at Salomon of being major
risk taker
- Partnership's theorists were lacking in "street smarts" and practical
investment experience
- **Warren Buffett** says: "Only swing at the fat pitches." This did not
look like a fat pitch

### The Collapse

- Annual percentage return to LTCM investors was in 30s and 40s, but based
on **enormous leverage**
- Leverage reportedly varying between **30:1 and 100:1**
- Without leverage, returns would be just a fraction of a percent over
cost of money
- Had hundreds of billions long and hundreds of billions short
- Expanded to **$7 billion in capital** before giving back $2.7 billion —
increased both risk and return on remaining capital
- When adverse market conditions created small losses in percentage terms,
leverage magnified impact and nearly wiped them out
- After losing **90% of capital in weeks**, total ruin imminent
- Fact that they were **"too big to fail"** led to rescue effort
encouraged by Federal Reserve
- Fund liquidated in orderly fashion, investors recovered small percentage
of stake

### The Aftermath

- Not long after, Meriwether and four others of the sixteen partners
started new hedge fund similar to LTCM, using less leverage
- **Scholes and Merton** chose not to join him again
- Investors, including some losers from LTCM, soon put up $350 million
- Growth and new capital increased it further
- His "flagship" fund reported to have ended 2008 down 42%, losing more
than $300 million, closed in 2009
- In 2010 Meriwether started yet another hedge fund
- Merton became consultant to **J. P. Morgan & Co.**, retained teaching
position at Harvard
- Scholes returned to faculty position at Stanford, became financial
consultant, later launched another hedge fund

### Lessons Ignored

> "The lessons we should have learned about excess leverage from the
> collapse of Long-Term Capital Management were ignored."

- Ten years later, history repeated on worldwide scale
- **Loose regulation and high leverage** led to near-collapse of entire
financial system in 2008
- As part of overall meltdown, hedge fund assets fell from $2 trillion to
$1.4 trillion from losses and withdrawal of capital
- Hedge funds now a mature asset class
- Thorp predicted to *The Wall Street Journal* that any edge for investors
would gradually disappear

### The Superrich Bounce Back

- Meanwhile, the superrich, buttressed with government bailout billions,
bounced back from Great Recession
- By 2012 they were richer than ever

## Chapter 23: How Rich Is Rich?

### Defining Wealth

- Financial entrepreneur in London told Thorp his exact number: **$20
million** to retire and live comfortably
- According to Thorp's calculations, each year can withdraw equivalent of
2% of amount, or $400,000 in today's dollars, with only small probability
of using up fortune
- In early forties, married with three small children, this sounded good
to entrepreneur, but everyone has different number

### Historical Wealth Classifications

- **John D. MacDonald** (*Travis McGee* series, 1970) via economist
co-hero Meyer:
  - $100,000 = "adequate"
  - $250,000 = "comfortable"
  - $1,000,000 = "substantial"
  - $5,000,000 = "impressive"
- Since inflation cut real buying power, MacDonald's 2015 equivalent
numbers would be **six times as large**:
  - $600,000 = adequate
  - $1,500,000 = comfortable
  - $6,000,000 = substantial
  - $30,000,000 = impressive

### Dinesh D'Souza's Classification (Inflation-Adjusted)

**Table 3: Classifications of Wealth**
- **Superrich**: $15 million+ income, $150 million+ wealth
- **Rich**: $1.5–15 million income, $15–150 million wealth
- **Upper-middle**: $112,000–1.5 million income, $750,000–15 million
wealth
- **Middle**: $50,000–112,000 income, $82,000–750,000 wealth
- **Lower-middle**: $22,000–50,000 income, $15,000–82,000 wealth
- **Poor**: $0–22,000 income, $0–15,000 wealth

### US Wealth Distribution (2014)

- US household wealth estimated at **$83 trillion** end of 2014
- Mainly stocks, bonds, real estate, personal property
- If divided equally with 320 million people participating: each would
have about **$270,000**
- Such estimates of national wealth and distribution are problematic —
depends on what's counted and how

### Growing Inequality

- National wealth has become more unevenly distributed
- **Median wealth** of US household fell 36% (after inflation) from 2003
to 2013: $88,000 to $56,000
- Household at **97.5 percentile** was 12% better off: $1.19 million to
$1.33 million
- A million dollars still sounds like real money, even though doesn't buy
nearly what it once did
- Would take **$20 million today** to match buying power of $1 million a
century ago

### Counting Millionaire Households

- How many in US have net worth of $1 million? No one knows exactly
- Comprehensive information on personal wealth difficult to collect
- Much not available, not reported, or deliberately hidden
- About **125 million households** total; most have single economically
dominant individual
- Number of households worth at least $1 million thought to be about **ten
million in 2015**
- Goal of becoming one of them looks within reach

### The Path to Millionaire Status

- Example: eighteen-year-old blue-collar worker with no savings, no
prospects
- Save **$6 a day** and buy shares in **Vanguard S&P 500 Index Fund** at
end of each month
- If investment grows in tax-deferred retirement plan at long-term average
for large stocks (~10% per year)
- After **forty-seven years** can retire at age sixty-five with **$2.4
million**
- Finding extra $6/day examples:
  - Pack-and-a-half-a-day smoker who kicks habit saves $6/day
  - Construction worker who drinks two $5 six-packs of beer or Coke daily,
  switches to tap water: saves $10/day ($6 to index fund, $4 to healthy
  food)

### Budget Recommendations

- Article "Budget Basics: 25 Things You Can Do to Trim Yours Today":
  - #1: Write down everything you spend — waste in daily spending becomes
  apparent
  - #2: Pay off credit card debt ASAP
  - #4: Stop smoking (number three suggests buying used car rather than
  new — "car is worth about ⅓ less the minute you drive it off the lot")
- Suppose settle for $10,000 used car rather than $20,000 new car
- Invested at hypothetical 8% after-tax annual return, $10,000 difference
grows to over **$100,000 in thirty years**

> "Who wants to be a millionaire?" — Regis Philbin

### The Multimillionaire Class

- Investors Thorp dealt with typically not just millionaires but
**multimillionaires** with fortunes of $5 million and up
- How many households have reached these rarefied heights?
- **Vilfredo Pareto** studied distribution of income in Italy in 1897,
came up with **"power law"** formula
- Formula describes fairly well how many top wealth holders in modern
society have reached various levels
- To calibrate formula, need two facts:
  - **Forbes 400** cutoff for US: $1.55 billion in 2014
  - Total wealth of those four hundred: $2.3 trillion

**Table 4: Estimated Numbers of Wealthiest Households, US, 2014**
- $1 million: 9,300,000
- $5 million: 1,030,000
- $10 million: 400,000
- $20 million: 155,000
- $50 million: 44,000
- $100 million: 17,000
- $250 million: 4,900
- $500 million: 1,900
- $1 billion: 730
- $1.55 billion (Forbes 400 cutoff): 400

- Formula good fit only for high wealth levels, gives numbers too large
below ~$1 million

### Regional Variations

- Numbers vary widely by region
- **Orange County, California** (where Thorp lives): just over 3 million
people in 2014 (1% of total US population)
- Simple calculation: move decimal point two steps left — forty-nine
people worth quarter billion dollars or more
- But distribution varies widely: areas like Redmond WA (Microsoft),
Silicon Valley CA, Manhattan NY have far more than their share

### The Top of the Ladder

- With 125 million American households, politically controversial **1%** =
wealthiest 1,250,000
- Cutoff around **$4 million**
- However, it's the **top 0.01%** (mere 12,500) that run our society
- Members of this group worth at least **$125 million**

### Bill Gates

- **William F. (Bill) Gates**: co-founder and largest shareholder of
**Microsoft Corporation (MSFT)**
- Fortune at one point made him first human ever to achieve net worth of
more than **$100 billion**
- Amount exceeded 1% of entire gross national product of United States
- Even after giving large part to his charitable foundation, once again
led 2014 *Forbes* list of richest people in US at **$81 billion**

### Estimating Your Net Worth

- To see where you stand on ladder of wealth, estimate your or your
household's **net worth**
- List value of assets (what you own) and debts/liabilities (what you owe)
- Difference is your net worth
- Quick start advice: don't do research, don't consult records
- When uncertain, guess: put in low value for what you own, high value for
what you owe
- Leads to conservative value for what you're worth

**Table 5: Example household at threshold of top 1%** (composite of several
wealthy people Thorp knows):
- Total assets: $5,015,000
- Total liabilities: $829,000
- **Net worth: $4,186,000**

## Chapter 24: Compound Growth — The Eighth Wonder of the World

### The Power of Compound Interest

- **Compound interest** described as **"the eighth wonder of the world"**
(phrase of disputed origin)
- Wonder or trick, it has built great fortunes, and you can use it to get
richer

### Anne Scheiber's Story

- **Anne Scheiber**: fifty-one-year-old IRS estate auditor left
organization in 1944 after twenty-three years of distinguished service by
never promoting her
- Invested savings of **$5,000** in stock market
- Living frugally and studying companies, continually reinvested dividends
- Portfolio continued to grow until she died in 1995 at age 101
- When lawyer **Ben Clark** met with Yeshiva University officials about
her bequest, they had never heard of Anne Scheiber and wondered how to
avoid wasting time
- When meeting finally held: Ms. Scheiber was leaving them **$22 million**
for benefit of women students

### Comparing Investment Returns

- Were Anne Scheiber's choices unusually lucky?
- Period from start of 1944 until end of 1997 (allowing couple years for
estate settlement and delivery of securities to Yeshiva)
- $5,000 invested in large stock index grew to mere $3.76 million
- Same amount invested in small stocks grew, on average, to **$12.31
million**
- Starting with little more than Anne, investing $8,936 instead of $5,000,
average small stock investor would have achieved her $22 million result

### Sam Scared vs. Charlie Compounder

- **Compound growth**: process Anne Scheiber used, accumulating wealth by
reinvesting gains
- Think about compound growth in terms of doubling and redoubling
- **Sam Scared** vs. **Charlie Compounder**: two investors start with $1
- Sam: each time it doubles, puts $1 profit in sock instead of reinvesting
- After ten doublings: Sam has profit in sock of $1 × 10 plus original $1
= $11
- Charlie: lets profit ride — $1 becomes $2, $4, $8, etc.
- After ten doublings: Charlie has **$1,024**
- Sam's wealth grows as $1, $2, $3…$11 (**simple growth**, **arithmetic
growth**, **growth by addition**)
- Charlie's increases as $1, $2, $4…$1,024 (**compound**,
**exponential**, **geometric**, **multiplicative growth**)

### The Power of Small Rates Over Time

- Over sufficiently long time, compound growth at small rate will vastly
exceed any rate of arithmetic growth, no matter how large
- Example: Sam Scared made 100% per year and put it in sock; Charlie
Compounder made only 1% per year but reinvested
- Charlie's wealth would eventually exceed Sam's by as much as you please
- True even if Sam started with far more than Charlie ($1 billion to
Charlie's $1)
- **Robert Malthus** (1766–1834): believing population grew geometrically
and resources grew arithmetically, forecast increasingly great misery

### Preventing Perpetuities

- Politicians dimly aware of awesome power of compound growth
- In many jurisdictions, passed laws against **perpetuities** to prevent
enormous concentrations of wealth from compounding without limit
- Other states and counties welcome perpetual trusts, being more interested
in deriving revenue from them now

### Population Growth

- World population increased from 2.5 billion (1930) to 7.3 billion (2015)
- Growth rate of about 1% per year
- Expected to reach 9.7 billion by 2050
- Everyone knows this can't keep up — **carrying capacity of the earth**
limited by available solar energy for food and scarce resources
- Estimated as up to one hundred billion people
- What if we could keep growing at 1% per century? Calculation shows in
1.2 million years would be solid sphere of flesh with radius almost as
large as our galaxy, expanding at speed of light

### How Fast Do Investments Grow?

- Best simple long-term choice: broad common-stock index fund
- At average past growth rate of ~10% per year, investment doubles in
about **7.3 years**
- Historically, inflation offset about 3% of this, stretching to little
over decade the average time required to double real buying power
- Taxable investors in index fund pay government another percent or so
annually, delaying doubling time to about twelve years

### The Rule of 72

- **"The rule of 72"**: handy trick for quick approximate answers to
compound interest problems
- If money grows at percentage R in each period, with all gains
reinvested, it will double in **72/R periods**
- Example: money grows at 8% per year, reinvest gains — how long to
double? 72 ÷ 8 = **9 years**
- Example: net after-tax return from market-neutral hedge fund averages
12% per year, start with $1 million, reinvest net profits — how much in
twenty-four years?
  - Money doubles in about six years by rule of 72
  - Doubles again in next six years, and so forth, for 24 ÷ 6 = 4
  doublings
  - Multiplies by 2 × 2 × 2 × 2 = 16, becomes **$16 million**

### Exposing Outrageous Claims

- Rule of 72 can expose outrageous claims
- Thorp's personal trainer went to stock market seminar where operators
pitched **"rolling stocks"** method
- Selecting common stocks that would supposedly oscillate between two
levels, advised repeatedly buy low and sell high
- Operators claimed suckers could make **22% per month**
- Why would they share their secret when, putting $2,000 in tax-deferred
IRA and reinvesting gains, they would have more than **$46 trillion in ten
years**?

<!-- pp. 281-300 -->

## Meeting Bill Sharpe and the Efficient Market Debate

### Bill Sharpe's Principle

- Met **Bill Sharpe** at UCI in 1968-69, both young professors
- Sharpe completed work that later won him the **Nobel Prize in 1990**
- Sharpe contributed the **binary model** for options, key simplification for understanding
- Thorp argued markets have inefficiencies (opportunities for abnormal returns)
- **Sharpe's counterargument**: PNP's rewards didn't demonstrate market inefficiency—just payment according to worth
- Sharpe's Principle: Combined holdings of all active investors replicates the index
- Before costs, passive investors get the same return as the index
- Active investors as a group also match the index before costs, but have more risk
- Individual active investor returns are statistically distributed around the index

### The Cost Disadvantage of Active Management

- **Index funds trade infrequently**: stocks turn over just a few percent per year
- **Active investors trade over 100 percent** of portfolio annually
- Trading costs include commissions and **market impact**
- Market impact example: stock with "true" price of $50, pays $50.10 via market order (10-cent impact)
- Large orders can clean out multiple price levels, increasing average purchase price
- At **Ridgeline Partners**, reduced costs by dividing orders into $20,000-$100,000 chunks with wait periods
- Active investors pay ~1% extra in trading costs plus 1% for "helpers" (**Warren Buffett's term**)
- Active investors trail index by ~2% before considering taxes
- No-load, low-expense index funds can charge <0.25% in total fees

### Tax Impact on Active Investing

- High portfolio turnover creates **short-term capital gains** (taxed higher than long-term)
- **Table 6 comparison**: 8% investment, paying 35% tax annually vs. 20% tax annually vs. 20% tax at end
- After 30 years: $4,576 (35% annually) vs. $6,431 (20% annually) vs. $8,250 (20% at end)
- Private equity and hedge fund managers lobbied Congress for **carried interest** tax benefits
- Defer taxes on overseas income for years, then pay at long-term capital gains rates (not ordinary income)

> "Before costs, each passive investor gets the same return as the index."

### Why the S&P 500 Beats Most Mutual Funds

- S&P 500 isn't the whole market—it's an active investor (doesn't include most small companies)
- S&P 500 = ~75% of market value, omits very large companies (pre-2010 **Berkshire Hathaway**)
- Small companies returned 12.45% annually 1926-2007 vs. 10.36% for large companies
- Mutual funds have fluctuating **cash balances** (drag when market rises, cushion when down)
- Academic studies show little evidence of superior managerial skill
- **Morningstar 2009 study**: only 37% of funds beat benchmark over 3 years (similar for 5 and 10 years)

### Table 7: Passive vs. Active Returns

- Before costs: 10.1% (both)
- After costs: Passives 9.7%, Actives 7.7%
- After inflation: Passives 6.7%, Actives 4.7%
- After taxes: Passives 4.8%, Actives 2.0%
- **Passive investors earn more than double** after-tax returns

### Index Fund Selection Advice

- Select funds with annual expenses <0.2%
- Reject funds with management fees, sales loads, other charges
- Each October, US equity mutual funds assign year-to-date gains/losses to current investors
- Inequity: buying before this date = paying taxes on others' gains
- **Tax-exempt investors** (IRAs, 401(k)s, foundations) should consider swapping to broad no-load index
- Superior stock-picking ability is rare—almost everyone should switch
- Taxable investors: review case-by-case (e.g., Berkshire Hathaway Class A with huge unrealized gains)

### Buy-and-Hold Alternative to Indexing

- Buy-and-hold investors who don't trade avoid expenses of active investors
- Can have even lower costs than indexers
- Random stock selection proportional to market cap yields same expected return as index minus small costs
- Main disadvantage: added risk (like buying index then repeatedly flipping a coin)
- 20-30 stocks spread across industries keeps extra risk small
- Threat: investor himself (following stories/advice leads to active trading)
- **Buffett quote**: "Only swing at the fat pitches"

### Thought Experiment: Index vs. Best Managers

- Suppose same percentage of each US stock in low-cost index fund
- Rest in giant pool managed by world's best managers
- Clerk with computer managing index would beat the experts by amount of their extra costs
- Random portfolios selected by chance devices (darts, dice, chimpanzees) hold their own

## Chapter 26: Can You Beat the Market? Should You Try?

### The Efficient Market Hypothesis (EMH)

- Blackjack skeptics said winning systems were impossible
- Stock market skeptics developed **efficient market hypothesis (EMH)**
- Financial market data showed tomorrow's prices look like random fluctuations around today's prices
- If price changes were predictable, someone would trade until no longer true

### The $100 Bill Story

- **Eugene Fama** (father of EMH) walking across University of Chicago campus with student
- Student: "Look, there is a $100 bill on the ground"
- Fama: "No, there isn't. If there were, someone would have picked it up already"
- Blackjack cards also seem random unless you "track the shuffle" or count cards

### EMH Believers' Position

- Securities markets in advanced developed countries respond quickly and almost completely to new information
- Believers originally held most investors were rational and well informed
- Reluctantly yielded to overwhelming evidence to contrary
- Still say collective impact of investors keeps prices close to best estimate of value
- Since 1960s, academics defended EMH, churning out tens of thousands of articles and PhDs

### The Classic View of Stock Pricing

- Stock price derived from value of all future earnings (uncertain, subject to unknowable factors)
- Example: impact of 9/11 on firms in Twin Towers
- Future payoffs discounted to present value reflecting probabilities and risks
- Only investors with **material private information** have an edge
- 1980s prosecution of insider trading illustrates this

### Disproving EMH with Examples

- EMH is a theory that can never be logically proved
- Can be disproven by providing examples where it fails
- Thorp's examples: gambling, Princeton Newport Partners, Ridgeline, hedge funds, **Warren Buffett**, **Berkshire Hathaway**
- Doing better than market ≠ beating it (first is often luck, second is finding statistically significant edge)

### Closed-End Funds: A Market Inefficiency

- PNP exploited large discounts to liquidation value in 1980s
- **Closed-end funds**: sell shares once at launch, then invest in stated category (high-tech, Korean, junk bonds, etc.)
- Example: "Pot of Gold" (POG) fund during precious metals boom
- Investors buy 10 million shares at $10, proceeds = $100M less 8% = $92M net
- Each share represents $9.20 worth of stock (**net asset value** or NAV)
- Wall Street promoters captured 8% immediately
- Shares trade at **premium to NAV** or **discount to NAV**
- **NAV = liquidation value**, but management controls fund (worth substantially less to shareholders)
- Management collects fees and expenses, reducing benefits vs. owning portfolio directly

### Exploiting Closed-End Fund Discounts

- Typical discounts: 15% if management takes 15% of future earnings
- Seen discounts of 50% and premiums of 80%
- Strategy: buy funds at deep discounts, sell short funds at high premiums
- Long and short positions hedge each other, futures/options provide additional risk-offsetting
- Returns fairly steady but "workout" periods can be long (premiums/discounts diminish slowly)
- Invested in intelligently managed hedge fund using this approach
- Annualized return: 10% instead of hoped-for 15% due to slow mispricing corrections

### Forcing Open-End Conversion

- If POG trading at 40% discount ($6/share, NAV $10):
- Buy enough shares to force vote converting to open-end mutual fund
- Shareholders redeem at NAV: pay $6, cash out at $10 = $4 profit (67%)
- PNP succeeded in such deals despite fierce opposition from entrenched management

### SPACs During 2008-09 Crisis

- **Special purpose acquisition corporations (SPACs)**: promised to invest in specified start-up type
- Dismal record by crash time (78% losing on average)
- Typical SPAC: agree to invest within 2 years, or investors get money back plus interest
- December 2008: panic drove SPACs holding only US Treasuries to discount to NAV
- Some SPACs bought holding Treasuries at **annualized returns of 10-12%**, cashing out in months
- Short-term Treasury rates near zero at the time

> "For those who still believe that the market always prices securities properly, here's a profit opportunity that arose because investors couldn't even do arithmetic."

### The 3Com/PalmPilot Mispricing (March 2000)

- **3Com** (ticker COMS) spinning off **PalmPilot** division as separate company
- 6% of PalmPilot (ticker PALM) offered in IPO at $38/share (March 2, 2000)
- Price peaked at $165 before closing at $95
- 23 million shares issued, traded 37.9 million shares in one day (1.5x turnover)
- Thursday closing: PalmPilot valued at $53.4 billion
- 3Com still owned 94% of PalmPilot (at "only" $28 billion)
- Market valued 94% of PalmPilot at $50 billion, **implying rest of 3Com at negative $22 billion**
- Analysts estimated rest of 3Com at $5-8.5 billion
- Within 6 months, 3Com intended to distribute PalmPilot shares to shareholders

### Arbitrage Opportunity: COMS vs. PALM

- Thorp's son **Jeff** called to mobilize capital
- Buy 100 shares COMS at $90 ($9,000), wait for distribution of 1.35 shares PALM per share COMS
- Total: 135 PALM shares + remaining 3Com stub (profitable business, $8 cash/share)
- **Jeff's estimate**: stock value $15-25 after spin-off
- Conservative assumption: 135 PALM shares distributed per 100 COMS (vs. "street" estimate of 150)
- Could buy PALM directly in IPO or at higher aftermarket prices
- Could buy PALM indirectly via COMS and wait 6 months for 1.35 shares PALM

### The Hedge Strategy

- Borrow and sell short 135 PALM at $110 = $14,850 proceeds (held in escrow)
- Buy 100 COMS at $90 = $9,000 cost
- Nearly riskless hedge for almost sure profit
- Six months later: get 135 PALM from 100 COMS, deliver to clear short position
- $14,850 short-sale proceeds released, leaving net profit of $5,850 plus 100 shares of 3Com stub
- If stub priced at $15/share, could sell for additional $1,500
- **Total gain: $7,350 on $9,000 investment in 6 months = 82% return**
- Limited by broker's willingness to lend PALM shares for shorting

### Market Inefficiency Evidence

- **Wall Street Journal** noted arbitrageurs could have corrected disparity if enough PALM shares available
- EMH advocate explained: not enough PALM available to sell short
- **True but insufficient**: buyers of PALM could correct mispricing themselves
- Simply sell PALM and reinvest proceeds in 3Com = increase PALM holdings at no cost
- **New York Times** front-page story next day had little immediate impact
- **Investors couldn't do arithmetic** and apparently didn't know anyone who could
- Similar mispricing: **IXnet** spun off from IPC Communications (mid-February)
- IPC owned 73% of IXnet, valued by market at less than half of IXnet alone

### Perfect Efficient Market Requirements

1. All information instantly available to many participants
2. Many participants financially rational (always prefer more money to less)
3. Many participants able to instantly evaluate all available information and determine fair price
4. New information causes prices to immediately jump to new fair price

**Note**: Supporters realize conditions are unrealistic but claim they hold well enough as approximation

### Real Markets: How They Actually Work

1. **Information spreads in stages**: minority listening at right time/place capture gains first; others get nothing or lose
2. **Limited rationality**: varies from almost totally irrational to striving for financial rationality
3. **Partial information**: participants typically have only some relevant information; processing time and analysis ability vary widely
4. **Delayed price adjustment**: sometimes flood within seconds, more often spread over minutes, hours, days, or months

### How to Beat the Market

1. **Get good information early** (if not sure it's good/early enough, it probably isn't)
2. **Be a disciplined rational investor**: follow logic and analysis, not sales pitches/whims/emotion; assume edge only when rational affirmative case withstands attempts to tear it down; don't gamble unless highly confident
3. **Find superior method of analysis**: statistical arbitrage, convertible hedging, Black-Scholes formula, card counting, security analysis by gifted few, better hedge fund methods
4. **Invest ahead of the crowd**: when securities known to be mispriced, trading eliminates mispricing; earliest traders gain most

> "Only swing at the fat pitches." — Warren Buffett

### Circle of Competence

- Focus on investments within your knowledge and ability to evaluate
- Be sure information is current, accurate, essentially complete
- Information flows down a "food chain" (those who get it first "eating," latecomers "eaten")
- Don't bet unless you can demonstrate by logic and track record that you have an edge

### Market Efficiency Depends on Observer's Knowledge

- Most participants have no demonstrable advantage
- For them, market appears completely efficient (like random blackjack/roulette)
- To beat market: focus on "circle of competence"
- Whether or not you try to beat the market, do better by properly managing wealth

<!-- pp. 301-320 -->

## Investment Advice for Individual Investors (continued)

### Stock Valuation Framework

- Determine a "buy" price through fundamental analysis (financial statements,
management, business model, prospects)
- Identify the price at which expected return becomes substandard
(likely overpriced)
- Range between buy price and overpriced level narrows for experienced
investors, allowing more opportunities
- Example: Stock worth buying at $40 might be overpriced at $80

### International Diversification

- US stock market = 1/3 of world total (as of 2014)
- Traditional pitch: international diversification reduces risk for given return
- Results mixed: excellent 1970–86, mediocre 1987–2015
- **Recent limitation**: Globalization + technology means world markets now
move more in tandem with US, reducing diversification benefit
- Crisis periods show markets falling together, limiting protective value

### Home Ownership as Investment

- **Robert Shiller's data**: US home prices increased ~0.4% annually after
inflation (1890–2004), 0.7% in 1940–2004
- Conclusion: Profit should NOT be primary reason for owning home
- Can rent and do as well financially
- Benefits of ownership: autonomy, control, fixed future costs
- Uncle's example (Torrance, CA): $12,000 purchase (1952) → $480,000 sale
(2006) = 40x in 54 years, ~7% compound annual return
- His property taxes + maintenance < rental costs

### Tax-Loss Selling

- Sell losing stocks before year-end to realize losses that reduce income taxes
- Creates **January effect**: December selling pressure depresses loser stocks,
followed by rebound/excessive performance in January
- Greater impact on smaller companies
- **Wash sale rule**: Cannot sell at loss and buy back within 31 days to
recognize loss for tax purposes
- Rule worded to prevent swapping into "equivalent" stock

### Tax-Gain Deferral

- Opposite strategy: Wait until after year-end to sell security with large gain
- Defers tax by one year, money available for additional year
- Long-term capital gains (>1 year holding) taxed substantially less than
short-term
- Short-term losses offset short-term gains first in tax calculation
- Often more valuable than long-term losses
- Better to sell losers before owning one year

### Princeton Newport Partners Tax Management

- PNP reduced/deferred much of partners' taxable gains when tax laws were
different
- Interesting possibilities still exist today

### Index Arbitrage and Tax-Loss Harvesting

- Buy basket of 20-30 stocks tracking an index instead of index fund
- Small baskets can track index (Dow Jones tracks S&P 500 despite different
methods)
- **PNP technique (mid-1980s)**: Find baskets that track index particularly well
- Used profitably after **Black Monday** (October 19, 1987) to capture >10%
spread between S&P 500 Index and futures
- Quants have refined this into fine art, keeping price discrepancy very small

### Tax Harvesting Strategy

- Start with tracking basket
- When stock drops 10%, sell loser and reinvest in another stock/stocks in new
basket that continues tracking
- If want only short-term losses (best): sell within year of purchase
- Simulate with historical databases before implementing seriously

### Liquidity Considerations

- **Liquidity**: How easy to sell an investment later
- Lack of liquidity in hedge funds and real estate proved costly in 2008–09
recession

### Post-2002 Hedge Fund Changes

- After closing **Ridgeline Partners** (2002), Thorp watched deficits expand,
housing/equity prices soar
- Hedge funds changed terms to lock up investors
- Withdrawal dates: monthly → quarterly → annually → worse
- Notice periods extended: 30 days → 45, 60, 90+ days
- **Throttles**: Limits on withdrawal amounts on any date
- **SEC requirement**: Hedge funds >$100M must become registered investment
advisers, lock up initial investments ≥2 years
- Many funds avoided registration, tying up investors' money (win-win for
funds, disadvantage for investors SEC meant to protect)

### 2008 Financial Crisis Impact

- Spring 2008: Thorp issued partial withdrawal notices to hedge funds he was
invested in
- Once fairly liquid, now no longer so
- Crisis intensified September 2008 before most withdrawals paid
- Fund values declined significantly
- Many funds faced crisis with imprudently leveraged assets
- Failure to anticipate financial collapse = sharp repositioning losses
- **2008 performance**: Hedge funds -18%, large stocks -37%, equity REITs -40%
- New generation of managers either didn't know how to hedge or didn't think
it worth the cost

### University Endowments Hit Harder

- **Harvard, Yale, Stanford, Princeton** with substantial hedge fund investments
had less flexibility
- Favored illiquid alternatives: private equity, commodities, real estate
- After years of high-teen returns, gave back much accumulated edge
- Mid-20s percentage losses vs 18% for median large endowment
- **Lesson**: Can't exit in time when trouble comes; excess returns from
illiquid investments may be offset by unforeseen future events

### Real Estate Leverage Dangers

- First decade of century introduced millions to leverage dangers
- Industry myth: prices only go up
- Homeowners borrowed 80%, 90%, even 100% to buy
- Millions retained high leverage via refinancing/second mortgages/home equity
loans
- 2006 peak → fall: selling by underwater owners + those who bought more than
they could handle depressed prices further
- **Leverage lesson**: Assume worst imaginable outcome will occur and ask if
you can tolerate it. If no, reduce borrowing.

### Kelly Criterion Origin

- Understanding of leverage use began in casinos with card counting
- More edge → bet more (but how much?)
- Answer: 1956 article by **Bell Labs physicist John L. Kelly**
- Kelly called smartest person at Bell Labs after **Claude Shannon**
- Referenced in **Fortune's Formula** by **William Poundstone**

### Kelly Formula

- For favorable bet paying odds of $A for $1 bet:
- Optimal Kelly bet = (percent of capital) = (your edge) ÷ (the odds, A)
- In blackjack: typical favorable edge 1–5%, odds ~1
- Thorp bet percentage of bankroll slightly less than percent advantage
- **Kelly Criterion applies generally** to any gambling/investing situation where
probabilities known/estimated

### What Kelly Shows

- With increasing likelihood, wealth of Kelly follower exceeds fortune of
competitor using essentially different betting scheme
- Thorp used Kelly's formula to manage bets in baccarat and allocate money
among investments

### Kelly Criterion Features

1. Investor/bettor generally avoids total loss
2. Bigger the edge, larger the bet
3. Smaller the risk, larger the bet
- Not invented by old-line academic economists, generated controversy

### Bill Gross and Kelly

- **Bill Gross**, PIMCO co-founder, learned Kelly Criterion summer 1969 playing
blackjack in Nevada
- Still influenced by it in investment decisions
- Told **Wall Street Journal**: "At PIMCO, doesn't matter $200 or $1 trillion.
See it throughout portfolio. Don't have >2% in any one credit. Professional
blackjack played from standpoint of risk management, big part of success."

### Kelly Caveats

1. May lead to wide wealth swings; most choose lesser fraction (typically
half-Kelly or less)
2. For short time horizons or risk-averse investors, other approaches may be
better
3. Exact Kelly requires exact payoff probabilities (like casino games)
- Investment world generally uncertain; Kelly bet should use conservative
estimate

### Warren Buffett and Kelly

- Article in **Wilmott** magazine: Buffett's thinking consistent with Kelly
Criterion
- Q&A at **Emory University**: Asked about **Fortune's Formula** and Kelly
Criterion
- With **Charlie Munger**, managing $200M, put most into just 5-6 positions
- Sometimes willing to bet 75% of fortune on single investment
- Investing heavily in extremely favorable situations = characteristic of
Kelly bettor

## Life Cycle Investing

### Accumulation Phase

- Prior to adulthood: consume more than produce
- Education/training period: contribute more to society than it takes to
support
- Prudent/fortunate investor accumulates wealth to draw upon later as income
reduces

### Retirement Spending Calculations

- Question: Supporting entirely from savings, how much can you spend yearly
without running short?
- No single answer due to individual differences

### Conservative Retiree Example

- Retiree with $10M
- Believes if investments keep up with inflation, can spend $400K/year for 25
years before running out
- "Most conservative" approach: Invest in short-term US Treasury bonds (little
risk, keep up with inflation)
- Divide wealth by greatest number of years may live = yearly spending amount

### Endowment Model for Perpetual Payouts

- For payouts to continue "forever" (endowments)
- Computer simulations: With best long-term investments (stocks, commercial
real estate), annual future spending limited to inflation-adjusted 2% of
original gift
- Assumes future results similar in risk/return to US historical experience
- Chance endowment never exhausted = 96%

### Why 2% Limit is Low

- If fund sharply reduced early by severe market decline, higher spending
might wipe it out

<!-- pp. 321-340 -->

### CMO Pricing Problems and Prepayment Risk

- **CMO pricing complexity**: Forecasting mortgage prepayment rates was critical
  but highly unpredictable
- **Term structure of interest rates**: CMO pricing depends on both default rate
  and how rapidly mortgages are paid off
- **Prepayment behavior**: When Fed lowers long-term rates, homeowners refinance
  and pay off mortgages early; when rates rise, they hold existing loans
- Thorp noticed this unpredictability in the 1980s—prepayment rates were
  volatile and model-dependent

### The CMO Credit Machine

- Wall Street used CMOs with flawed models to flood housing market with credit
- **Recycling mechanism**: Mortgage companies refinanced homes → sold to banks/
  Wall Street → pooled into CMOs → sold to investors → cash recycled into new
  mortgages
- "Everybody got rich"—fees extracted at every step (origination, issuance,
  servicing)
- **Financial alchemy**: CMOs divided into **tranches** (French for "slices")—
  hierarchy where senior tranches paid first, junior got leftovers
- **Rating agency complicity**: Agencies paid by issuers, erred toward optimism
  —higher ratings meant CMOs sold for more than they were worth
- "The sum of the parts sold for more than the cost of the whole"—political
  contributions from real estate and securities industries flowed freely

### Academic Enablers

- **Paul Krugman** (Nobel Prize winner): Macroeconomists assured us catastrophic
  failures could no longer occur due to "greater understanding"
- **Scott Patterson** details in *The Quants*: Quants with academic financial
  theory calculations assured everyone model prices were accurate and risks small
- Hundreds of billions in CMOs sold worldwide

### From CMOs to CDOs and Credit Default Swaps

- **CDOs** (collateralized debt obligations): Expanded concept to other debt
  (auto loans, credit cards)—even riskier than CMOs
- **CDS** (credit default swap): Insurance policy a lender buys to protect
  against borrower default
- Typically purchased for fixed annual payment over certain years (e.g., $1,600/
  year or 0.5% of $320,000 loan for 5-year protection)
- Trillions issued and traded like securities—buyers/sellers didn't need to own
  underlying debt
- **Core problem**: CDS issuers could issue with "no collateral other than their
  full faith and credit"—if bets lost, might not have money to pay
- Margin generally small to zero; unregulated, often held by subsidiaries hidden
  from parent company financial statements

### AIG Collapse

- **AIG** (American International Group): Huge worldwide insurance company,
  largest single recipient of 2008 bailout at $165 billion
- Issued trillions in CDSs through subsidiary backed mainly by their name
- As bonds insured dropped in price, had to post collateral to back losing CDSs
- Eventually couldn't pay, threatening hundreds of billions in bank/investment
  house losses worldwide
- **Taxpayer rescue**: US bailout helped **Goldman Sachs** (held $10 billion of
  AIG's bad assets absorbed by taxpayers) and distributed largesse worldwide to
  cover AIG's defaults

### Joe Sixpack's CDS Ponzi Scheme

- Hypothetical: Joe sells CDS on friend's $320,000 mortgage for $1,600/year
- "Good for the money"—million-dollar house, no debt
- Unregulated, sells thousand more, income grows to $1.6 million/year
- Insuring total of $320 million backed only by his million-dollar house
- **Hiding in subsidiary**: If done through subsidiary without disclosure, scale
  of operations hidden—"Welcome to AIG"
- **Ponzi-like structure**: CDS should be liability on books; needs reserves for
  future payouts
- If collects income without setting aside reserves, it's a Ponzi scheme like
  **XYZ Corporation** in 1970s (sold call options on precious metals too cheaply,
  called proceeds income, didn't reserve for payouts)
- **How AIG differed**: "How did AIG's CDS operation differ from either Joe's
  scheme or XYZ's?"

### 2004 Leverage Deregulation

- Five major investment banks (Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lynch,
  Bear Stearns, Lehman Brothers) persuaded **SEC** to increase allowable leverage
- Previously: could borrow $11 for every $1 net worth (only $1 out of every $12,
  or 8.33% cushion against disaster)
- **SEC Chairman Christopher Cox** allowed expansion to **33:1 leverage**—rivaling
  Long-Term Capital Management's fatal levels six years earlier
- With $33 assets and $32 liabilities per $1 net worth, decline of just over 3%
  in assets wipes out equity
- Once technically insolvent, creditors demand payment, triggering classic bank
  run (like 1930s)

### 2008 Crisis Aftermath

- Four years after leverage increase, same duration that destroyed LTCM, crisis
  hit
- Three of five investment banks ceased to exist as independent entities
- **Morgan Stanley** and **Goldman Sachs** saved by government intervention plus
  **Warren Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway** (multibillion-dollar purchase of 10%
  preferred stock and warrants for Goldman)
- Both returned to prosperity in 2009, Goldman triumphant
- Partners on track for near-record bonuses: $20-30 billion total

### "Doing God's Work"

- **CEO Lloyd Blankfein** at public appearances: Asked about gigantic bonuses,
  explained firm was "doing God's work"
- **Standard academic argument**: More trading creates efficient capital markets,
  better prices for buyers/sellers, benefits all humankind
- Later revealed: "God's work" included bankers knowingly selling mortgage-based
  junk securities while making massive bets that would pay off if their clients
  were ruined
- "When you compare the pay scale for God's bankers with that for his clerics,
  you must conclude that the work of bankers is indeed divine"

### Bailout Politics and Special Interests

- Politically connected wealthy raided public purse for trillion dollars to save
  "too big to fail" entities
- **Cash for Clunkers**: $4,500 program, spun as environmental benefit but new
  car purchase got only 1-4 mpg more—offset by pollution from manufacturing new
  automobile
- Car dealers cheered as replacement-car sales cleared inventory
- **Unemployment insurance**: Repeatedly extended (good to extent needed) but
  better to employ idle beneficiaries in useful work like **WPA** and **CCC**
  (Civilian Conservation Corps) which built infrastructure in 1930s

### First-Time Homebuyer Tax Credit

- $8,000 "fully refundable" tax credit—could get $8,000 even if never paid a
  penny of tax
- "Deceptive language is typical of politicians"
- Poorly monitored: four-year-old bought a house ("at least it was his first
  time")
- Some lenders accepted tax "refund" as down payment (no additional equity
  required)
- Congress extended to those who hadn't bought in last three years
- **Satirical proposal**: "Dollars for Demolition"—$100,000 fully refundable
  credit to tear down run-down residence and build new one, would reenergize
  construction industry

### Spotting vs. Profiting from Bubbles

- **Asset bubbles**: Easy to spot after well underway (valuations far exceed
  norms, seem to have no economic sense)
- Examples: S&L boom (1980s), tech stock overvaluation (1999-2000), housing
  inflation peak (2006)
- **Profiting is trickier**: Like Ponzi scheme, hard to tell when it will end
- Betting against too early ruins you in short run even if right in long run
- **Keynes**: "The market can remain irrational longer than you can remain
  solvent"

### March 2009 Decision Point

- **S&P 500** had fallen 57% from peak
- Thorp couldn't tell whether to buy stocks or sell what he had
- Either decision might have been disaster: if continued into major worldwide
  depression, buying costly; if bottom, stocks rebounded over 70% in less than
  a year
- **Warren Buffett** told *The Wall Street Journal*'s **Scott Patterson**: At
  one point was "looking into the abyss and considering the possibility that
  everything could go down, even Berkshire Hathaway"
- Only when US government indicated willingness to bail out financial system did
  Buffett realize we were saved

### Preventing Future Crises

- **Limit extreme leverage**: Require sufficient collateral posted by both
  counterparties when they trade
- **Regulated futures exchanges**: Model has worked well for decades, easy to
  regulate (mostly by exchanges themselves), few problems
- Contracts are standardized

### Breaking Up "Too Big to Fail"

- Institutions "too big to fail" with significant systemic risk should be broken
  into pieces small enough to fail without jeopardizing financial system
- **Alan Greenspan** finally admitted: "Too big to fail is too big"
- **Contrarian point**: "This is a catchy sound bite but it misstates the real
  problem"
- Not mere size that creates danger—it's **size of risk to financial system**
  from a failure
- **Paul Krugman** example: Canada's financial system concentrated in big
  institutions but didn't have massive mortgage defaults, collapsing institutions,
  giant bailouts
- **Difference**: Canada had strict mortgage standards and tighter limits on bank
  leverage and risk

### Privatize Profit, Socialize Risk

- Corporate executives speculate with shareholders' assets—get big personal
  rewards when they win
- Even if they lose, often bailed out with public funds by obedient politicians
- "We privatize profit and socialize risk"

### CEO Pay Inequality

- CEOs in 1965 took home 24 times average worker pay
- Four decades later: **ratio was 411 to 1**
- **Top 0.01% share of national income**: Top one-hundredth of 1% (12,500
  households)
  - 1929: captured 10% of national income
  - Great Depression: fell to ~5%
  - Gradually rising again beginning in 1980s
  - Recent years: broke 1929 record of 10% and continues to increase

### Executive Compensation and Company Performance

- Studies before and after 2008-09 recession: Larger percentage of corporate
  profit paid to top five executives → poorer earnings and stock performance
- These superstars tended to drain companies rather than benefit them
- Executives claim "market forces" determine salary
- **Moshe Adler** ("Overthrowing the Overpaid"): **David Ricardo** and **Adam
  Smith** concluded 200+ years ago that earnings determined not by what person
  produces but by **bargaining power**

> "Production is typically carried out by teams…and the contribution of each
> member cannot be separated from that of the rest."

### Corporate Governance Reform

- **Empower shareholders**: They are owners of company and ones looted by
  officers and directors
- Current corporate boards run firms like "third-world fiefdoms"
- Shareholders vote yes or no on board-nominated directors—one yes vote can elect
  in face of million no votes
- Rules deliberately make it difficult/impossible for independent shareholders to
  nominate directors or place issues on ballot
- **Proposal**: Corporations should conduct democratic elections following usual
  American voting rules
- Any block of shareholders holding specified percentage should have unrestricted
  right to nominate directors and put issues on ballot, including replacement of
  board members and top executives

### Dual-Class Share Structures

- Some companies disenfranchise shareholders with two or more share classes with
  different voting power
- Management may own A shares (ten votes each), public owns B shares (one vote
  each)
- "How would you like to live in a country where any 'insider' could cast ten
  votes and any 'outsider' got only one?"
- **Abolish this**: Make it one share, one vote
- Currently institutions holding shares in custody can cast proxy votes for
  shareholders who decline to vote
- These proxies usually perpetuate current management and ratify decisions
- **Change**: Only votes cast directly by shareholder should count; proxy votes
  would not count

### Slow Recovery and Future Risks

- Economy slowly recovered in years following 2008-09 crisis
- Little done to add safeguards to prevent recurrence
- **George Santayana**: "Those who cannot remember the past are condemned to
  repeat it"
- "Though the institutions of society have difficulty learning from history,
  individuals can do so"

## Chapter 30: Thoughts

### Value of Education

- "Education has made all the difference for me"
- **Mathematics**: Taught logical reasoning, understanding numbers, tables,
  charts, calculations as second nature
- **Physics, chemistry, astronomy, biology**: Revealed wonders of the world,
  showed how to build models and theories to describe and predict
- "This paid off for me in both gambling and investing"

### Education as Software for the Brain

- When born: "Think of yourself as a computer with a basic operating system and
  not much else"
- Learning adds programs from drawing a face to riding bicycle to mastering
  calculus
- Much learned from schools and teachers; even more valuable: learned at early
  age to teach myself
- "This paid off later on because there weren't any courses in how to beat
  blackjack, build a computer for roulette, or launch a market-neutral hedge
  fund"

### Probability and Everyday Decisions

- Most people don't understand probability calculations for gambling games or
  everyday life problems
- "We didn't need that skill to survive as a species in the forests and jungles"
- When lion roared, you instinctively climbed nearest tree and thought later
- Today we have time to think, calculate, plan ahead—math can help make decisions

### Cost-Benefit Analysis Examples

- **Seatbelts and airbags**: Upgrade 100 million vehicles at $300 each = $30
  billion total, 5,000 fewer traffic deaths/year
- If vehicles with safety features last 10 years, that's 50,000 lives saved at
  $30 billion cost, or $600,000 per life
- Auto industry disagreed, spent the money and saved the lives

### Smoking as Probabilistic Risk

- Pack-a-day smoker: 40 years makes life on average 7 years shorter
- Each cigarette brings death 12 minutes closer, adds health problems
- Costs: higher medical costs in final years, sick days during working years,
  secondhand smoke damage
- "But these are averages. Some smokers do not die of smoking-related diseases,
  whereas others die at an early age"
- "It's like gambling at roulette. On average you lose 5 cents when you bet $1.
  But this is an average. Some gamblers are wiped out quickly and others may hold
  their own for quite a while"

### Public Policy Trade-offs

- Major issue: trade-off between costs and benefits of certain procedures
- Example: $500,000 to save life of someone with super-drug-resistant
  tuberculosis vs. same amount to save 50 lives by delivering 50,000 flu vaccine
  doses at $10 each to schoolchildren
- Statistical thinking can help with choices like these

### Gambling and Financial Education

- Simple probability and statistics should be taught K-12
- Analyzing games of chance (coin matching, dice, roulette) teaches thinking
  through such issues
- Understanding why casinos usually win might help avoid gambling and limit
  losses to entertainment value
- "Gambling now is largely a socially corrosive tax on ignorance, draining money
  from those who cannot afford the losses"

### Risk, Reward, and Uncertainty in Investing

- "Most of what I've learned from gambling also is true for investing"
- People mostly don't understand risk, reward, uncertainty—investment results
  could be much better if they did
- **Homeowners' association example**: Kept cash reserves in 30-day US Treasury
  bills for absolute safety, spent only about 1/5 each year
- **Thorp's suggestion**: Put 1/5 of reserves into Treasuries maturing in coming
  year, another 1/5 to mature year after, and so forth
- **Laddering strategy**: Generally pays off because longer-term US bonds yield
  more before maturity
- 5-year bonds beaten 30-day T-bills by ~1.8% annually over last 83 years
- Treasurer opposed at first but later agreed and used it profitably

### Basic Finance Education

- Would like to see basic finance taught in elementary and secondary schools
- If more citizens knew how to balance checkbooks, create/understand income
  statements and balance sheets, might choose homes they can afford
- Properly managing investments would better prepare people for retirement, make
  them less dependent on society

### Insights About People and Society

- "One of my great pleasures from the study of investing, finance, and economics
  is the discovery of insights about people and society"
- Physical sciences have rules (law of gravitation) that generally hold true
- Human beings and their interactions aren't covered by broad, unchanging
  theories and may never be
- Instead: "More limited concepts that tie things together and serve as shortcuts
  to understanding"

### Invisible Hand and Its Limits

- **Adam Smith** (1776): In economy of many small buyers/sellers, each trying to
  increase own profit, collective benefit maximized as though guided by
  "invisible hand"
- **Limited use**: Most markets not as Smith assumed
- **Computer chips**: 99.8% worldwide made by just two US companies, smaller one
  fighting to survive

### Tragedy of the Commons

- Opposite concept explained by **Garrett Hardin**
- Natural resource anyone can freely use (e.g., catching fish in ocean)
- 18th century: Schools of cod so vast **Benjamin Franklin** was amazed when ship
  plowed through them for days
- After two centuries of overfishing, population collapsed
- "How has individual self-interest maximized social good?"
- Global scale example: pollution—individual humans freely burned fossil fuels,
  greatly increased greenhouse gases like CO₂
- Temperature rise over last century, lung diseases and deaths from particles
- "Each polluter gains more individually from his own actions than he loses, so
  he has no direct pressure to change"

### Externalities

- "The solution for society illustrates another neat unifying concept, that of
  'externalities'"
- **Externality**: Cost or benefit for society that results from private economic
  activity
- **Negative externality** (air pollution): Estimate damage and tax by that
  amount
- **Positive externality**: If I fireproof my house it protects neighbors, tends
  to reduce local fire service costs and increase insurer profits
- Instead of being taxed, may be rewarded by drop in insurance rates

### Cui Bono and Political Economy

- **Charlie Munger** presents thinking tools in *Poor Charlie's Almanack: The Wit
  and Wisdom of Charles T. Munger*
- Favorite: "Look for the incentives" (closely related to "Cui bono?" or "Who
  gains?")
- Cui bono explains: 7,000 US gun dealers lining Mexico border (Tijuana to Corpus
  Christi) freely provide military-level arms to Mexican drug cartels
- Explains: Congress mandated wasteful corn-based ethanol (causes almost as much
  pollution as it offsets, drives up food prices)
- Until end of 2011: 54-cent-per-gallon tariff kept Brazilian ethanol out

### Politically Connected Rich

- "The politically connected rich are the dominant economic and political power
  in the United States"
- Key concept for understanding what happens in society and why
- They buy politicians using campaign contributions, career opportunities,
  investment profits
- As owners of wealth who also control power, they run the country and will
  continue to do so
- "We saw how they used the government to bail them out of the financial crisis
  of 2008–09"

### Two Types of Rich

- No objection to some people being richer, even much richer, than others
- Objects to gain of wealth through political connections rather than earning by
  merit
- Basketball franchise example: If pays neighbor Kobe Bryant $20 million/year
  because it takes that much to get him, fine
- But if hedge fund managers bribe politicians to cut their tax rate to fraction
  of percentage average worker pays, objects
- **Two types**: Those who use government to tilt playing field in their favor
  (pay taxes well below middle class) vs. those who don't (pay substantially
  higher rates)
- Blended rate of two groups similar to upper middle class rate
- Politically connected rich point to higher rates of nonconnected fellows as
  cover to demand still more tax breaks
- "The power of this group resides mostly in those who are in the upper 0.01
  percent of wealth holders, currently worth $125 million or more"

### Tax Simplification

- **Get government out of micromanaging**: California and many states have own
  income tax code resembling federal but different enough so resident must
  complete detailed state return
- **Solution**: Let state tax for individuals simply be fraction of federal tax,
  set by legislature, chosen to raise same revenue as current tax
- Return would fit on postcard, save hours for citizens, free thousands of
  unproductive state employees for useful work in private sector
- Eliminating 3,000 California employees at $100,000 each (salaries, benefits,
  overhead) would save state $300 million/year plus time and money saved by
  citizens
- Revenue-neutral proposal, net gain for state

### Federal Tax Reform

- Even greater benefits from applying to federal tax code
- Tax rates high because loophole-riddled regulations allow many to pay less or
  nothing
- **Revenue-neutral flat tax**: Could make tax code simple and fair, catch those
  currently getting free ride
- All income taxed equally with exemption at, say, 1.5 times poverty level
- Those below cutoff pay no tax (small part of national income, minor impact)
- Much currently untaxed income would be taxed, estimated revenue-neutral rate
  ~20%
- Benefit to society: Hundreds of thousands of government employees, tax lawyers,
  accountants, tax preparers freed to make (hopefully) productive contribution
- **Value-added tax**: Another proposal that recaptures escaped taxation, cuts
  top tax rate in half

### Political Gridlock

- "Having an idea that benefits society is the first step. The hardest part, more
  often than not, is passing laws to implement it"
- Has become harder as political clash between parties in US has become extreme
- "Politics, once called the art of the possible, is becoming the art of the
  impossible"
- Gridlock between uncompromising factions was one cause of fall of Roman Empire

### US Future: Two Scenarios

- **Long-term investor question**: Whether US will be dominant world power in
  21st century or whether we have peaked
- Dissipating strength in costly foreign wars, financial mismanagement, domestic
  strife
- **Optimistic scenario**: Could lead to another century of equities returning 7%
  /year after inflation
- **Pessimistic scenario**: Could be far less pleasant
- **Reassurance**: Rome wasn't destroyed in a day; nations once among most
  powerful (Britain, France, Italy, Spain, Netherlands, Portugal) still among
  most developed and civilized
- To optimists: Endless deficits, massive wastage of lives/wealth in wars,
  political subsidies (pork, bailouts, corporate welfare, paying able-bodied not
  to work), destructive partisanship in all three branches
- Meanwhile: Rise of China transforming geopolitical and economic landscape

### Education Crisis

- "One of the most ominous and underappreciated threats to our future is in
  education and technology"
- California leader in race to bottom
- Anti-tax movement starved state of revenue, especially educational system
- **University of California**: Once among finest public higher education systems
  worldwide, raised tuition to $12,000/year by 2015
- When Thorp was student in 1949: $70 (like $700 today adjusting for inflation)
- Good education available to any qualified student; graduates led technological
  revolution
- By 2014: State contributed only ~10% of total cost of all campus operations

### Brain Drain

- If UC system doubled tuition and fees, could drop state support altogether and
  go private
- Out-of-state and foreign students charged 3x tuition paid by California
  residents
- Individual deans and administrators raising more money by replacing California
  residents with higher-paying out-of-state/foreign students
- Gifted foreign students (many Chinese) receive advanced degrees in US and
  return home rather than struggle for postdoctoral funding and permission to
  become residents
- Talented American-born scientists and engineers joining them in reverse brain
  drain
- **Economists**: One factor explained nation's future economic growth and
  prosperity more than any other: **output of scientists and engineers**
- "To starve education is to eat our seed corn. No tax today, no technology
  tomorrow"

## Epilogue

### Life Philosophy

> "Freud said that once we have the basic necessities of food, clothing, shelter,
> and health, then what we seek is wealth, power, honor, and the love of men and
> women."

- For financial titans aggressively seeking tens/hundreds of millions/billions:
  "Is the winner really the one who dies with the most toys?"
- "How much is enough? When will you be done? Often the answer is 'Never.'"

### Career Choices

- To preserve quality of life and spend more with valued people and exploring
  ideas, chose not to follow up on profitable business ventures
- Believed they were nearly certain to become extremely profitable
- Once worked out major concepts in a subject and proved them in action, liked
  new mental challenges
- Moved from gambling games to investment world (warrants, options, convertible
  bonds, derivatives) then statistical arbitrage
- Expected to spend life teaching, doing research, talking to smart like-minded
  people
- From childhood intrigued by power of abstract thinking to understand and direct
  natural world
- When saw how physics could predict roulette through fog of chance and
  mathematics could tip odds in blackjack, was drawn into lifetime of adventure

### Vivian's Influence

- Good fortune to share most of journey with remarkable companion
- Wife Vivian loved books, voracious reader
- One year kept journal about books they read: In 12 months she cruised through
  150+ books at 700+ words per minute
- Timed her for an hour without her knowing
- Passed on love of books and extraordinary facility with English language to
  children and grandchildren
- She mastered bridge, studied art and art history, learned to prepare quality
  healthy meals, completed master's degree in library science, inspired family to
  focus on personal fitness and health, supported causes and charities
- One of few people known as "super-recognizers"—could casually recognize people
  she'd met decades before even though transformed by age, style, carriage, shape,
  size
- "When most of us remember the past, the memories fade over time and the 'facts'
  may shift closer to the heart's desire. When it had to do with people, Vivian's
  memory was both extraordinarily accurate and unchanging over time"

### Final Thoughts

- Vivian died from cancer in 2011
- Memorial service, brother said: "Nobody can take away the dance you have
  danced"

> "Life is like reading a novel or running a marathon. It's not so much about
> reaching a goal but rather about the journey itself and the experiences along
> the way."

- **Benjamin Franklin**: "Time is the stuff life is made of, and how you spend it
  makes all the difference"
- "Best of all is the time I have spent with the people in my life that I care
  about—my wife, my family, my friends, and my associates"
- "Whatever you do, enjoy your life and the people who share it with you, and
  leave something good of yourself for the generations to follow"

