## Chapter Notes (Continued)

### Chapter 1 Notes

**a single word** — Thorp's son had the same delayed speech experience, not speaking until about the same age. His sister acted as interpreter, understanding body language and facial expressions to communicate his needs.

**complete sentences** — Reference to Henriette Anne Klauser's *Writing on Both Sides of the Brain* (Harper, 1997), telling of a first grader who wouldn't write despite prompting, then suddenly released a torrent of fluency after seven months.

**Great Flu Pandemic** — The 1918-19 flu pandemic killed more people than World War I itself, more than any other plague in history.

**the US version** — Number naming differences: In US and UK, a million = 1 followed by 6 zeros. US adds three zeros per step (billion = 9 zeros, trillion = 12 zeros). UK traditionally adds six zeros per stage (billion = 12 zeros).

**one standard deviation** — Statistical measure indicating the size of typical fluctuation around an average value.

**to the news** — Reference to Nassim Taleb's *Fooled by Randomness* for insights on randomness and news.

**quick mental estimate** — Using the rule of 72 for doubling time: 24% annual growth doubles money in about 3 years (72/24). The rule underestimates doubling time as rates exceed 8%.

**of the Alamo** — Epic battle story told in Eric Morris's *Corregidor: The American Alamo of World War II* (Stein and Day, 1981, reprinted Cooper Square Press, 2000).

### Chapter 2 Notes

**surgical facilities** — Horrors of Japanese prison camps rendered in Agnes Keith's *Three Came Home: A Woman's Ordeal in a Japanese Prison Camp* (1949, paperback 1985).

**was still running** — Edmund Scientific's *Scientifica 2000 Catalog for Science and Engineering Enthusiasts*, page 31.

**several thousand feet** — Reference to *The Darwin Awards, Evolution in Action* by Wendy Northcutt (Plume, 2002), "Lawnchair Larry" pp. 280-81.

**of these flares** — String soaked in potassium nitrate solution and dried.

**recipe and procedure** — Fifty years later, listening to Ken Follett's novel *The Man From St. Petersburg*, Thorp noted the terrorist-anarchist's nitroglycerin recipe matched his boyhood refrigerator method.

**depth of 5 feet** — Reference: digitalcollections.lmu.edu/cdm/ref/collection/chgface/id/294

**a man's hand** — Biblical reference: 1 Kings 18:44

**dimensional analysis** — Thorp was familiar with Percy W. Bridgeman's *Dimensional Analysis* (Yale University Press, 1922).

**joined the rest** — In 2015, Thorp's granddaughter **Claire Goul** was one of three hundred semifinalists in the Intel Science Talent Search, now more competitive with three top prizes of $150,000 each versus one $10,000 prize in 1949.

### Chapter 3 Notes

**standard American wheel** — European wheels had only one green number. Further improvements like betting red or black only cost half the stake if that number came up.

**systems must fail** — The **Pythagorean theorem** from plane geometry: sum of squares of two sides equals square of hypotenuse. Example: triangle with sides 3, 4, 5 is right triangle (3²+4²=5²). Infinitely many such triangles exist, but impossible to check them all one at a time.

**a rubber ring** — **Richard Feynman** demonstrated that the Challenger's rubber O-ring became brittle in ice water, explaining the launch failure. Story in *Classic Feynman*, edited by Ralph Leighton (Norton, 2006).

**wealthy older student** — T.T. Thornton

**for every frame** — Film viewable at www.edwardothorp.com

### Chapter 4 Notes

**a new strategy** — Baldwin et al (1956)

**and even awe** — For blackjack rules and Thorp's original report, see *Beat The Dealer* (1962, revised edition 1966).

### Chapter 5 Notes

**mathematics course** — Measure theory, foundational to probability and statistics.

**partially played decks** — For a 52-card deck, choosing Aces can be done in 5 ways, selecting 2-9 cards in five ways each, and 0-16 Ten-value cards in seventeen ways. Total: about 5×7×17 = 595 combinations, or just over 33 million different partial decks.

**to a gigantic** — Strategy tables written on dollar-bill-sized paper would occupy 1.08 cubic centimeters each, totaling 27 cubic meters or 1300 cubic feet. Eight decks would fill 6.5 cubic kilometers or 1.6 cubic miles.

**0.21 percent** — The **Baldwin group** later corrected their 0.62% casino edge figure to 0.32% due to arithmetic error.

**the blackjack rules** — Casino rules varied across time and locations. Thorp's calculations used then-current standards.

**(half the deck)** — Chance that last 26 cards contain all four Aces is about 5.5%.

**type from the deck** — Later exact calculations gave slightly more favorable numbers to the player, affected by rule variations. Details in Thorp (1962, 1966), Griffin (1999), Wong (1994).

**$200 bankroll** — Money values changed dramatically over 80+ years. Thorp provides conversion appendix for current dollars.

**my mathematical work** — Discovery involved **functional analysis**, where both Taylor and the mathematician were specialists.

**Shannon at noon** — Meeting on September 29, 1960, memorialized in a letter Thorp wrote that evening to mathematician **Berthold Schweizer**.

**to the academy** — Thorp, Edward O., "A Favorable Strategy for Twenty-One," *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, Vol. 47, No. 1, 1961, pp. 110-12.

**the program booklet** — Thorp (1960). *Fortune's Formula* was also the title of **William Poundstone's** 2005 book covering blackjack, roulette, the stock market, and the **Kelly Criterion**.

***The Boston Globe*** — "Can Beat Blackjack, Says Prof.," by Richard H. Stewart, *Boston Globe*, January 24, 1961, page 1.

**across the country** — Examples: *Columbus Dispatch* (1961), *Las Vegas Sun* (1961), *Miami News* (1961), *New York Herald Tribune* (1961), *New York World Telegram and Sun* (1961), *Washington Post* and *Times Herald* (1961).

### Chapter 6 Notes

**ran his story** — Thomas Wolfe, *Washington Post*, January 25, 1961, page A3.

**offered a strand** — Paul O'Neil (*Life* magazine, 1964) erroneously quoted Thorp about the pearl string: "We had it appraised first thing in the morning. It was worth $16." Neither statement correct; misquote hard to kill even after Thorp's correction to Bruck (1994).

**the everyday gambler** — Schwartz, David G., *Roll the Bones* (Gotham Books, 2006).

**was a characteristic** — Feller (1957), (1968).

**the investment worlds** — **William H. Gross**, greatest bond investor, learned casino lessons in Las Vegas. Motivated by *Beat the Dealer*, he went summer 1966, turning $200 bankroll into $10,000. Reference: *Bill Gross on Investing* (Wiley, 1997, 1998). Later co-managed trillions for **PIMCO**.

**with the house** — Thorp realized later he would have had advantage starting each deal with big bets, maintaining them when count was good, causing dealer to shuffle when it wasn't.

**a serious loss** — Why might bigger bankroll lead to more risk of losing it all? Technical and psychological reasons. Technically, with a $100,000 bankroll they'd make maximum bets even in slightly favorable situations, increasing fluctuation size and requiring longer playing time than Thorp's available time.

> "X and Y didn't have my level of understanding of, and confidence in, the system. If, with a $100,000 bankroll they would in fact quit when we were down say $60,000, then I would be playing and sizing bets as though I had a $100,000 bankroll when, unknown to anyone, I really only had a $60,000 bankroll."

Psychological problem: **Kimmel** insisted playing his "pidgeon" version of the system, betting big, losing back much profit, then refusing to stop.

**afternoon in Boston** — **Ivi**, her mother, and two sisters came to US after World War II as refugees from Estonia.

### Chapter 7 Notes

**great mathematics centers** — Segel, Joel, *Recountings* (A.K. Peters, Wellesley, MA, 2009), tells MIT mathematics history.

**to stay on** — Thorp's family relationship with MIT continued two generations later. Three grandchildren (fraternal triplets) attended MIT. See "Triplets Celebrate After ALL are Accepted to Prestigious MIT...," *London Daily Mail*, Saturday, July 25, 2015.

**building the first one** — MIT Media Lab timeline erroneously gives 1966 for the computer, likely because Thorp first revealed its existence in the 1966 revised edition of *Beat the Dealer*. Correct year: 1961, when completely tested in Las Vegas. Verified in August 1961 correspondence between **Shannon** and Thorp, now in MIT Museum archives. Device itself remains at the museum.

**few early players** — Among them: **Emmanuel Kimmel** (Mr. X of *Beat the Dealer*), **Jesse Marcum** ("little dark haired guy from Southern California"), **Russell Gutting** ("Junior"), **Benjamin F. "System Smitty" Smith**, and **Mr. P.** (possibly Joe Bernstein, the "silver fox" in columnist Herb Caen's book *Don't Call It Frisco*). Marcum seems to have consistently adhered to the method.

**fairly thorough shuffles** — Seven shuffles isn't magic; actual number needed varies by how "random" is specified, shuffle type, and measurement method.

**in private games** — *Danger in the Cards* has been out of print for many years.

**William F. Rickenbacker** — For more on this trip see letters from Thorp and Barnhart in *Blackjack Forum*, Vol. XVII #1 (Spring 1997), pp. 102-104, XX #1 (Spring 2000), pp. 9-30, and XX #2 (Summer 2000), pp. 105-107.

**working for the board** — Rickenbacker wrote about the experience in syndicated column titled "Even 'Honest' Vegas House Cheats."

**bits of publicity** — Example: *Time*, "Games: Beating the Dealer," January 25, 1963, p. 70.

**"It's Bye! Bye! Blackjack" appeared** — Scherman, 1964.

**a nine-page story** — O'Neil, Paul, "The Professor Who Breaks the Bank," *Life*, March 27, 1964, pp. 80-91.

**a heart attack** — In April of 1966.

**thwart these card counters** — Vic Vickery, "Counting on Blackjack," *Las Vegas Style* magazine, May 1993, pp. 61, 67.

**Players Too Smart** — Carson City (UPI): *New York Journal-American*, April 3, 1964.

### Chapter 8 Notes

**High-Low System** — Called the **Complete Point Count** in *Beat the Dealer*.

**pooling their bankrolls** — For optimal risk-return trade-off, bet size in a given situation is proportional to bankroll. When players on a team are unsure about current bankroll size, they should reduce bets slightly.

**Pacific Stock Exchange** — Google's Blackjack Hall of Fame write-ups for more on **Francesco**, **Hyland**, **Uston**, and others.

**the blackjack community** — As blackjack popularity surged, a community evolved. Special newsletters for counters circulated, later replaced by websites. **Stanford Wong's** newsletters and websites provided information on where to play for best advantage. **Arnold Snyder's** quarterly *Blackjack Forum* featured articles from leading players and theorists over twenty years, providing informal history of the war with casinos. **Anthony Curtis's** *Las Vegas Advisor* was a monthly guide to events and best deals. **Gambler's Book Store** (managed by Howard Schwartz) offered latest books and systems. **Richard Reid's** website www.bjmath.com was a treasury of articles, workshops, and discussions. The network accelerated development of new methods for advantageous play.

**The second line** — Later exact calculations changed these numbers somewhat, varying slightly with deck count.

**nearest whole number** — Thirteen was chosen for good fit.

**count was to use** — Card counting system strengths thoroughly discussed in *The Theory of Blackjack* by **Peter Griffin**, 6th Edition (Huntington Press, 1999).

**in the discard tray** — Easy method: estimate how many half decks are left, described in *Professional Blackjack* by **Stanford Wong** (pseud.), Pi Yee Press, 1994.

**the point count** — Dividing ultimate strategy values in table 1 by eight and rounding to nearest whole number gives the values of −1 and +1 that make up the complete point count. Values for sevens and nines are closest to 1 and −1 respectively, making them alternative choices for the system Thorp used in Puerto Rico.

> **"what I've got."** — Quote from Thorp (1966), pp. 84-85.

**1970s, several people** — Notably, **Keith Taft**.

**a powerful advantage** — Thorp explained the idea in "Non-random Shuffling With Applications to the Game of Faro," *Journal of the American Statistical Association*, pp. 842-47, December 1973. Much expanded version appears in *Gambling and Society*, edited by W. Eadington, Charles C. Thomas (Springfield, IL, 1975), as "Probabilities and Strategies for the Game of Faro," pp. 531-60.

**cheating, the statutes** — N.R.S. 465.015.

**success much more difficult** — *Legends of Blackjack* by Kevin Blackwood and Larry Barker (Kindle eBook, April 5, 2009), tells stories of leading professionals.

**the Blackjack Ball** — "The Smartest Guy in the Room," by R.M. Schneiderman, *Newsweek*, February 20, 2012, pp. 56-57.

**in the movie 21** — Inspired by the Ben Mezrich book *Bringing Down the House*.

**rate the games** — **Stanford Wong's** monthly newsletter is thorough.

