## Chapter 13: Black-Scholes Endnotes

### Hedge Fund Industry Origins and Early Performance

- **Arbitrage Management Company** set up in 1967 to exploit hedging
ideas from *Beat the Market*
- Founders included **Harry Markowitz** (later Nobel Prize in
Economics) and **John Shelton** (finance professor, warrant theorist)
- Though profitable, gains weren't enough to keep it running —
disappeared after three years
- Only tenth of what hedge funds would become: grew 100x from 1968 to
2016

### Historical Context: 1968-1970 Hedge Fund Performance

- **Robertson, Wyndham and Haines article** in *Fortune* (Oct 1970):
"The Hedge Funds' Dubious Prospects"
- Report analyzed twenty-eight largest hedge funds as of Dec 31, 1968
- Most performed poorly during 1968-1970 market decline
- Only winner: **Buffett Partnership, Ltd.** — closing after
spectacular twelve-year run because stock prices too high relative to
underlying value
- Other success: **Steinhardt, Fine, Berkowitz & Co.**

### Black-Scholes Formula Development

- **Physics as foundation**: For full account of how 1905 physics would
transform finance, see *Annus Mirabilis: 1905, Albert Einstein and the
Theory of Relativity* by John and Mary Gribban (Penguin, 2005)
- **Paul Cootner's work**: See "The Random Character of Stock Market
Prices" (MIT Press, 1964) on stock price changes as random walks
- **Riskless interest rate assumption**: Academic economists and
theorists long assumed US Treasury bonds and bills are riskless
- Argument: government can print money to pay interest and redeem at
maturity
- **Debt ceiling disputes** expose this fallacy — US can pay debts but
may choose not to if forced to pay higher interest rates
- Congressional battles make the debt larger by increasing borrowing
costs

### Warrant Valuation Methods

- **Thorp's approach**: Plausible reasoning led to correct result
- Articles in *Wilmott* magazine (Sept 2002, Dec 2002, Jan 2003)
available at www.edwardothorp.com
- Introduction to methods: *Mathematics and Plausible Reasoning*
(Vols. I and II) by **George Polya** (Princeton, 1954)
- More elementary: *How to Solve It* (2nd Ed, Doubleday, 1957)
- Background discussion: *Derivatives: Models on Models* by **Haug,
Espen Gaarder** (Wiley, 2007)

### Black-Scholes Formula Validation

- **Beat the Market acknowledgment**: Black and Scholes famous paper
(May-June 1973) acknowledged their formula identical to Thorp's
- "The Pricing of Options and Corporate Liabilities" in *Journal of
Political Economy*, Vol. 81, pp. 637-54
- The fact that formulas were identical verified Thorp's plausible
reasoning approach

### Derivatives Trading and Financial Risk

- **Roger Lowenstein**: *Buffet: The Making of an American Capitalist*
(Random House, 1995, p. 156)
- **Over-the-Counter (OTC) derivatives**: Hundreds of trillions of
dollars' worth now trade
- Banks and brokers love high fees, resist standardizing contracts
- Under-collateralized OTC contracts could precipitate financial
collapse (as seen 2008-09)
- Exchange-traded standardized contracts could eliminate this threat

### Wall Street Journal Coverage

- **September 23, 1974 article**: "Computer Formulas Are One Man's
Secret to Success in Market" by Jonathan R. Laing
- Years later, Thorp heard one trader consulted Black and also used
formula prices when CBOE trading began

### Media Misreporting

- ***Fortune's Formula* error** (page 172): Incorrectly reported Thorp
making as much as **Paul Newman**
- Thorp's story in *Beat the Dealer* (1966 edition, pp. 167ff)

